[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6
{ The Queen's Gambit Declined is the ideal opening for a lifetime repertoire. 'The opening for world championship matches' as described by Kasparov, it has all the required characteristics for an opening to serve for a lifetime: it is safe, solid, reliable and theoretically sound. It is also universal, as the Queen's Gambit Declined set-up can be used against a vast majority of White's attempts. There were two main principles that guided me when creating this repertoire:    1. The universality of the set-up against White's main theoretical lines:the Main Line with 5.Bg5,the Main Line with 5.Bf4 and theCatalan - against all of them I chose the lines with ...Nbd7 and against the last 2 the knight move is often followed by ...c6, ...b6 and the development of the light-squared bishop to b7 or a6. This universality is very important in a lifetime repertoire because the player can rely more on understanding than on memory, especially as times passes and some of the lines fade away.    2. Against all the lines my main priority was to provide variations that solve the problem of the 'bad' bishop on c8. Therefore there are 2 solutions in the whole repertoire: either the QGD set-up followed up with a clear plan how to develop the bishop or a plan where Black doesn't play ...e6 and develops the bishop freely along the h3-c8 diagonal.    What is very important for the Queen's Gambit Declined is that Black can play for a win in a lot of simplified positions. I have given a few examples of this in the chapter with model games and these should serve as a good reminder of what Bobby Fischer used to say about playing with Black: you should first equalize before starting to play for more. Playing the Queen's Gambit Declined is like standing on the shoulders of giants. Played by all the champions of past and present, centuries of theory and practice have determined the best ways for Black and the latest engines only added to the precision, guaranteeing an infallible defence against all White's tries.    I see Lifetime Repertoires as repertoires that do not depend so much on concrete and forcing lines, but rather on understanding the principles behind the opening moves. These repertoires should become second nature to the player as after absorbing the material, he or she can play them with confidence forever. I believe that having the Queen's Gambit Declined as a lifetime repertoire is a wise choice and one that you will always be happy you have made. }
*

