1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. b3 O-O 6. Bb2 b6 7. c4 Bb7 8. e3
{ This is a slower set-up for White. He intends to play Qe2, and then he will have two plans at his disposal: Rd1 followed by taking on d5 and pushing d4 or d3 with the idea of Ne1 @@StartBracket@@or Nh4@@EndBracket@@ and then f4, g4, etc. }
8... c5 { Black expands in the center. } 9. Nc3
{ White's set-up is very flexible, so he can start with other moves as well, though more likely than not they will lead to a transposition. For example, after   9.Qe2  Nbd7  10.Rd1  Qc7  11.Nc3  Rac8  we have a transposition to the line starting with 9. Nc3.   A move like  9.d3  is met with the same set-up of  9...Nbd7  followed by ...Qc7, ...Rac8, and ...Qb8. }
9... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black intends a very harmonious regrouping: the queen will go to c7, the rook from a8 will come to c8 or d8, and then the queen will drop back to b8, thus removing herself from the central files. From b8, the queen controls the e5-square and can also go to a8 to increase Black's control over the long diagonal. }
