[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. Bd3 { This is the most common choice. } 7... cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 and after White takes with the pawn, the bishop on b2 will be rather passive. }
8. exd4 { Taking with knight runs into  8.Nxd4?!  e5 } 8... b6
{ Black develops the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nbd2
{ Note that after  10.Nc3   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ we will have a transposition to the lines after  4.Nc3  Be7  5.e3  By developing the knight on d2, White has the option to play Ne5 and Ndf3. }
10... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. The knight on c6 puts pressure on d4 and can also go to b4 to harass the bishop on d3. Now White needs to decide whether to put the queen on e2 or not. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Catalan 5.Nbd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5. Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5. Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black takes ...dxc4. }
5. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black castles and on the next move he will play ...b6 to develop the light-squared bishop on b7. }
6. Bg2 b6 { The most natural way to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. O-O
Bb7
{ Now White has a wide choice, but Black's general ideas are control of the light squares in the center  (d5 and e4)  and preparing the ...c5-push. }
*

