1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5. Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5. Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black takes ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ... c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ...dxc4 and ... b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. Bf4
{ White activates the bishop, but there are also quite a few alternatives. }
9... b6 { Black continues with the plan to develop the light-squared bishop. }
10. Rd1
{ The rook on the d-file discourages attempts based on ...c5 because after the opening of the d-file the black queen on d8 may turn out to be vulnerable. }
10... Bb7 { Black finished development and now his aim is to push ...c5. } 11.
Nc3 { This is the main alternative to   11.Ne5 } 11... dxc4
{ As is usual in the Catalan, a knight on c3 signals that the pawn on c4 should be captured, because that knight on c3 makes it more difficult for White to regain it. The capture on c4 also liberates the d5-square for the knight, which is particularly important when the bishop is already on f4. }
12. Nd2
{ White manages to regain the pawn, but now Black uses the other idea of the ...dxc4 capture. }
12... Nd5
{ Attacking the bishop on f4 and threatening ...b5, which immediately wasn't possible in view of the pin on the long diagonal:   12...b5?  13.Nxb5 }
13. Nxc4 Nxf4 { Black takes the bishop before it could retreat. } 14. gxf4 Qc7
{ Developing the queen with tempo and connecting the rooks. } 15. e3 Rad8
{ The rook comes to the d-file in anticipation of White's d5 after Black executes ...c5. Black's only problem in this position is his lack of space, but he solves that easily because White cannot prevent ...c5. When Black pushes ...c5, White's chance is to push d5, and that is when the rook on d8 will come in handy. }
