1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5. Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5. Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black takes ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 Be7 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ... c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ...dxc4 and ... b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. Bf4
{ White activates the bishop, but there are also quite a few alternatives. }
9... b6 { Black continues with the plan to develop the light-squared bishop. }
10. Rd1
{ The rook on the d-file discourages attempts based on ...c5 because after the opening of the d-file the black queen on d8 may turn out to be vulnerable. }
10... Bb7 { Black finished development and now his aim is to push ...c5. } 11.
Ne5 Nxe5
{ Black takes the centralized knight. The most popular move here is  11...Nh5  but that allows a repetition after  12.Bd2  Nhf6  13.Bf4  and this may sometimes be a problem for the Black player. }
12. dxe5
{ White opens the d-file and plans to attack Black's pawn on d5 by e4. } 12...
Nd7 { Covering the d-file. } 13. cxd5
{ The immediate  13.e4?  allows  13...dxc4  14.Qxc4  Qc7  when White has problems with the e5-pawn. Therefore, White takes on d5 to avoid the capture on c4. }
13... exd5
{ The more combative recapture. Now the structure is asymmetrical and Black will have counterchances thanks to his queenside majority and good central control. }
14. e4 { White continues with his plan to attack down the d-file. } 14... d4
{ Black doesn't want to activate White's light-squared bishop by taking on e4. He will regain the pawn as the one on e5 is impossible to defend. }
15. Rxd4 Bc5 { Liberating the e7-square for the queen. } 16. Rd2
{ This will allow White to double the rooks later on. } 16... Qe7
{ Black regains the pawn and now a complex middlegame ensues. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Exchange Variation with 5.Bf4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation, but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by   6.Qc2  and the other is to allow it with 6. e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is natural. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. g4 Be6
{ In view of the possible h4-h5, the bishop drops back to e6 where it is safer. }
8. h3
{ This used to be the old treatment of the line, simply securing the pawn on  g4  . It may experience resurgence since the more aggressive treatment with  8.h4  turned out to lead to a draw. }
8... Nd7
{ Black develops the queen's knight first, as the other one awaits the developments on the kingside. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural and flexible move. After  9.Qb3  b5  @@StartFEN@@rn1qk1nr/pp2bppp/2p1b3/3p4/3P1BP1/2N1P3/PP3P1P/R2QKBNR w KQkq - 1 8@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line starting with  8.Qb3  b5  9.h3  Nd7   Another transposition is the move  9.Qc2  as after  9...h5  10.gxh5  Ngf6  11.h6  g6  12.Bd3  Nh5  we have a transposition to the line starting with 9.Bd3 }
9... h5
{ Attacking the advanced g-pawn and forcing White to worsen his structure by taking on h5. }
10. gxh5 Ngf6 { Black develops normally and wants to take on h5. } 11. h6
{ White tries to wreck Black's structure, but Black won't comply. } 11... g6
{ Naturally, Black wants to preserve the better structure. He plans to play ... Nh5 and take on h6 with the rook. }
