[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Exchange Variation with 5.Bf4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation, but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by   6.Qc2  and the other is to allow it with 6. e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is both natural and forced. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. g4 Be6
{ In view of the possible h4-h5, the bishop drops back to e6 where it is safer. }
8. Qb3
{ This is an interesting attempt. White wants to provoke ...Qb6 and then push h4, avoiding the forcing line after   8.h4  Bxh4 }
8... b5
{ This is a more active approach than 8. ..Qb6. Black grabs space on the queenside and still doesn't allow h4. The weaknesses on the c-file are not easy to take advantage of while Black's extra control over the c4-square may come in handy for the ... Nd7-b6-c4 maneuver. }
9. h3
{ Defending the pawn on g4 that was hanging with the removal of the queen from d1. }
9... Nd7
{ Black develops naturally. The knight can easily become active after ... Nb6-c4 and it also supports the ...c5-push. }
10. Nf3
{ If White starts with  10.Bd3  Black plays the same  10...Ngf6  and after  11.Nf3  Rc8  we have a transposition. }
10... Ngf6 { Continuing with development. } 11. Bd3
{ This is another try, but it gives Black counterplay based on the jump to e4. }
11... b4 { Kicking away the knight that controls the e4-square. } 12. Na4
{ Controlling the c5-square. If  12.Ne2  then  12...c5 } 12... Ne4
{ The knight is nicely centralized. } 13. Rc1
{ White tries to take advantage of the weaknesses on the c-file, but Black can eliminate them with his next move. }
13... c5
{ Black has enough control over the c5-square in order to be able to push this and get rid of the backward pawn. }
14. Nxc5 { White must take twice on c5. } 14... Ndxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb5+
{ If White moves the queen, for example  16.Qd1  then Black takes the light-squared bishop with  16...Nxd3  17.Qxd3  O-O  and his safer king and the bishop pair are more than enough compensation for the IQP. }
16... Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 18. Qd1
{ The queen needs to keep an eye on the d3-square. } 18... O-O
{ Finishing development. } 19. O-O Rac8
{ Black is comfortably equal here. The two major issues in the position are White's weaker king and Black's IQP and these compensate each other. Black has ideas like ...h5, to further weaken White's kingside, ...Ne6 and ...Bf6 to control the square in front of the IQP. }
