[Black "Exchange Variation with 4.Nf3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the white knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Bg5 c6
{ Black's main idea in the Carlsbad structure is to develop the light-squared bishop to f5. This is dictated by his pawn structure - with his queenside pawns on light squares the light-squared bishop is somewhat limited and the best square for it is f5. The reason why this version of the Exchange Variation is harmless for Black is because he can successfully develop his bishop on f5 as White cannot really prevent it. }
7. Qc2
{ This is an attempt to prevent ...Bf5 but after Black's next move it proves futile. }
7... g6
{ Black follows his plan. Now White has two options - either to allow ...Bf5 or to push e4 and change the character of the game. }
8. e3 Bf5
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ Black develops the bishop to  f5  . Play is similar to the line  7.e3  Bf5  as the difference is the pawn on g6, which doesn't affect the assessment of the position as the plans and ideas that both sides follow remain the same. }
9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7
{ Black wants to meet  11.Bxf6  with  11...Nxf6  capturing on f6 with the knight instead of the bishop. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1
{ The traditional minority attack doesn't bring White anything. In fact, it can easily lead him into trouble, but Black must know how to react to it. }
12... a5 { Preventing b4 for now. } 13. Qc2 Re8
{ The difference with the Kramnik game is that here ...Ne4 would be bad. White can escape with the bishop on h6, gaining tempo and winning a pawn after taking on e4 twice, i.e.  13...Ne4?  14.Bh6  Re8  15.Nxe4  dxe4  16.Qxe4  with a pawn up. Therefore, with the rook move Black prepares the knight jump to e4. }
14. a3 Ne4 { Now this works. } 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. b4
{ Continuing with the minority attack, but here we see why the exchange of the light-squared bishops is key for Black. By moving the b-pawn to b4, the c4-square is weakened. White doesn't have the light-squared bishop to control it, while both Black knights can target it. }
16... Nd6
{ Again we see the same idea as in the model game, Nikolic-Kramnik. Once White has weakened the c4-square by advancing the b-pawn, Black immediately takes advantage of it. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange Variation with 4.Nf3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the white knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Bg5 c6
{ Black's main idea in the Carlsbad structure is to develop the light-squared bishop to f5. This is dictated by his pawn structure - with his queenside pawns on light squares the light-squared bishop is somewhat limited and the best square for it is f5. The reason why this version of the Exchange Variation is harmless for Black is because he can successfully develop his bishop on f5 as White cannot really prevent it. }
7. e3 Bf5 { Black develops the bishop to f5 before White can play Bd3. } 8. Bd3
{ Otherwise the bishop on f5 will be very active. } 8... Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7
{ Connecting the knights so in case White takes on f6, Black can retake with a knight. }
10. O-O O-O
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/pp2bppp/2p2n2/3p2B1/3P4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  The position is very similar to the line   7.Qc2  g6  8.e3  Bf5  here Black's pawn is still on g7 rather than on g6. The manner of treating the position remains the same though - Black can successfully defend against the typical minority attack. }
11. Rab1 a5
{ Preventing b4 and when White prepares it with a3, then the exchange on b4 will open the a-file for Black. }
12. a3 { Preparing b4. } 12... Ne4
{ This knight jump is based on the tactic that the bishop on g5 is attacked so White cannot take twice on e4. If White takes on e7 and Black takes with the queen, the knight on e4 is defended twice. }
13. Bxe7
{ Note that   13.Nxe4?  loses a piece to  13...dxe4  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  and there is a fork on the queen and the knight. }
13... Qxe7 { Just in time to defend the knight on e4. } 14. b4
{ In fact this isn't very good, but it is important to know how to react to it. After   14.Nd2  Nxd2  15.Qxd2  Nb6  Black again comfortably controls the c4-square thus making White's minority attack less desirable. }
14... b5
{ A very important move. It prevents the minority attack with b5, fixes the pawn on b4 and establishes a strong outpost on c4 for one of the knights. Since White doesn't have the option to take on a5 and push a4, @@StartBracket@@like in the line 7.Qc2 where the queen was on c2 to support that a4-push@@EndBracket@@ Black doesn't need to hurry with the opening of the a-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Main Line 5.Bf4 with 7.Qc2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. White wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. Qc2 c5 8. Rd1 cxd4 { Luring the rook to d4. } 9. Rxd4
{ Taking with pawn gives Black a good version of the IQP after  9.exd4  dxc4  10.Bxc4  Nb6  with excellent control over the d5-square and quick development of the bishop with ...Bd7-c6.   Taking with knight loses a piece after  9.Nxd4?  e5 }
9... Qa5 { Pinning the knight and removing the queen from the d-file. } 10. Bg3
{ The bishop moves away from possible attacks after  10.cxd5  Nxd5 } 10... Nb6
{ Attacking White's pawn on c4. } 11. Nd2
{ White defends the pawn and breaks the pin on the c3-knight. } 11... dxc4
{ Black releases the tension in the center and exchanges one pair of minor pieces in order to gain time for the development of the light-squared bishop. }
12. Bxc4
{ White wants to have an active knight on  c4  . After  12.Nxc4  Nxc4  13.Bxc4  Bd7  Black easily finishes development. }
12... Nxc4
{ Black now has the bishop pair but still needs to develop the light-squared bishop. }
13. Nxc4 Qa6 { The queen is out of harm's way on a6. } 14. O-O Rd8
{ Challenging White's dominance on the d-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Main Line 5.Bf4 with 7.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. Be2
{ White develops and wants to castle as soon as possible. Note that after   7.Bd3  dxc4  8.Bxc4  we have a transposition to the line   7.Be2  dxc4  8.Bxc4 }
7... dxc4 8. O-O
{ After   8.Bxc4  c5  9.dxc5  Nxc5  10.O-O  (@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnbppp/4pn2/8/2pP1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R2QK2R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line   8.O-O  c5  9.dxc5  Nxc5  10.Bxc4  while after   8.Bxc4  c5  9.O-O  cxd4  we transpose to   8.O-O  c5  9.Bxc4 }
8... c5 9. Bxc4 cxd4
{ Black takes in this moment so White cannot recapture with a knight in view of the fork after ...e5. }
10. Qxd4
{ Black has good play against the IQP in case of   10.exd4  Nb6  followed by ...Nbd5 and ...Bd7-c6. }
10... Nb6
{ A multi-purpose move, liberating the d7-square for the light-squared bishop, threatening to take on c4 and offering an exchange of queens. }
