[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Main Line 5.Bf4 with 7.a3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Main Line 5.Bf4 with 7.c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. h3
{ With this move, White will try to wait with the development of the bishop from f1 in the hope that Black will play ...Ba6 so he can take on a6 in one go, without moving the bishop from the initial square. }
8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make  @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Bd3
{ With this move, White gives up the fight for tempo. He can try to postpone the development of the bishop, but Black simply develops following the rule of thumb: he plays ...Ba6 only when White has already moved the bishop, otherwise he prepares it with ...Bb7 and ...Qc8 first. }
11... Ba6
{ Since White moved his light-squared bishop, Black can play ...Ba6 immediately. }
12. O-O
{ In case of   12.b5  Bb7  the exchanges that will ensue on the queenside will free Black's pieces. For example,  13.cxb6  Qxb6  14.O-O  Rfc8 }
12... Qc8
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  Black plays the usual moves and prepares ...Qb7. Note that the lines that follow are identical to the lines after   8.Bd3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  Ba6  11.O-O  Qc8  the only difference being that the pawns are on h3 and h6 here, but this doesn't affect any variation. }
13. Rb1 { White removes the rook from the a-file and avoids exchanges. } 13...
axb4
{ Since White abandoned the a-file, Black opens it to activate the rook on a8. }
14. axb4 Bxd3
{ Black exchanges the bishops and follows up with ...Qb7 to enable the doubling of the rooks on the a-file. }
15. Qxd3 Qb7
{ Liberating the 8th rank so that the rook from f8 can come to a8. } *

