{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. Bd3 { The natural development of the bishop. } 8... b6
{ Black undermines White's pawn on c5. } 9. b4 a5
{ Attacking the b4-pawn. It is important to note that it is Black who controls the tension on the queenside as it is he who decides when and if to take. Generally, White cannot wreck his structure by taking on a5 or b6. }
10. a3
{ The move  10.b5  is met by  10...Bb7  and Black doesn't mind the exchanges on the queenside. }
10... Ba6
{ Black continues with his strategic plan to exchange his bad bishop. } 11. O-O
Qc8
{ Black doesn't rush with the exchange on  d3  and waits for the white queen to move first. As with the 8.h3 line, Black makes useful moves and manages to outlast White. The idea of this move is to play ...Qb7 and allow for the doubling of the rooks on the a-file. Another idea is to go for ...Rfc8 followed by  ...Bd8-c7  . The moves  12.h3  h6  will lead to the line starting with 8.h3. In fact, the lines are identical, the only difference being that the pawns are on h2 and h7 here, but this doesn't affect any of the variations.    Generally speaking, the positive aspect for Black in these lines is that against all of White's attempts, his play is more or less the same. The queen goes to b7, the bishop is exchanged, and then either he will double on the a-file or will play ...Rfc8 and ...Bd8-c7. The only thing Black needs to be careful about is the possibility of b5 by White, so when this becomes a threat, he will likely play ...b5 himself, with or without taking on b4 first. }
12. Qc2
{ This is the most commonly played move. White accepts to lose a tempo as he needs to connect his rooks. }
12... Bxd3
{ Black naturally wins the tempo by forcing the queen to move again. } 13. Qxd3
Qb7 { The usual move. Black prepares for the doubling on the a-file. } 14. Nd2
{ With this move, White wants to put the knight on b3 from where it will control both the c5 and a5-squares, but the drawback is that it weakens control of the e5-square. }
14... axb4 { Black exchanges on b4 and c5 in order to weaken the c5-pawn. } 15.
axb4 bxc5 16. bxc5 e5
{ This is the idea - by removing the pawn on b4 the pawn on c5 lacks protection and thanks to the central push, Black liberates his play. }
*

