Qc8
{ Black doesn't rush with the exchange on  d3  and waits for the white queen to move first. As with the 8.h3 line, Black makes useful moves and manages to outlast White. The idea of this move is to play ...Qb7 and allow for the doubling of the rooks on the a-file. Another idea is to go for ...Rfc8 followed by  ...Bd8-c7  . The moves  12.h3  h6  will lead to the line starting with 8.h3. In fact, the lines are identical, the only difference being that the pawns are on h2 and h7 here, but this doesn't affect any of the variations.    Generally speaking, the positive aspect for Black in these lines is that against all of White's attempts, his play is more or less the same. The queen goes to b7, the bishop is exchanged, and then either he will double on the a-file or will play ...Rfc8 and ...Bd8-c7. The only thing Black needs to be careful about is the possibility of b5 by White, so when this becomes a threat, he will likely play ...b5 himself, with or without taking on b4 first. }
