[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Main Line 6.Bxf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Qd2
{ White's plan is to castle long and if possible play e4 in one go. } 7... dxc4
{ This is known to be good for Black since the 1984 Karpov-Kasparov match. Even though White can take on c4 without losing a tempo with the bishop, it is important for Black to start immediate counterplay in the center. }
8. e4 { If  8.e3  then again  8...c5 } 8... c5 { Attacking White's center. } 9.
d5
{ This is the ambitious try. In case of   9.dxc5  Nd7  Black will take the c5-pawn with good play, or after  10.c6  bxc6  11.Bxc4  O-O  with ... Ne5 next. He can even claim to be better because of the bishop pair and his activity. }
9... exd5 10. e5
{ After   10.Nxd5  Nc6  Black has smooth development with ...O-O, ...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@fighting for the d4-square@@EndBracket@@ and so on. }
10... Bg5 11. Qxd5 Qxd5
{ Exchanging the queens and keeping the bishop pair with his next move. } 12.
Nxd5 Bd8
{ Black keeps the bishop pair and controls the c7-square. For now the knight on d5 looks strong, but it's not vey stable there and Black can develop his play around it. }
*

