1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move   7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line   7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Qb3 dxc4
{ The pawn on d5 was hanging, so Black takes on c4 to be able to prepare ... c5 as soon as possible. }
9. Bxc4 c5 10. dxc5
{ White takes the pawn, but he cannot keep it for long. Castling queenside is risky for White, after   10.O-O-O  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Qe7  followed by ...Nd7-c5. Black has good play on the queenside.  In case of   10.Rd1  cxd4  11.Nxd4  Qc7  Black has no problems as he finishes development with ... Bd7-c6. }
10... Nd7 { Black wants to recapture the pawn on c5 with a knight. } 11. Qa3
Qc7 12. b4
{ The only way to try to keep the pawn, but it is insufficient. After   12.Ne4  Be7  13.b4  b6  White's queenside collapses. }
12... a5
{ Undermining White's queenside. Black wants to play ...Qb8 or ...Rb8 and then take on b4. White cannot keep his queenside together. }
