{ Whenever possible, Black should strive to open the a1-h8 diagonal for the unopposed bishop on f6. }
9. dxc5
{ If   9.cxd5  then  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  exd5  with ...Nc6 next, when the dark-squared bishop ensures good control over the dark squares. }
9... dxc4
{ Black eliminates the tension in the center and plans to capture the pawn on c5. }
10. Bxc4 Nd7 { The most natural way to recapture the pawn. } 11. c6
{ Otherwise Black simply takes the pawn with ...Nxc5, or after   11.Rd1  Qa5 }
11... bxc6 12. O-O Rb8 { The rook occupies the semi-open b-file. } 13. Rac1 Qa5
{ Putting the queen on an active square. } 14. Rfd1 c5
{ The pawn controls the d4-square and limits the movement of the knight on f3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Main Line 6.Bxf6 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move   7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line   7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Rc1 dxc4
{ A relatively fresh idea that simplifies Black's task. The idea is similar to the lines after 7/8.Qd2, and 8.Qb3 when Black doesn't wait for White to move the light-squared bishop to take on c4 but takes immediately and proceeds with ...Nd7 and ...c5. }
9. Bxc4 Nd7 { Following the plan. } 10. O-O c5
{ Black achieved the ...c5 push and now he only needs to solve the problem of the development of his light-squared bishop. }
11. Qe2
{ This is an ambitious choice. White accepts an IQP in an attempt to have more active piece play. }
11... cxd4
{ Black needs to take on d4 so that he can move the knight from d7. } 12. exd4
{ After  12.Nxd4  Nb6  followed by ...Bd7 and ...Qe7. Black has no problems. }
12... Nb6
{ The usual move in these positions, the knight moves from d7 and attacks the bishop on c4. }
13. Bd3 g6
{ Black shuts the b1-h7 diagonal and with a good dark-squared bishop, he is ensured against any attacks. }
*

