1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn. Black wants to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation, he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 Nbd7
{ This has been used by Kramnik and he had excellent results with it. This move, together with the fact that the alternatives like the Lasker Variation with   7...Ne4  and the Tartakower Variation with   7...b6  are perfectly viable, are the main reasons why the move 5.Bg5 dropped in popularity and is less seen nowadays. }
8. Bd3 dxc4
{ A typical reaction to gain a tempo when a White bishop appears on d3. The same reaction would have happened against 8.Be2, as White doesn't really have an alternative to taking on c4, for example   8...dxc4  9.a4  is well met by  9...b6  followed by ...Bb7 and ...c5. }
9. Bxc4 c5 { The usual move for Black. } 10. O-O cxd4
{ Black resolves the tension in the centre. } 11. Nxd4
{ In case of   11.exd4  Nb6  12.Bb3  Bd7  with the idea of ...Bc6. Black will have great play against the IQP. }
11... Qb6 { Developing the queen and attacking the b2-pawn. } *

