[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange with 4.Nf3 and 6.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the White knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas on how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Qc2
{ This is an attempt to prevent ...Bf5 before developing the dark-squared bishop. }
6... c6
{ Black connects his pawn structure and awaits to see how White will proceed. }
7. h3
{ White shows his cards. He intends to play g4 to chase away the bishop once it comes to f5. However, this will weaken his kingside. }
7... O-O
{ Black continues with development and neutralises the development of White's bishop to g5. }
8. Bg5 { Would be natural, but it's met with } 8... Ne4 9. Bxe7
{ If   9.Bf4  Bf5  Black has an excellent position with the bishop developed on f5 and a centralized knight on e4. }
9... Qxe7 { With the bishop coming to f5 next, Black is very comfortable. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange with 4.Nf3 and 6.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the White knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas on how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Qc2
{ This is an attempt to prevent ...Bf5 before developing the dark-squared bishop. }
6... c6
{ Black connects his pawn structure and awaits to see how White will proceed. }
7. h3
{ White shows his cards. He intends to play g4 to chase away the bishop once it comes to f5. However, this will weaken his kingside. }
7... O-O
{ Black continues with development and neutralises the development of White's bishop to g5. }
8. Bf4 g6
{ Just like in the other lines, Black prepares the development of the bishop on f5. }
9. g4
{ White prevents the development of the bishop on f5 but weakens his kingside. }
9... Bd6
{ A good move, fighting for control of the dark squares in the center by exchanging White's active bishop. This idea is also frequently seen in the London System. }
10. Ne5
{ An ambitious play by White. The simplistic  10.Bxd6  Qxd6  is easy for Black who will develop with ...Nbd7, ...Re8 and then he will see where White castles before starting his activity. }
10... Qe7 { Defending the bishop on d6 and preparing ...Nbd7. } 11. e3 Nbd7
{ Forcing the knight from e5 to decide what to do, to retreat or to exchange on d7. The latter makes Black's play easier as exchanging the knight on d7 and the bishop on d6 solves Black's development instantly. }
12. Nd3 a5
{ A useful move, Black anticipates White's long castle and makes a move on the queenside that will help him advance his play there. }
13. Bg2
{ In case of  13.Bxd6  Qxd6  14.O-O-O  b5  Black is quick to start his queenside play. }
13... Bxf4 { With this exchange Black liberates the d6-square for the knight. }
14. Nxf4 Ne8
{ The d6-square is the ideal square for the knight in the Carlsbad structure. From there it controls all the important light squares: b7 @@StartBracket@@defending the pawn@@EndBracket@@, b5, c4, e4 and f5. }
15. O-O-O b5
{ Black starts his queenside action. The knights have good squares to go to and he will continue to advance. The position is double-edged but Black has good chances with his natural plan of a queenside advance. }
*

