[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Exchange with 4.Nf3 and 6.Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the White knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas on how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Bg5 c6
{ Black's main idea in the Carlsbad structure is to develop the light-squared bishop to f5. This is dictated by his pawn structure - with his queenside pawns on light squares the light-squared bishop is somewhat limited and the best square for it is f5. The reason why this version of the Exchange Variation is harmless for Black is because he can successfully develop his bishop on f5 as White cannot really prevent it. }
7. Qc2
{ This is an attempt to prevent ...Bf5 but after Black's next move it proves futile. }
7... g6
{ Black follows his plan. Now White has two options - either to allow ...Bf5 or to push e4 and change the character of the game. }
8. e4
{ Now play becomes more concrete. White voluntarily creates an IQP on d4 but hopes to get enough piece activity in return. }
8... dxe4 { Black naturally takes on e4. } 9. Bxf6
{ The move   9.Nxe4  is met by  9...Nxe4  10.Qxe4  Be6  followed by ...0-0 with easy development and play against the IQP. }
9... Bxf6 10. Qxe4+ Qe7
{ Since White has an IQP and banks on piece activity, it makes sense to exchange queens and go for an endgame. }
11. Bc4 Bf5 { Black develops with tempo and forces an exchange of queens. } 12.
Qxe7+ Kxe7
{ If Black is allowed to finish development and contain White's piece activity, he will stand better with his bishop pair and easy play against the IQP. That is why White must hurry to create something. }
13. O-O-O
{ Connecting the rooks. After   13.O-O  Black plays the same  13...Nd7  with similar ideas. }
13... Nd7
{ Black also connects the rooks. With the knight on d7, he can play ...Nb6 to attack the bishop on c4 and establish better control over the d5-square. }
14. h3
{ Threatening g4. In case of   14.Rhe1  Kf8  the king will move to g7  while the move   14.d5  is met by  14...Rhc8  with great play. }
14... h5 { Preventing White's threat of g4. } 15. Rhe1+ Kf8
{ Black will put the king on g7 next and will start play against the IQP with ...Nb6 and ...Rhd8. White should be careful not to end up worse, a sample line is }
16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Rxd3 Kg7 18. Ne4 Be7
{ With equality. If undisturbed, Black will put the rooks on e8 and d8 and play ...Nb6 to blockade the d4-pawn. }
