14. h3 Ngf6
{ We have arrived at the typical position for this line of the Exchange Variation. Black's ideas are to play ...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@by moving the bishop from e7 first@@EndBracket@@, ...Nb6 @@StartBracket@@to control the c4-square@@EndBracket@@, to put a piece @@StartBracket@@bishop or knight@@EndBracket@@ on d6, and if White is passive to eventually organize play on the kingside. }
15. Ne5
{ White seeks exchanges. In case of  15.Rab1  a5  16.a3  Nb6  Black controls the c4-square and intends ...Nc4 and ...Bd6. }
15... Nb6
{ This move is useful as it controls the c4-square, which dissuades White from the minority attack. Black is very comfortable here, so please take a look at the model game,Bobotsov-Petrosian, to see how Black can win in these positions when White plays passively. }
