14. a3 Ne4 { Now this works. } 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. b4
{ Continuing with the minority attack, but here we see why the exchange of the light-squared bishops is key for Black. By moving the b-pawn to b4, the c4-square is weakened. White doesn't have the light-squared bishop to control it, while both Black knights can target it. }
16... Nd6
{ Again we see the same idea as in the model game, Nikolic-Kramnik. Once White has weakened the c4-square by advancing the b-pawn, Black immediately takes advantage of it. }
17. Nd2
{ Covering the c4-square. In case of   17.b5  Nc4  the knight is quite annoying on c4. }
17... axb4
{ Opening the a-file first and releasing the tension. In case of   17...b5  White has  18.bxa5  Rxa5  19.a4 }
18. axb4 b5
{ Black is better here. His ideas are putting a knight to b6 and then decide which one should go to c4. This will be combined with the play on the a-file and against the weak pawn on b4. In case White manages to defend the queenside, Black can switch his play on the kingside as shown in the model game Nikolic-Kramnik. A sample line here is: }
19. Ra1 Nb6 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. e4
{ White tries to be active but this only weakens the d4-pawn. } 21... Ndc4 22.
exd5 Nxd5 23. Nxc4
{ After   23.Nxd5  cxd5  White has problems with the pawn on b4. } 23... bxc4
24. Nxd5 cxd5
{ Black is clearly better here - he has a protected passed pawn and can play against White's weak pawns on b4 and d4. }
