[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Nf3 Nf6 5. cxd5 exd5
{ This version of the Exchange Variation, with the White knight already on f3, is harmless for Black. However, it is in this line that all the main ideas on how to successfully play the Carlsbad structure are demonstrated, so I'd urge you to pay special attention to the lines that follow, especially as the Carlsbad structure features in other lines in this repertoire, like for example the London System. }
6. Bg5 c6
{ Black's main idea in the Carlsbad structure is to develop the light-squared bishop to f5. This is dictated by his pawn structure - with his queenside pawns on light squares the light-squared bishop is somewhat limited and the best square for it is f5. The reason why this version of the Exchange Variation is harmless for Black is because he can successfully develop his bishop on f5 as White cannot really prevent it. }
7. e3 Bf5 { Black develops the bishop to f5 before White can play Bd3. } 8.
Bxf6
{ With this exchange, White prevents the recapture on f6 with a knight after ...Nbd7. }
8... Bxf6 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Be7
{ The bishop drops back to e7 to control the b4-square and slow down the minority attack. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 a5 { Preventing b4. } 13. a3 Nd7
{ Black develops normally and the knight is ready to go to b6 to target the c4-square when White pushes b4. }
14. b4 axb4 { Opening the a-file first. } 15. axb4 b5
{ The typical reaction. It fixes the pawn on b4 and allows for ...Nb6-c4. Black has excellent play here. If White plays }
16. e4 { Then after the exchange on e4, Black continues with his plan. } 16...
dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nb6
{ Black has great play on the light squares and White has problems with the pawn on b4. }
*

