[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "White Plays 4.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. Qc2
{ This is a tricky attempt to enter the Exchange Variation by keeping the knight on g1. }
4... Nf6 { Black develops normally. } 5. cxd5 Nxd5
{ This is the important recapture as taking with a pawn will give White what he wants   5...exd5  6.Bg5  leads to the Exchange Variation where White can employ the Botvinnik set-up with e3, Bd3 and Nge2. }
6. Nf3 O-O
{ Black wants to follow up with ...Nd7 and ...c5 or ...b6 and ...Bb7. } 7. e4
{ White advances in the center, forcing Black to take on c3. } 7... Nxc3 8.
bxc3 { If   8.Qxc3  then again  8...b6  with ...c5 and ...Bb7 to come. } 8...
b6
{ This is an important move, aiming to exchange the light-squared bishops as soon as possible. After the natural   8...c5  things can become dangerous after  9.Bd3  cxd4  10.e5  with initiative for White thanks to the strong pressure on the b1-h7 diagonal. In order to avoid these problems Black wants to exchange the dangerous bishop. }
9. Bd3 Ba6 { Following the plan. } 10. O-O c5
{ With the exchange of the light-squared bishops assured, Black now starts the usual play against White's center. After ...c5, he will take on d4 and use the c-file to create play on the queenside. }
11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. Bf4 cxd4 { Opening the c-file. } 13. cxd4 Nb4
{ Moving the knight from the rim with tempo. } 14. Qb3 Rc8
{ With good play for Black. Since a couple of minor pieces have been exchanged, White cannot really create threats on the kingside. His only feasible plan is to push d5, but Black's well-placed pieces can deal with the passed d-pawn. Black's own queenside majority waits to be utilized at an appropriate moment. Black's ideas include the exchange of the bishops with ...Bd6, rerouting the knight via c6 to a5 and c4, and the move ...Qd7 for better control of the light squares on the queenside. }
