1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. g4
{ This is very rare and not particularly good, but since these types of moves have become popular it's worth taking a quick look. }
4... Nf6
{ Black continues with normal development. It goes against the principles of chess that such an early aggressive treatment with 4.g4 should pose serious problems. Black reacts by developing and playing in the centre, following the classical principles. }
5. g5
{ After  5.Nf3  O-O  we have a transposition to the chapter The Main Line 5.Various. }
5... Ne4 { Attacking g5, thus forcing White to take on e4. } 6. Nxe4 dxe4 7.
Bg2 e5
{ Here comes the central strike solving all problems. If anything, White should be careful about his kingside weaknesses. }
8. dxe5
{ In case of  8.d5  Bxg5  9.Bxe4  f5  10.Bc2  Bf6  followed by ...O-O and Black has excellent play. }
8... Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bf5
{ Defending the pawn on e4. Black will continue with ...Nc6 and ...O-O-O with great play. }
