[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is natural. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. Nge2 Nd7
{ It is important to start with this flexible move as keeping the knight on g8 leaves the h4-d8 diagonal open and the move h4 by White in some lines can be difficult to achieve. }
8. Ng3
{ This forces the bishop to g6 as going to e6 would allow Bd3. White can also start with   8.Rc1  but after  8...Nb6  9.Ng3  Bg6  we have a transposition. }
8... Bg6 9. Rc1 Nb6 { Black still keeps the knight on g8 to discourage h4. }
10. Nh5
{ The only way to take advantage of the absence of the knight on f6. If   10.Be2  Nf6  11.h4  (@@StartFEN@@r2qk1nr/pp1nbppp/2p3b1/3p4/3P1B2/2N1P1N1/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 5 9@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line starting with  9.Be2  Nb6  10.Rc1  Nf6  11.h4 }
10... Bxh5 { Black naturally takes the knight. } 11. Qxh5 Bd6
{ Exchanges help Black and with the exchange of the dark-squared bishops, White will no longer have the advantage of the bishop pair. }
12. Bg3
{ If   12.Bxd6  Qxd6  with ...g6 and ... Nf6 next Black is very comfortable.  The move   12.Bg5  Be7  may lead to a repetition after  13.Bf4  Bd6  though Black if he wishes may continue with   13...Nf6  followed by ...O-O and play ...Re8 and perhaps ...Bd6 at a later stage. }
12... Nf6 { Developing the chasing away the queen. } 13. Qf3 g6
{ A flexible move that prepares ...Nh5 to force the exchange of the bishops and keeps the option for Black to castle on either side. Additionally, by placing a pawn on a light square it limits White's light-squared bishop. }
14. Bd3 { If   14.Bh4  Be7  and then again with the idea of ...Nh5. } 14... Nh5
15. Bxd6 Qxd6
{ Black has no problems here. He is still flexible with the castling and the knight from h5 will come back via either g7 or f6. }
