1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is natural. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. Nge2 Nd7
{ It is important to start with this flexible move as keeping the knight on g8 leaves the h4-d8 diagonal open and the move h4 by White in some lines can be difficult to achieve. }
8. Ng3
{ This forces the bishop to g6 as going to e6 would allow Bd3. White can also start with   8.Rc1  but after  8...Nb6  9.Ng3  Bg6  we have a transposition. }
8... Bg6 9. Be2
{ Note that the move   9.Nh5?  loses to  9...Qb6  as White cannot defend the pawn on b2 since the queen on d1 must keep contact with the knight on h5. }
9... Nb6
{ This is a useful move as the knight can often jump to c4, either attacking b2 or en route to d6. At the same time Black still keeps the knight on g8 to discourage h4. }
10. Rc1
{ The move   10.Nh5  is harmless as after the exchange on h5 Black can continue with ...Bd6 exchanging the dark-squared bishops:  10...Bxh5  11.Bxh5  Bd6  with easy play. The move with the rook is a waiting move for White as he anticipates the development of the knight on f6. }
10... Nf6
{ Black ran out of useful moves and finally develops the knight on f6 allowing h4. }
11. h4 h6
{ It is better to put the pawn on h6 than on h5 since on h5 it is always under attack. }
12. h5 Bh7 13. Bd3
{ Similar to the line with 10. Be5 White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops to obtain the f5-square for his knight. }
13... Qd7
{ A nice move, making White work harder for access to the f5-square. } 14. Qc2
{ This forces Black to take on d3 but it loses a tempo. After } 14... Bxd3 15.
Qxd3 O-O 16. Nf5 Ne4 { Cuts the connection between the queen and the knight. }
17. g4
{ If White takes on e4 then Black takes on f5:   17.Nxe4  Qxf5  with great play. }
17... Rae8
{ Indirectly defending the pawn on e4 in case of   18.Nxe4  dxe4  19.Qxe4?  Bb4  winning the queen. }
18. f3 Ng5
{ One of the key ideas for Black in this line - the knight is excellent on g5, preventing any attacks and controlling both f3 and e4. }
19. Kf2 Nc4 { Activating the knight and bringing it to d6. } 20. b3 Nd6
{ Challenging the knight on f5. } 21. Bxd6 Bxd6
{ With great play for Black. The knight on g5 is untouchable @@StartBracket@@chasing it away with f4 will weaken the e4-square@@EndBracket@@ and he can double on the e-file and try a move like ...a5 on the queenside to introduce some tension there. If allowed, he would gladly open the game with ...c5 as his king is safer than White's. }
