1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is natural. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. g4 Be6
{ In view of the possible h4-h5, the bishop drops back to e6 where it is safer. }
8. h3
{ This used to be the old treatment of the line, simply securing the pawn on  g4  . It may experience resurgence since the more aggressive treatment with  8.h4  turned out to lead to a draw. }
8... Nd7
{ Black develops the queen's knight first, as the other one awaits the developments on the kingside. }
9. Bd3
{ The most natural and flexible move. After  9.Qb3  b5  we have a transposition to the line starting with 8.Qb3 b5 9.h3 Nd7   Another transposition is the move  9.Qc2  as after  9...h5  9.gxh5  Ngf6  10.h6  g6  11.Bd3  Nh5  we have a transposition to the text variation. }
9... h5
{ Attacking the advanced g-pawn and forcing White to worsen his structure by taking on h5. }
10. gxh5 Ngf6 { Black develops normally and wants to take on h5. } 11. h6
{ White tries to wreck Black's structure, but Black won't comply. } 11... g6
{ Naturally, Black wants to preserve the better structure. He plans to play ...Nh5 and take on h6 with the rook. }
12. Qc2
{ White cannot save the pawn and continues with development. In case of  12.Qd2  @@StartBracket@@with the idea to play e4 when the bishop from f4 retreats@@EndBracket@@ Black plays  12...Bf8  with the idea to recapture on d6 with the bishop. }
12... Nh5
{ Black continues with his plan, attacking the bishop and when it moves he recaptures the pawn on h6. }
13. Bh2 Rxh6
{ Black accomplished his plan and now can boast a better pawn structure. } 14.
O-O-O Ng7 { Bringing the knight back into the game and preparing ...Bf5. } 15.
Kb1
{ In case of  15.Nge2  @@StartBracket@@with the idea of Nf4@@EndBracket@@ Black still plays  15...Bf5   while after  15.Nf3  he can safely take the pawn on h3  15...Rxh3 }
15... Bf5 { Black accomplishes the exchange of the light-squared bishops. } 16.
Bxf5 Nxf5 17. e4
{ This is an attempt to take advantage of the black king in the centre, but Black can deal with the threats. }
17... dxe4 18. d5
{ Trying to bust open the centre as the alternatives are fine for Black, for example  18.Nxe4  Nf6   or  18.Qxe4  Rh4  chasing away the active queen. }
18... Qb6 { Defending the pawn on c6 and preparing long castle. } 19. d6 Bf6
20. Nxe4 O-O-O
{ Black has very good play here, with the better pawn structure and more compact position. }
