9. Qb3 { This was supposed to be the refutation of 8...Bxh4, but after } 9...
g5 { Black has more than enough counterplay. } 10. Qxb7
{ Is the most direct move, but Black plays } 10... gxf4 11. Rxh4
{ White takes the bishop and still attacks the rook on a8. } 11... Nd7
{ Developing the knight and threatening ...Rb8 and ...Qh4. } 12. Nf3
{ White defends the rook and develops the knight. } 12... fxe3 13. fxe3
{ In case of   13.Qxc6  exf2  14.Kxf2  Ne7  the position remains complex but Black is perfectly fine as he intends to play ...Nf6 next. }
13... Rb8 14. Qxa7
{ In case of   14.Qxc6  Black plays  14...Rxb2  all the same. } 14... Rxb2 15.
Qa3 Qb8
{ Defending the rook and threatening ...Qg3. Black's king is relatively safe with many pieces around him and Black has good central control so White cannot easily create threats. The middlegame is complicated with chances for both sides. }
