9. Qb3 { This was supposed to be the refutation of 8...Bxh4, but after } 9...
g5 { Black has more than enough counterplay. } 10. Qxb7
{ Is the most direct move, but Black plays } 10... gxf4 11. exf4
{ White wants to return the piece by playing f5 as the rook on a8 also hangs so Black's next is forced. }
11... Nd7 { The only way to defend the rook on a8. } 12. f5 Rb8
{ Not only attacking the queen, but in fact getting the rook to e6! } 13. Qxc6
Rb6 14. Qa4 h5
{ Undermining White's g4-f5 pair. Additionally, when the h-file is opened Black will threaten ...Bxf2 when the undefended rook on h1 will fall. }
15. fxe6 Rxe6+ { The rook got to e6 in a very curious manner! } 16. Nge2 hxg4
{ Threatening ...Bxf2. } 17. Bg2
{ White defends the rook on h1 and threatens the pawn on d5. } 17... g3
{ Going forward, Black wants to harass White's king. } 18. fxg3
{ Otherwise Black would have a well-advanced pawn on g3. } 18... Bxg3+ 19. Kd1
Rxh1+ 20. Bxh1 Qf6
{ Activating the queen. The position is very sharp but with best play should end in a draw. A sample line is }
21. Nxg3 Qf2 { Threatening mate. } 22. Nge2 Rxe2 23. Nxe2 Qf1+ 24. Kd2 Qxa1
{ With an equal endgame. } *

