{ Unlike the line with immediate 10.Bh2, Black cannot play   11...Qb6  here as after  12.Qc2  he doesn't have the ...Nf6 move at his disposal. This means he needs to take on g4 with his bishop but after  12...Bxg4  13.Be2  Bxe2  14.Qxe2  White is fully developed, he will castle long next and play Nf3 to take the bishop on h4 while Black has no counterplay. Therefore, he takes on g4 immediately. }
12. Qxb7 Qe7
{ The important counter-attacking move. The pawn on e3 is hanging. } 13. Qxa8
{ This is critical, but now Black develops a strong attack and White must defend carefully. }
13... Qxe3+ 14. Be2
{ Otherwise White gets mated,   14.Nge2?  Bxf2  15.Kd1  Qd3  16.Kc1  Be3# }
14... Bxf2+ 15. Kf1
{ Going to d1 again leads to mate,   15.Kd1?  Qd3  16.Kc1  Be3# } 15... Bh4
{ Threatening mate on f2. } 16. Qxb8+ Kf7
{ Black is a rook and piece down, but his attack is so strong that White must play only moves to avoid being mated! }
17. Nd1
{ The only way to defend against mate. White could have inserted   17.Qc7  Ne7  but then again he would have had to play  18.Nd1 }
17... Bxe2+
{ Forcing White to take with the knight so that he can give check from f3. }
18. Nxe2 Qf3+ 19. Kg1 Qxe2 { The threat now is to give check from e1. } 20. Bg3
{ Trying to exchange another attacking piece, the bishop on h4. } 20... Qg4
{ Pinning the bishop. } 21. Kg2 Qe4+ 22. Kh2
{ Going to g1 leads to repetition,   22.Kg1  Qg4 } 22... Ne7
{ Black continues in sacrificial style, giving away the useless rook on h8 in order to get the knight included in the attack. }
23. Qxh8 Bxg3+ 24. Kg1
{ Much safer than taking the bishop after   24.Kxg3  as after  24...Qxh1  Black continues the attack - White is a rook up with his knight on d1, and the rook on a1 is paralyzed. White's queen is out of play while Black threatens ...Nf5-d4 or to advance his kingside pawns. }
24... Qe1+ 25. Kg2 Qe2+ { Offering White a last chance to go wrong. } 26. Kg1
{ Taking the bishop would be suicidal,   26.Kxg3??  Nf5  27.Kh3  g4#  as would   26.Kh3??  g4  27.Kxg3  Nf5  28.Kf4  Qf3# }
26... Qe1+ { With a perpetual check. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Main Line 6.e3 #17"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. e3
{ White wants to play Bd3 now to reach the ideal set-up, so Black's next is natural. }
6... Bf5
{ Developing the bishop on the best square and preventing Bd3. White now hopes to take advantage of the bishop's position on f5 by attacking it with g4 or Nge2-g3. }
7. g4 Be6
{ In view of the possible h4-h5, the bishop drops back to e6 where it is safer. }
8. Qb3
{ This is an interesting attempt. White wants to provoke ...Qb6 and then push h4, avoiding the forcing line after   8.h4  Bxh4 }
8... b5
{ This is a more active approach than   8...Qb6  Black grabs space on the queenside and still doesn't allow h4. The weaknesses on the c-file are not easy to take advantage of while Black's extra control over the c4-square may come in handy for the ... Nd7-b6-c4 maneuver. }
9. h3
{ Defending the pawn on g4 that was hanging with the removal of the queen from d1. }
9... Nd7
{ Black develops naturally. The knight can easily become active after ...Nb6-c4 and it also supports the ...c5-push. }
10. Nf3
{ If White starts with  10.Bd3  Black plays the same  10...Ngf6  and after  11.Nf3  Rc8  we have a transposition. }
10... Ngf6 { Continuing with development. } 11. Bd3
{ This is another try, but it gives Black counterplay based on the jump to e4. }
11... b4 { Kicking away the knight that controls the e4-square. } 12. Na4
{ Controlling the c5-square. If  12.Ne2  then  12...c5 } 12... Ne4
{ The knight is nicely centralized. } 13. Rc1
{ White tries to take advantage of the weaknesses on the c-file, but Black can eliminate them with his next move. }
13... c5
{ Black has enough control over the c5-square in order to be able to push this and get rid of the backward pawn. }
14. Nxc5 { White must take twice on c5. } 14... Ndxc5 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Bb5+
{ If White moves the queen, for example  16.Qd1  then Black takes the light-squared bishop with  16...Nxd3  17.Qxd3  O-O  and his safer king and the bishop pair are more than enough compensation for the IQP. }
16... Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 18. Qd1
{ The queen needs to keep an eye on the d3-square. } 18... O-O
{ Finishing development. } 19. O-O Rac8
{ Black is comfortably equal here. The two major issues in the position are White's weaker king and Black's IQP and these compensate each other. Black has ideas like ...h5, to further weaken White's kingside, ...Ne6 and ...Bf6 to control the square in front of the IQP. }
*

