4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. Qc2 { This prevents the development of the bishop on f5. } 6... Nf6
{ Natural development, but in fact Black wants to take advantage of the fact that the white queen no longer controls the d1-h5 diagonal and play ...Nh5, harassing the bishop on f4. It is worth noting why the natural move   6...g6  with the idea of ...Bf5 doesn't work here. The reason lies in the line  7.e3  Bf5  8.Qd2  and with f3 and e4 next Black is pushed backwards. Compare this to the line 6...Nf6 7.h3 g6 where Black has already developed the knight on f6 so when White plays Qd2 he has the simplifying move ...Ne4 at his disposal before White plays f3. }
7. h3 { This is an attempt to preserve the bishop. } 7... g6
{ Black insists on developing the bishop on f5. } 8. e3 Bf5 9. Qd2
{ This is White's idea. He doesn't exchange the light-squared bishops but intends to expand with either g4 or f3 and e4 and gain space by kicking away Black's bishop. }
9... Ne4
{ An important move. Even though Black would like to exchange the light-squared bishops, the exchange of knights will make his position more comfortable to play as his pieces feel less confined. }
10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. f3
{ White gains tempo for a useful move that can support both g4 and e4. } 11...
Bf5 12. Ne2 { The knight goes to c3. } 12... Nd7
{ Black finished development and now we have a complex middlegame ahead. One general idea for Black is that he should castle on the same side as White because it will avoid an attack against his king. }
13. Nc3
{ The move   13.Bh6  allows  13...Bg5  with a favorable exchange of another minor piece. }
13... Nb6
{ Similar to the line with 13.O-O-O, Black liberates the d7-square for the queen so that a long castle is possible. It also allows for the ...Bd6 idea to exchange the dark-squared bishops. }
14. e4 Be6 15. O-O-O
{ White cannot really go for short castling as after   15.Be2  Black has the annoying check on h4:  15...Bh4  that forces White to weaken his kingside with  16.g3  and after  16...Be7  White will again be forced to castle long. }
15... Bd6
{ Now whatever White does: take on d6 and push e5, push e5 immediately or move the bishop, Black's plan is to castle long and then either undermine or blockade White's centre. Here're a few sample lines: }
16. e5 Be7 17. Bh6 Qd7
{ With ...O-O-O next and then either ...f6 to undermine the e5-pawn, or ...f5 to stop White's advance after g4 and f4. These ideas are coupled with the move ...Nc4. }
