[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Main Line 6.Qc2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. Qc2 { This prevents the development of the bishop on f5. } 6... Nf6
{ Natural development, but in fact Black wants to take advantage of the fact that the white queen no longer controls the d1-h5 diagonal and play ...Nh5, harassing the bishop on f4. It is worth noting why the natural move   6...g6  with the idea of ...Bf5 doesn't work here. The reason lies in the line  7.e3  Bf5  8.Qd2  and with f3 and e4 next Black is pushed backwards. Compare this to the line 6...Nf6 7.h3 g6 where Black has already developed the knight on f6 so when White plays Qd2 he has the simplifying move ...Ne4 at his disposal before White plays f3. }
7. e3
{ This is natural, but it allows the exchange of the dark-squared bishop for a knight. This exchange leads to very dynamic play. }
7... Nh5
{ Now the dark-squared bishop is short of squares and it will be exchanged for Black's knight, giving Black the advantage of the bishop pair. The only thing White can do now is to seek compensation for the bishop pair by attempting to wreck Black's structure. }
8. Bg3 { This is possible, but obviously not threatening. } 8... Nxg3
{ Black eliminates the bishop and then uses the fact that his access to the g4-square cannot be challenged. }
9. hxg3 g6 { Defending the pawn on h7. } 10. Bd3 Nd7
{ The knight is en route to the g4-square. Now White needs to decide whether to let it arrive there, so he has two possible plans: to play Nf3 @@StartBracket@@allowing ...Nf6-g4@@EndBracket@@ or Nge2 @@StartBracket@@preventing ...Ng4 as there always will be f3@@EndBracket@@ . }
11. Nf3 Nf6 { Black continues with the plan. } 12. O-O-O
{ If   12.Ne5  Ng4  gets rid of the knight on e5. } 12... Ng4
{ The knight is excellent on g4 - it targets the f2-pawn, thus limiting the activity of the queen on c2. It also controls the e5-square, preventing a centralization of White's knight. Black can continue with ...Bf6 and ...O-O and then start play on the queenside. }
