12. Nge2 f6 { Attacking the advanced pawn. } 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Rd1
{ White wants to push e4, so the rook belongs on the d-file to control the movement of Black's d-pawn. }
14... O-O 15. O-O
{ If   15.e4  d4  and then White would have to castle short anyway. } 15... Kh8
{ Generally a useful move, removing the king from the a2-g8 diagonal and liberating the g8-square for a rook. }
16. e4
{ White should try to play in the centre as otherwise he has no active plans. }
16... d4 { Naturally, Black advances and obtains a protected passed pawn. } 17.
Nf4 Qe8
{ Getting away from the pin on the d-file and defending the pawn on h5. } 18.
Nce2 b6 { Black wants to connect his queenside structure. } 19. b4
{ Preventing ...c5. Note that   19.Nxd4?  loses a piece after  19...Bxd4  20.Rxd4  Rxf4 }
19... Ba6
{ A very good diagonal for the light-squared bishop from where it also supports the d-pawn. }
20. Rfe1 Rc8
{ With the idea to push ...c5 and then have a pair of passed pawns in the center. The position is still complex, but objectively Black is better as his bishops and pawns are dominating the board. }
