{ Of course, if the bishop moved Black would have lost the d4-pawn without any compensation. }
17. exf6 cxb2+ 18. Qxb2 O-O
{ Black has great play here as White's king is more exposed than Black's. The ideas are ...Bf5 and ...Qc5 so White's best is to save the draw by }
19. Qe5 { Threatening mate by Qg5-g7. } 19... Qa3+ 20. Kb1 Bf5+ 21. Qxf5 Qb4+
22. Kc2 Qa4+
{ With perpetual check as White cannot cross the d-file as then Black's rook gets to d8 with check. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 1: The Exchange Variation"]
[Black "Main Line 6.Qc2 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7
{ The point of developing the bishop first is to avoid the development of White's knight to  e2  in the Exchange Variation. This would happen in case of  3...Nf6  4.cxd5  exd5  5.Bg5  Be7  6.e3  c6  7.Bd3  followed by 8. Nge2. This invention by Mikhail Botvinnik is still considered the most promising for White in the Exchange Variation. The idea is not to block the f-pawn so as to be able to build a big center by playing f3 and e4 and later this can develop into a strong kingside attack. With the move order 3...Be7, if White still wants to play the Exchange Variation he will have to make some concessions. }
4. cxd5
{ The Exchange Variation is one of the core variations in the Queen's Gambit Declined. White immediately defines the pawn structure, transposing to the so-called Carlsbad structure, and plans to develop with e3, Bd3, Qc2, and Nge2 or Nf3. }
4... exd5 5. Bf4 c6
{ Black connects his structure and plans ...Bf5 next. Solving the problem of the development of the bishop on c8 is one of Black's main ideas not only in the Exchange Variation but also in the whole QGD. Now White has two options: one is to prevent the development of the bishop on f5 by 6. Qc2 and the other is to allow it with 6.e3. }
6. Qc2 { This prevents the development of the bishop on f5. } 6... Nf6
{ Natural development, but in fact Black wants to take advantage of the fact that the white queen no longer controls the d1-h5 diagonal and play ...Nh5, harassing the bishop on f4. It is worth noting why the natural move   6...g6  with the idea of ...Bf5 doesn't work here. The reason lies in the line  7.e3  Bf5  8.Qd2  and with f3 and e4 next Black is pushed backwards. Compare this to the line 6...Nf6 7.h3 g6 where Black has already developed the knight on f6 so when White plays Qd2 he has the simplifying move ...Ne4 at his disposal before White plays f3. }
7. e3
{ This is natural, but it allows the exchange of the dark-squared bishop for a knight. This exchange leads to very dynamic play. }
7... Nh5
{ Now the dark-squared bishop is short of squares and it will be exchanged for Black's knight, giving Black the advantage of the bishop pair. The only thing White can do now is to seek compensation for the bishop pair by attempting to wreck Black's structure. }
8. Be5 Nd7 { Black develops and goes after the bishop. } 9. Be2 Nxe5
{ Black takes the bishop pair and then defends the knight on h5. } 10. dxe5 g6
{ Defending the knight and opening an escape route via g7. } 11. Bxh5 gxh5
{ White wrecked Black's kingside structure, but had to give up both his bishops. The ensuing middlegame is very dynamic as we see a battle of knights versus bishops. White needs to make two important choices: where to castle and where to develop the knight from g1 - to e2 or f3. }
12. O-O-O f6 { The usual move for Black, getting rid of the pawn on e5. } 13.
e4 d4
{ Black obtains a passed pawn now and even though it cannot advance further, White must keep an eye on it at all times. }
14. exf6 Bxf6 15. Nge2
{ This development of the knight is flexible as it doesn't block the f-pawn. }
15... O-O
{ Black castles and now wants to play ...Be6 and then ... c5, as the bishop on e6 prevents the Nd5 jump. }
16. f4 Bg7 { Getting away from attacks with e5. } 17. e5
{ Attacking the pawn on d4 and shutting the bishop on g7. But White's problem in all these positions is that he can never entirely close the position. On whichever squares he puts his pawns, one bishop will become stronger. This is the case here - the dark-squared bishop is limited by the f4-e5 pair, but this weakened the light squares, and the light-squared bishop obtained great squares on e6, f5, and g4. }
17... c5
{ Defending the pawn on d4 and since White played e5, now there is no Nd5. }
18. Ne4 Qd5
{ Centralising the queen and attacking the pawn on a2. Black has fantastic play here, his ideas are ...Be6 @@StartBracket@@to reinforce the attack on the a2-g8 diagonal@@EndBracket@@, ...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@exposing the weakness of the f4-pawn by pinning the knight that defends it@@EndBracket@@ and various ideas based on the movement of the central pawns. }
*

