[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Keeps the Knight on g1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ With this move order, we will examine the lines where White keeps the knight on b1 and keeps maximum flexibility where to develop it @@StartBracket@@d2 or c3@@EndBracket@@. }
3... Nf6 { Black develops in the usual manner. } 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 h6
{ Black plays the same moves as always. } 6. Bxf6
{ The alternatives are either harmless or transpose: after  6.Bh4  O-O  7.Nbd2  Nbd7  Black plays ...c5 next and the knight on d2 is worse than on c3;   or  6.Bf4  O-O  7.Nc3  transposes to the chapter  The Main Line 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bh4 }
6... Bxf6 7. Qc2 dxc4
{ An important move. In case of the automatic  7...O-O  White has  8.h4  followed by g4 and compared to the line 8.h4, the move Qc2 is more useful than Nc3. }
8. Bxc4
{ After  8.Qxc4  O-O  9.Nc3  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/4PN2/PP3PPP/RN1QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  9.Nc3 }
8... Nd7
{ Another important move. After  8...O-O  White can again start with  9.h4  with unpleasant initiative against Black's king. That is why Black waits to see where White will put his king, and second, prepares the ...c5-push with central play, which will distract White from any kingside activity. }
9. Nc3 { In case of  9.O-O  O-O  10.Nc3  c5  Black has no problems. } 9... c5
{ Still waiting with the castling and starting immediate center action. } 10.
O-O-O { The ambitious attempt, as otherwise Black is fine. } 10... cxd4
{ Avoiding dxc5. } 11. Nxd4 Qe7
{ Getting away from the d-file and preparing ... Nb6 and ...Bd7. } 12. g4
{ Continuing with aggressive play. } 12... Nb6
{ Liberating the d7-square for the bishop. } 13. Bb5+
{ After  13.Bb3  Bd7  14.h4  Black can play  14...Qc5  with ...O-O-O next. Here we can see the advantage of being flexible and not castling short too early. }
13... Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Qxd7
{ Black is ready to start his own activities on the queenside. } 15. h4
{ The move  15.Nf5  is not dangerous as after  15...Qc7  16.Nd6  Ke7  with the rook from h8 joining the game and coming to d8 Black will chase away the knight from d6. }
15... Rc8 { The threat is to play ...Nd5 and attack the pinned knight on c3. }
16. g5
{ If  16.Nf5  Nd5  White is in trouble as both his knights are under fire. }
16... Bxd4 { The simplest, escaping the attack with tempo. } 17. Rxd4 Qc6
{ Again escaping with tempo. } 18. Rhd1 Nd5
{ The position is equal. Black's pressure on c3 will likely lead to many exchanges and an equal rook endgame @@StartBracket@@after Black castles short to avoid Rd8 ideas@@EndBracket@@. }
