[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.Qd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, in case we castle short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Qd2
{ White's plan is to castle long and if possible play e4 in one go. } 7... dxc4
{ This is known to be good for Black since the 1984 Karpov-Kasparov match. Even though White can take on c4 without losing a tempo with the bishop, it is important for Black to start immediate counterplay in the center. }
8. e4 { If  8.e3  then again  8...c5 } 8... c5 { Attacking White's center. } 9.
d5
{ This is the ambitious try. In case of  9.dxc5  Nd7  Black will take the c5-pawn with good play, or after  10.c6  bxc6  11.Bxc4  O-O  with ...Ne5 next. He can even claim to be better because of the bishop pair and his activity. }
9... exd5 10. e5
{ After  10.Nxd5  Nc6  Black has smooth development with ...O-O, ...Bg4 @@StartBracket@@fighting for the d4-square@@EndBracket@@ and so on. }
10... Bg5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Nxd5 { is not very good for White in view of }
12... Rh4
{ A nice rook maneuver, typical for this line. The rook enters the game via the 4th rank, the main idea is ...Rd4. This development of the rook must always be kept in mind whenever White takes the bishop on g5. }
