[Black "White Plays 7.e4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e4
{ White's immediate central play is harmless because he is not yet fully developed to support this kind of direct play. }
7... dxe4
{ Black takes on e4 and quickly develops, putting pressure on the d4-pawn. } 8.
Nxe4 Nc6
{ Quick development is important here. Black attacks d4 so White must take on f6, but this will speed up Black's development as the queen will come to f6, liberating the eighth rank which will make Black's long castle quicker. }
9. Nxf6+
{ In case of  9.d5  Ne5  Black is fine, as White voluntarily opened the long diagonal and the pawn on b2 becoming somewhat tender. }
9... Qxf6
{ Black will now finish development by ...b6 and ...Bb7 and may even think for an advantage by putting pressure on the d4-pawn. }
10. Qd3
{ White tries to pose concrete problems. In case of  10.Be2  O-O  followed by ...Rd8. He will have problems defending the pawn on d4. }
10... b6 { The bishop will be very active on the long diagonal. } 11. Qe4 Bb7
12. Ne5
{ White's play looks dubious, neglecting development, but it is a direct attempt to punish Black. }
12... Na5
{ This is the simplest, gaining tempo to castle long. Then the knight can return to c6. }
13. Qe3 O-O-O
{ Black is very comfortable here. After ...Nc6, he will attack both the knight on e5 and the d4-pawn. }
