[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.Qb3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Qb3
{ White attacks d5 and wants to proceed with e4, so Black immediately wins a tempo by taking on c4 and castling, thus being ready for play in the centre. }
7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O
{ Black castled and now wants to develop with ...b6 and ...Bb7, but he may also vary his plans depending on how White continues. }
9. Ne4 Be7
{ Black keeps the bishop pair. His position is solid and he can calmly finish development. }
10. Rc1 { Putting pressure on the c-file. } 10... Qd5
{ Black wants to exchange White's active queen and dull White's play along the c-file. If White takes on d5, then the familiar Carlsbad structure will be very comfortable for Black because White will not find it easy to play the usual minority attack given Black's good control over b4 @@StartBracket@@which can be further increased by ...a5@@EndBracket@@ . }
11. Nfd2 Qxc4
{ By exchanging the queens, Black gains a tempo to develop the bishop along the long diagonal. The endgame is equal, but Black can be happy about it since he has the bishop pair. }
12. Nxc4 b6 13. e3 Bb7
{ Black has easy play here - the Ne4 is attacked and Black will follow up with .. .Nd7 and ...c5, opening the game for the bishops and eliminate the backward c7-pawn in the process. }
