[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.Qb3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. Qb3
{ White attacks d5 and wants to proceed with e4, so Black immediately wins a tempo by taking on c4 and castling, thus being ready for play in the centre. }
7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O
{ Black castled and now wants to develop with ...b6 and ...Bb7, but he may also vary his plans depending on how White continues. }
9. e4 a6
{ Black prepares an expansion on the queenside with ...b5 and ...c5. He will also develop the bishop on b7 in the process. }
10. e5
{ This is the critical approach because if left alone, Black will push both ...b5 and ...c5. With the bishop coming to b7, he will have excellent play. With the pawn advance, White tries to create threats on the kingside, but as we will see, Black has more than enough resources to deal with them. }
10... Be7 11. Qe2
{ White's plan is to put the queen on e4 from where she prevents the move ...b5 and the development of the bishop to b7 and also looks towards Black's kingside. He then wants to continue with Bd3 and O-O-O. }
11... c5 { Black attacks White's centre. } 12. Qe4 cxd4
{ Black naturally takes on d4. } 13. Bd3 g6 14. Nxd4 Qb6
{ Black develops the queen with tempo. } 15. O-O-O Bd7
{ Preparing ...Nc6 without allowing the wrecking of the structure after Nxc6 bxc6. }
16. h4 { In this line, White tries to break down Black's kingside by h5. }
16... Nc6 { But Black's play in the centre is faster. } 17. Bc2
{ Defending the knight. } 17... Nxd4
{ Eliminating the centralised knight and liberating the c6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
18. Rxd4
{ Objectively speaking taking with the queen is better, but the endgame after   18.Qxd4  Qxd4  19.Rxd4  Bc6  is somewhat better for Black with his bishop pair and less extended position. }
18... Bc6 { The bishop is very active on the long diagonal. } 19. Qg4
{ If   19.Qf4  Kg7  is similar. Black will follow up with a rook move to d8. }
19... Kg7
{ This is the simplest, just eliminating any possible sacrifice. With a rook coming to d8 next, Black is slowly taking over the initiative as White's attack has come to a standstill. With further exchanges, Black's bishop pair will start to be felt more prominently. }
