7... dxc4 8. Qxc4 O-O
{ Black castled and now wants to develop with ...b6 and ...Bb7, but he may also vary his plans depending on how White continues. }
9. g3 b5
{ An unexpected move, a result of Gelfand's fantastic preparation demonstrated in the third game of his Candidates match final against Grischuk in 2011. Black sacrifices a pawn to gain a development advantage and open the files on the queenside. Coupled with the unopposed and strong bishop on f6, this will give him excellent play along the open b and c-files. }
10. Qb3 { This is rather tame, after } 10... c5
{ Black has great play. He wants to open the position for his bishops and the b and c-files for his rooks and queen. White is underdeveloped and cannot keep the position closed, which means that Black's initiative will be very strong. A sample line is }
11. dxc5 Qa5 { Activating the queen and pinning the knight on c3. } 12. Bg2 Bb7
13. O-O Na6
{ If Black recaptures the pawn, he will be better because of the strong bishop pair @@StartBracket@@and the unopposed dark-squared bishop in particular@@EndBracket@@. But unfortunately for him, White cannot take on b5: }
14. Qxb5 { If   14.Nxb5?  Bd5  White loses a piece. } 14... Bxc3
{ Forcing White's next move. } 15. Qxb7 Nxc5 16. Qe7 Bxb2 17. Rab1 Bf6
{ Black returned the material and is better here because White cannot defend the a2-pawn. }
18. Qd6 Rad8 { Removing the rook from the long diagonal. } 19. Qf4 Qxa2
{ With a clear pawn up. } *

