[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.e3, 8.Qd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, in case we castle short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Qd2
{ White wants to castle long. } 8... dxc4
{ Even though this allows White to take on c4 in one go, it is important to start counterplay with ...c5 as soon as possible. The reaction is the same as in the7.Qd2 line. }
9. Bxc4 Nd7
{ This was an important idea by Portisch at the time. Black wants to push ...c5. }
10. O-O
{ This is harmless, but it's instructive to see how Black should treat these positions. }
10... c5
{ Please note Black's following play in the early middlegame as it is a good example of how Black should develop in these symmetrical structures: the knight on d7 should liberate the d7-square for the bishop and then a possible set-up is to play ...Qe7, ...Rfd8 and ...Be8, safely defending f7 and connecting the rooks without the bishop in between. Another idea is to play ...Qb8 and ...Rd8@@StartBracket@@c8@@EndBracket@@ and then drop the bishop to e8. A sample line is }
11. Rfd1 cxd4
{ Now the knight doesn't need to defend the c5-pawn anymore and can move. } 12.
Nxd4 Nb6 { The knight liberates the d7-square. } 13. Be2 Bd7
{ The bishop is developed. } 14. Bf3 Qb8
{ Patience is a good trait to have in these positions. Black has no weaknesses so he can calmly play moves like this one as White has nothing to attack. He will play ...Rd8 next and drop the bishop to e8. }
*

