[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Qd2
{ White wants to castle long. } 8... dxc4
{ Even though this allows White to take on c4 in one go, it is important to start counterplay with ...c5 as soon as possible. The reaction is the same as in the7.Qd2 line. }
9. Bxc4 Nd7
{ This was an important idea by Portisch at the time. Black wants to push ...c5. }
10. O-O-O
{ If   10.Ne4  then simply  10...Be7  Castling long is an ambitious attempt by White. }
10... c5 { The usual move to free Black's position. } 11. h4
{ White indends to attack with g4-g5. } 11... b5
{ But Black is faster! With this pawn sacrifice, Black wrestles the initiative from White. }
12. Nxb5
{ This is too dangerous for White, but also illustrative of Black's attacking possibilities. }
12... cxd4 { Black also opens the c-file. } 13. Nbxd4 Qb6
{ Soon enough, all of Black's pieces will be looking down White's queenside. He will play ...Bb7 and put the rooks on b8 and c8 while the knight can join via the c5-square, all of which will give him a strong attack. }
*

