1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Qb3 dxc4
{ The pawn on d5 was hanging, so Black takes on c4 to be able to prepare ... c5 as soon as possible. }
9. Bxc4
{ Note that the other recapture,   9.Qxc4  b6  transposes to the line   @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  9.e3 }
9... c5 10. d5 exd5 11. Nxd5
{ If   11.Bxd5  then  11...Na6  with the idea of ...Nc7 to attack the bishop on d5 and control the d5-square. }
11... Nc6 { Black threatens ...Na5. } 12. Qb5
{ Escaping the double attack and attacking c5, though the b2-pawn will be en prise if the queen leaves the b-file. }
12... Nb4
{ Challenging the centralised knight. The pawn sacrifice is temporary as after }
13. Nxb4 cxb4 14. Qxb4 a5
{ The queen doesn't have a good square to go to. For example } 15. Qa3
{ If   15.Qb3  then  15...a4  followed by ...a3,  or   15.Qb5  Bd7  when again the queen cannot continue to defend the pawn on b2. }
15... b5 16. Rd1
{ If   16.Bxb5  Rb8  Black uses the b-file to great effect as the b2-pawn is lost. }
16... Qe8 { Defending the b5-pawn. } 17. Be2 b4
{ White's queen is seriously short of good squares. The line is a fine illustration of Black's dynamic possibilities on the queenside and the power of the dark-squared bishop. }
18. Qb3 Be6 19. Qc2 Rc8
{ Black includes a new piece in the attack with every move. } 20. Qb1 Qc6
{ Now the queen joins the attack. } 21. O-O Qc2
{ And White's queenside collapses. } *

