[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.e3, 8.cxd5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. cxd5
{ Transforming the structure to a Carlsbad, but one that is very comfortable for Black. }
8... exd5 9. b4
{ This prevents a possible ...c5 that would open the bishop on f6. } 9... c6
{ The usual move for Black in the Carlsbad structure. } 10. Be2
{ In case of   10.Bd3  Black can employ the same idea as in the line 9.Bd3 c5, only here he should start with  10...a5  first, and after  11.b5  c5  he gets a great position as White cannot take on c5 because the knight on c3 is undefended. }
10... Be7 { Black starts to attack White's expanded queenside immediately. }
11. a3
{ In case of   11.Rb1  b5  12.O-O  a5  Black takes over the initiative on the queenside. }
11... b5
{ This is very instructive as Black uses his dark-squared bishop to attack White's queenside. Black here takes over the initiative on the flank where White was doing the attacking. }
12. O-O a5 { Now the pawn on b4 is under attack. } 13. Rb1
{ In case of   13.bxa5  Nd7  followed by ...Qa5 and ...Nb6-c4. Black is overtaking the queenside. }
13... axb4 14. axb4 Na6 { White is driven on the defensive now. } 15. Na2 Bd6
{ The bishop on d6 liberates the e7-square for the queen and also controls the e5-square. }
16. Qc2 Bd7
{ Black is obviously very comfortable here, having pinned down White to the defence of the b4-pawn. He can continue with ...Qe7 and then a curious maneuver is ...Ra7, ...Nc7-a8-b6-c4. }
