1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Qc2 c5
{ Whenever possible, Black should strive to open the a1-h8 diagonal for the unopposed bishop on f6.  Here the immediate 8...dxc4 allows for the additional possibility of 9.Ne4, so it's better to start with the immediate 8...c5. }
9. dxc5
{ If   9.cxd5  then  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  exd5  with ... Nc6 next when the dark-squared bishop ensures good control over the dark squares. }
9... dxc4
{ Black eliminates the tension in the center and plans to capture the pawn on c5. }
10. Ne4 Nd7
{ Black continues to round up the c5-pawn. He can continue with ...Qa5 and ...Be7, when the pawn will fall. }
11. Rd1 Qa5+ { Moving away from the pin and following the plan. } 12. Nfd2 Be7
{ This is the simplest - Black takes the pawn on the next move. } 13. Qxc4 Bxc5
{ Of course, not   13...Nxc5?  14.b4  losing a piece. } 14. Nxc5 Qxc5
{ With easy equality for Black both in the middlegame @@StartBracket@@if White decides to keep the queens@@EndBracket@@ or the endgame - in both cases he develops quickly with ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
*

