[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 2: The Main Line: 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6"]
[Black "White Plays 7.e3, 8.h4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. h4
{ This is almost never played, but these moves need to be checked as it became fashionable to play h4 or g4 at some point in the opening. Note that the move  8.g4  would transpose to this line after  8...c5  9.h4 }
8... c5
{ Black replies according to the principle that an attack on the flank is best met by an attack in the centre. }
9. g4 { White continues to advance. } 9... cxd4
{ Black takes so that White doesn't have the option of dxc5 and then continues to develop. }
10. exd4 Nc6 { The pawn on d4 is under attack so White must sacrifice a pawn. }
11. g5 hxg5 12. hxg5 Bxg5
{ Black takes the pawn, but now must be a bit careful about the open h-file. }
13. Qd3 f5
{ Shutting the b1-h7 diagonal and liberating the f7-square for the king just in case. The immediate  13...Bh6  is risky in view of  14.Rxh6  gxh6  15.Qe3  Kh7  16.O-O-O  with a murky position where White has compensation in view of an attack and weak dark squares in Black's camp. }
14. Nxg5
{ In case of  14.cxd5  exd5  15.Bg2  Bh6  closing the h-file, Black is quite alright. The position is sharp, but Black has an extra pawn and the bishop pair so he can be optimistic about his chances. }
14... Qxg5 15. Qh3
{ If  15.Be2  then again  15...Bd7  preparing ...Ne7 and ...Kf7, stabilizing the position. }
15... Bd7
{ Black finishes development and his plan is to play ...Kf7 and ...Rh8, with or without the move ...Ne7 that stabilises the centre. Also, don't forget that the pawn on d4 is hanging. The reason for the developing move ...Bd7 is that the immediate   15...Nxd4  leads to a complete mess after  16.Rd1  Nc2  17.Ke2 }
16. Ne2
{ After  16.Rd1  then  16...Ne7  securing the pawn on d5 followed by ...Kf7 with a very solid position for Black who is still a pawn up. }
16... Qg4
{ Black would like to exchange queens as apart from being a pawn up it's obvious that White's activity lies on the h-file. With this move, he also attacks the pawn on d4. }
17. cxd5
{ If  17.Qc3  Rac8  it's clear that White abandoned the idea of an attack so it's difficult for him to find compensation. }
17... exd5 18. Bg2 Be6
{ Defending the central pawn. The position is sharp but Black is a pawn up and his king is relatively safe. He can play ...Kf7 threatening ...Rh8 and would also like to exchange queens. }
*

