1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Rc1 dxc4
{ A relatively fresh idea that simplifies Black's task. The idea is similar to the lines after 7/8.Qd2, and 8.Qb3 when Black doesn't wait for White to move the light-squared bishop to take on c4 but takes immediately and proceeds with ...Nd7 and ...c5. }
9. Bxc4 Nd7 { Following the plan. } 10. Ne4
{ White wants to take on f6, but this only simplifies the position and this is in Black's favour, who has less space. }
10... c5 { The planned push. } 11. Nxf6+
{ If White takes on c5 then the pawn on b2 will fall, for example   11.Nxc5  Nxc5  12.dxc5  Bxb2  which is in Black's favor as he has the bishop pair and the better structure. }
11... Qxf6 { The knight remains on d7 to defend the c5-pawn. } 12. O-O Rd8
{ Defending the knight and putting the rook on the d-file that can be opened at any moment. Black is now planning ...b6 and ...Bb7. He is comfortable as he manages to finish his development without problems. }
