1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3
{ This is the main option, but White can try other moves as well, even though they have long been proven to be rather harmless. Note that the move  7.Qd3  doesn't have independent value as after  7...dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O  we have a transposition to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp2pp1/4pb1p/3p4/2PP4/2N2N2/PP2PPPP/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Qb3  dxc4  8.Qxc4  O-O }
7... O-O { Now again White has many options. } 8. Rc1 dxc4
{ A relatively fresh idea that simplifies Black's task. The idea is similar to the lines after 7/8.Qd2, and 8.Qb3 when Black doesn't wait for White to move the light-squared bishop to take on c4 but takes immediately and proceeds with ...Nd7 and ...c5. }
9. Bxc4 Nd7 { Following the plan. } 10. O-O c5
{ Black achieved the ...c5 push and now he only needs to solve the problem of the development of his light-squared bishop. }
11. Qe2
{ This is an ambitious choice. White accepts an IQP in an attempt to have more active piece play. }
11... cxd4
{ Black needs to take on d4 so that he can move the knight from d7. } 12. exd4
{ After  12.Nxd4  Nb6  followed by ...Bd7 and ...Qe7. Black has no problems. }
12... Nb6
{ The usual move in these positions, the knight moves from d7 and attacks the bishop on c4. }
13. Bd3 g6
{ Black shuts the b1-h7 diagonal and with a good dark-squared bishop, he is ensured against any attacks. }
14. Be4
{ White tries to slow down Black's development. Otherwise Black would have played ...Bd7-c6. }
14... Rb8
{ Black calmly defends the pawn on b7 and prepares the development of the bishop on d7. }
15. Rfd1 Bd7
{ Black finished development. If he is allowed to play ...Qe7, ...Rfd8 and ...Be8 @@StartBracket@@or . ..Bc6@@EndBracket@@ he can slowly start play against the IQP. }
16. Ne5
{ Increasing White's activity. A move like  16.Qe3  is met by  16...Bg7  and the according to plan: ... Qe7, ...Rfd8 etc. }
16... Qe7 { Black continues with the plan. } 17. Qf3
{ White continues to put pressure. } 17... Be8
{ Defending the pawn on b7 and preparing ...Nd7 to chase away the knight from e5. }
18. g3
{ White ran out of active moves and simply opens some luft for his king. }
18... Bg7
{ The last preparatory move before ...Nd7, as the immediate  18...Nd7  is met by  19.Nxd7  Bxd7  20.Bxb7  and the queen must defend the bishop on f6 and Black cannot play ...Qb4. }
19. h4 Nd7 { Black slowly liberates his position. } 20. Nxd7 Bxd7 21. d5
{ In case of  21.Bxb7  Qb4  Black attacks both the bishop on b7 and the pawn on b2, which he will capture on the next move. }
21... Qb4 { Activating the queen. } 22. dxe6 Bxe6
{ With an equal position. White's activity should compensate for Black's pair of bishops. }
