1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bf4
{ This appears to be a strange retreat, giving Black a full tempo compared to the line 5.Bf4. It is not without an idea though. The idea is to try to use the h6-pawn as a hook for an upcoming attack with g4-g5. }
6... O-O { Black develops normally, like in the 5.Bf4 line. } 7. e3 Nbd7
{ The same move as in the line with 5.Bf4, preparing ...c5. } 8. g4
{ Here we see White's idea. He wants to push g5 and open the g-file for a direct attack on the king. }
8... dxc4
{ With this capture, Black liberates the d5-square so the knight from f6 can move away from the attack after g5. }
9. g5 { This is more aggressive, but after } 9... hxg5 10. Bxg5
{ The other recapture   10.Nxg5  is met by  10...Nd5  attacking both the knight on g5 and the bishop on f4, when taking on f4 would wreck White's structure. }
10... b5
{ Black defends the pawn on c4 and starts immediate counterplay on the queenside. He also allows the bishop from c8 to come to the long diagonal on b7. }
11. Rg1
{ Moving away from the long diagonal. Taking the pawn is good for Black,   11.Nxb5  Rb8  and Black takes over the initiative. }
11... Bb7
{ Black if fully developed and ready to start his own active play by ...b4 and ...c5. He has nothing to worry about on the kingside as a move like Bh6 can be met by ...Ne8 and White cannot include more pieces to support his kingside activity. }
*

