{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bh4 O-O
{ Black finished with the development of the kingside and now White needs to decide how to proceed. }
7. e3 { This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives. } 7... Nbd7
{ This has been used by Kramnik and he had excellent results with it. This move, together with the fact that the alternatives like the Lasker Variation with   7...Ne4  and the Tartakower Variation with   7...b6  are perfectly viable, are the main reasons why the move 5.Bg5 dropped in popularity and is less seen nowadays. }
8. Qc2 c5 { Attacking White's center in the usual manner. } 9. cxd5 Nxd5
{ As usual, Black avoids an isolated pawn and welcomes exchanges. } 10. Bxe7
Nxe7
{ Black takes with knight in order to avoid an IQP after   10...Qxe7  11.Nxd5  exd5 }
11. Be2 cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 so that the knight on d7 doesn't have to protect the c5-pawn anymore. The knight can move from d7 to liberate the square for the bishop. }
12. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Following the plan. Black is one step from finishing development. } 13. O-O
Bd7
{ The bishop is out, so next Black needs to move the queen from d8 to connect the rooks. }
14. Rfd1 Qa5 { Black plans to place his rooks on c8 and d8. } 15. Bf3
{ White forces one rook to defend the pawn on b7. } 15... Rab8
{ Defending the pawn on b7 and removing the rook from the long diagonal. Black will play ...Rfc8 next and if necessary the bishop can drop back to e8. Black has a very solid position without weaknesses. }
