1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5
{ The fact that Black has several good options for how to deal with the mainline options in the QGD has caused a significant decrease in its popularity. }
5... h6
{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bh4 O-O
{ Black finished with the development of the kingside and now White needs to decide how to proceed. }
7. e3 { This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives. } 7... Nbd7
{ This has been used by Kramnik and he had excellent results with it. This move, together with the fact that the alternatives like the Lasker Variation with   7...Ne4  and the Tartakower Variation with   7...b6  are perfectly viable, are the main reasons why the move 5.Bg5 dropped in popularity and is less seen nowadays. }
8. Qc2 c5 { Attacking White's center in the usual manner. } 9. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The natural recapture, as the bishop is needed on e7 so that the knight on f6 is not pinned. }
10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5
{ After   11.Bxe7  Nxe7  play is similar to the other lines - the bishop will come out to d7 and the queen to b6 to connect the rooks. }
11... Bxh4
{ Black takes the bishop on h4 and now wants to take on d5 with his queen. }
12. Qxc5 exd5
{ This is forced as the queen must defend the bishop on h4. Now Black's activity and White's lag in development give Black compensation for the IQP. }
13. Nxh4
{ This is forced as the bishop can become extremely dangerous, for example   13.Rd1  Be7  14.Qxd5?  Bb4  forcing  15.Ke2  Qf6  with decisive attack. }
13... Qxh4 14. Be2
{ Taking on d5 is way too risky,   14.Qxd5  Be6  with the rooks coming to d8 and c8. The threat to give a check from b4 is very dangerous for White. }
14... d4 { The best move, liquidating to an equal endgame. } 15. Qxd4
{ The only move, as after   15.exd4?  Re8  Black is winning as White cannot get away with the king from the center. }
15... Qxd4 16. exd4 Be6
{ This is the precise move, pinning down White to the defence of the a2-pawn and winning a tempo for the doubling of the rooks on the d-file. }
17. O-O Rfd8 { Black simply doubles on the d-file and returns the pawn. } 18.
Rfd1 Rd7 { With ...Rad8 and ...Rxd4 next. } *

