{ Black immediately chases away the bishop and makes a useful move - the luft for the king, if he castles short, will always be useful. }
6. Bh4 O-O
{ Black finished with the development of the kingside and now White needs to decide how to proceed. }
7. e3 { This is by far the main move, but there are alternatives. } 7... Nbd7
{ This has been used by Kramnik and he had excellent results with it. This move, together with the fact that the alternatives like the Lasker Variation with   7...Ne4  and the Tartakower Variation with   7...b6  are perfectly viable, are the main reasons why the move 5.Bg5 dropped in popularity and is less seen nowadays. }
8. Rc1
{ The exchange on d5 should be met by the thematic   8.cxd5  Nxd5  avoiding a favorable Exchange Variation for White after   8...exd5  9.Bd3 }
8... c5
{ This thematic push ensures Black gets an equal game. Despite this, the whole line became popular only after Kramnik took it up and achieved excellent results in the second half of the 2010s. }
9. dxc5 dxc4
{ Striving to clarify the position in the center by symmetrically taking on the c-file. }
10. Bxc4
{ Breaking the symmetry doesn't bring much to White,   10.c6  bxc6  11.Bxc4  Nb6  followed by ...c5 and ... Bb7. This gives Black comfortable play, similar to the lines with 8.Qc2 from the chapter  The Main Line 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6.  The pawn on c5 controls the d4-square and Black has good development and can jump to d5 and possibly use the b-file. }
10... Nxc5 11. O-O a6
{ Black wants to grab some space on the queenside by ...b5, and at the same time, solve the problem of the light-squared bishop by developing it on b7. }
12. Be2 b5 { Shows Black's idea. } 13. Ne5 Bb7
{ Black has excellent development already. } 14. Bf3 Qc7
{ Black wins a tempo by attacking the knight on e5 and wants to get his rooks into the game. }
15. Bxb7 Qxb7
{ Now the queen took over the task to control the light squares. With the rooks coming to c8 and d8, Black has easy play. }
