{ Breaking the symmetry doesn't bring much to White,   10.c6  bxc6  11.Bxc4  Nb6  followed by ...c5 and ... Bb7. This gives Black comfortable play, similar to the lines with 8.Qc2 from the chapter  The Main Line 5.Bg5 h6 6.Bxf6.  The pawn on c5 controls the d4-square and Black has good development and can jump to d5 and possibly use the b-file. }
