{ Black wants to grab some space on the queenside by ...b5, and at the same time, solve the problem of the light-squared bishop by developing it on b7. }
12. Nd4 Nfe4
{ Forcing the exchange of the bishops helps Black place the queen on the ideal square e7 from where she doesn't interfere with play along the central lines. }
13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qc2
{ In case of   14.Nxe4  Nxe4  15.Qc2  Nf6  followed by ...Bd7. Black is fine. }
14... Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Na4
{ Removing the knight from the unstable c5-square and gaining tempo for the development of the bishop. }
16. Qc2 Bd7
{ Black finished development and equalized without problems. Please take a look at the model game, Matlakov-Kramnik, to see another example how Black can play for a win in these simplified positions. }
