[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "White Plays 4.Bf4, 6.Rc1 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. Rc1
{ By putting the rook on the c-file, White wants to take on d5 and force Black to recapture with the pawn as taking with a knight would lose the pawn on c7 after Nxd5 and Bxc7. }
6... c5 { Therefore Black strikes in the centre immediately. } 7. dxc5 Qa5
{ Pinning the knight on c3 and liberating the d8-square for the rook. } 8. Nf3
{ In case of   8.Bd6  Bxd6  9.cxd6  Rd8  10.Nf3  Rxd6  we have a transposition. }
8... Rd8 { Now Black threatens to take on c4. } 9. Qc2
{ With this move, White removes the queen from the d-file. } 9... Nc6
{ Black develops first as the pawn on c5 will not run away. } 10. a3
{ Covering the b4-square and perhaps intending b4 to defend the pawn on c5. }
10... dxc4
{ Black avoids possible b4 and lures the bishop to c4. This is because when Black takes on c5 with the queen, the bishop is attacked. }
11. Bxc4 Qxc5 12. Be2 Qf5
{ The endgame is fine for Black as he can calmly develop with ...Bd7 and ... Rac8. }
13. O-O
{ After   13.Qxf5  exf5  Black has the e6-square for the bishop and the pawn on f5 gives him good control over the e4-square. }
13... Qxc2 14. Rxc2 Bd7
{ With an equal endgame as Black successfully manages to finish development. }
*

