[Black "White Plays 4.Bf4, 6.Rc1 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. Rc1
{ By putting the rook on the c-file, White wants to take on d5 and force Black to recapture with the pawn as taking with a knight would lose the pawn on c7 after Nxd5 and Bxc7. }
6... c5 { Therefore Black strikes in the centre immediately. } 7. dxc5 Qa5
{ Pinning the knight on c3 and liberating the d8-square for the rook. } 8. Nf3
{ In case of   8.Bd6  Bxd6  9.cxd6  Rd8  10.Nf3  Rxd6  we have a transposition. }
8... Rd8 { Now Black threatens to take on c4. } 9. Bd6 Bxd6 10. cxd6 Rxd6
{ Black returned the pawn and now needs to finish development. } 11. Be2 Rd8
{ The rook is now defended by the queen and Black threatens to take on c4. }
12. cxd5 Nxd5 { Now the threat is ...Nxc3. } 13. Qb3
{ In case of   13.Qc2  Black exchanges everything on c3 and develops the queenside:  13...Nxc3  14.Qxc3  Qxc3  15.Rxc3  Nc6  with ...Bd7 next. }
13... Nc6 { Black develops naturally. } 14. O-O Qb4
{ A good move, seeking exchange of queens. Black wants to exchange them, then take on c3 or move the knight from d5 and develop the bishop to d7. A sample line is }
15. Rfd1 Qxb3 16. axb3 Nxc3 { Avoiding a creation of an IQP on d5. } 17. Rxd8+
Nxd8 18. bxc3 Bd7 19. Ne5 Be8 { With an equal endgame. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "White Plays 4.Bf4, 6.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. Qc2
{ White wants to take on d5 when again Black won't be able to take on d5 with a knight because the pawn on c7 hangs. }
6... c5
{ Black strikes in the centre immediately, as after  6...Nbd7  7.cxd5  exd5  forced, otherwise Black loses the pawn on c7  8.Bd3  White has an ideal version of theExchange Variation. }
7. dxc5 Na6
{ Black still wants to recapture on c5 with a knight, as in the case with ...Nbd7. }
8. Rd1 Nxc5
{ Black takes on c5 with the knight and now has excellent control over the e4-square, where one of the knights can land. This will be particularly important once Black plays ...Qa5, pinning the knight on c3. }
9. cxd5 exd5
{ The IQP on d5 is not a major worry as Black has excellent activity. } 10. Nf3
Qa5 { Pinning the knight and threatening ... Ne4. } 11. Be2 Nfe4
{ The knight on c5 is more active than the one on f6, that is why the knight from f6 goes to e4. }
12. O-O
{ Taking the pawn on d5 leads to an equal position after   12.Rxd5  Be6  as the pawn on a2 falls after exchanging the knights on c3 when the rook moves, while  13.Qxe4  Qxc3  14.bxc3  Nxe4  15.Re5  Nxc3  returns the material with equality. }
12... Nxc3 { Creating a backward pawn on c3. } 13. bxc3 Be6
{ The position is dynamically balanced. The pawns on c3 and d5 balance each other out. Black's play is aimed against the pawn on c3, using the c-file and the light squares, for example putting a rook on c8 and then ...Ne4 @@StartBracket@@or ...Na4@@EndBracket@@. }
