1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. Qc2
{ White wants to take on d5 when again Black won't be able to take on d5 with a knight because the pawn on c7 hangs. }
6... c5
{ Black strikes in the centre immediately, as after  6...Nbd7  7.cxd5  exd5  forced, otherwise Black loses the pawn on c7  8.Bd3  White has an ideal version of theExchange Variation. }
7. dxc5 Na6
{ Black still wants to recapture on c5 with a knight, as in the case with ...Nbd7. }
8. Nf3 Nxc5 9. Be2
{ White rushes to develop the kingside. Note that   9.Rd1  Qa5  10.cxd5  exd5  transposes to the line starting with 8.Rd1.  The move   9.cxd5  is harmless as after  9...Nxd5  10.Nxd5  Qxd5  Black has easy play. }
9... dxc4
{ This capture is especially good when White has spent a move on his bishop since now he has to move that same bishop again, basically granting a tempo to Black. }
10. Bxc4 a6
{ Preparing to win more time by attacking the exposed bishop by ...b5 and then develop with ...Bb7. }
11. a4 b6 { Continuing the plan to finish development by ...Bb7. } 12. O-O Bb7
13. Qe2
{ In case of   12.Rfd1  Qc8  the queen will come to c6 and the rook from f8 on d8. }
13... Qc8 { The queen aims for c6. } 14. Rfd1 Qc6
{ This maneuver is essential in this line. Black is very comfortable because the knight on f3 is pinned so the queen cannot be attacked. Afterwards, Black will put the rooks in the center. }
