[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "White Plays 4.Bf4, 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. a3
{ White covers the b4-square in advance to prevent a check from b4. } 6... Nbd7
{ Black continues along the usual lines. } 7. Nb5
{ This was White's idea. Now there is no check from b4 and Black needs to defend the c7-pawn. }
7... Ne8
{ The only way to defend the pawn, but there are other positive sides to the knight on e8. }
8. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black lures the bishop to c4 so that he can play ...Nd6 to attack both the knight and the bishop. }
9. Bxc4 Nd6
{ Here we see the positive side to the knight on e8. Black forces an exchange of one minor piece. }
10. Nxd6 { This is natural, not wasting time, but after } 10... cxd6
{ Black has easy equality. With one pair of minor pieces exchanged, he doesn't suffer from lack of space and develops comfortably with ...Nf6 and ...Bd7. }
11. Bd3 Nf6 12. e4 Bd7
{ Black finished development of their minor pieces. Next, he will develop the queen to b6 and one rook will occupy the open c-file. }
13. O-O { If   13.Qb3  then  13...Bc6  putting pressure on White's center. }
13... Qb6
{ The queen is active on b6. Black's plan is to play ...Rfc8 and then possibly ...a5-a4 to fix White's queenside. What is important is that neither pawn push in the center, e5 or d5, isn't dangerous for Black. The move e5 allows the knight to slot in on d5, while d5 is more difficult to achieve when Black can either take on d5 or push ...e5 and then strive to organize the ...f5-push. }
