[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "White Plays 4.Bf4, 6.a3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Bf4
{ This is possible and here we take a look at various move-orders that don't tranpose to the main lines after 4.Nf3. They are usually aimed against the line with 6...Nbd7. }
4... Nf6 5. e3 O-O
{ Black plays the usual developing moves and here White has a choice. } 6. a3
{ White covers the b4-square in advance to prevent a check from b4. } 6... Nbd7
{ Black continues along the usual lines. } 7. Nb5
{ This was White's idea. Now there is no check from b4 and Black needs to defend the c7-pawn. }
7... Ne8
{ The only way to defend the pawn, but there are other positive sides to the knight on e8. }
8. Nf3 dxc4
{ Black lures the bishop to c4 so that he can play ...Nd6 to attack both the knight and the bishop. }
9. Bxc4 Nd6
{ Here we see the positive side to the knight on e8. Black forces an exchange of one minor piece. }
10. Bd3 Nxb5 { Black gains tempo for the ...c5-push. } 11. Bxb5 c5
{ Black achieved the ...c5-push and now it only remains to solve the problem of the bishop on c8. }
12. O-O { Avoiding the check from a5. } 12... cxd4
{ With the disappearance of the pawn on c5, the knight on d7 can move to liberate the d7-square for the bishop. }
13. Qxd4
{ Taking with knight is met by   13.Nxd4  a6  and in view of the threat of ...e5, White must take on d7,  14.Bxd7  Bxd7  with easy play for Black who has the bishop pair. }
13... Qb6 { Forcing the exchange of queens. } 14. Qxb6 Nxb6
{ Now Black wants to develop the bishop to d7. } 15. Rfc1
{ A curious move that has a deep tactical prophylaxis in mind. Why not play the natural   15.Rac1? }
15... Nd5
{ We saw the reason why the move   15...Rd8  doesn't work in this case @@StartBracket@@see the line 15.Rac1 for the details@@EndBracket@@ so Black first plays a move the controls the c7-square and then plays ...Rd8. }
16. Bg3 Rd8 { With the idea of ...Bd7. } 17. Bc4
{ After   17.e4  Nf6  18.Bc7  Rf8  19.e5  Nd5  the untouchable knight controls everything and Black will soon develop after ...a6 and ...Bd7. }
17... b6
{ Black wants to develop the bishop on b7 now in order to avoid a creation of an IQP after   17...Bd7  18.Bxd5  exd5  19.Rc7  with strong pressure for White. }
18. Bb5 { The bishop changes its mind and now wants to come to c6, but after }
18... Bd7 { Black successfully exchanges the bishops and equalizes the game. }
