[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
11. Rc1
{ This is dubious as Black can take advantage of the light-square weaknesses on the queenside after }
11... Bd7
{ The threat of ...Ba4 is very strong, so White practically must take the pawn on d5. }
12. Qxd5 Rc8
{ Defending the knight on c5 and threatening ...Nd3. Another threat that is hard to deal with is the move ...Qb6, not only attacking the pawn on b2 but also liberating the d8-square for the rook. }
13. e4
{ Defending the rook on c1. In case of   13.Rd1  Qb6  with ...Rfd8 next. White's is on the verge of defeat. }
13... Qb6 { Attacking the pawn on b2 and threatening ...Rfd8. } 14. b4 Be6
{ A very important move, as the knight on c5 is practically taboo. In the model game, Duda-Grischuk, Black failed to remember his analysis and played the inferior   14...Rfd8 }
15. bxc5
{ Taking the knight loses, but it's a good illustrative line to show Black's attacking potential: }
15... Bxc5 { Threatening ...Bxf2. } 16. Qd2
{ Defending the rook on c1 and the pawn on f2. } 16... Bxa3
{ Threatening both the rook on c1 and ...Bb4. } 17. Rxc8 Rxc8
{ Black is winning here as he easily attacks via the deserted queenside, while White is playing with the bishop on f1 and the rook on h1. }
*

