{ If   18.Qe2  Bb4  wins for Black as White loses too much material. } 18...
Rxc5 { Black wins thanks to his overwhelming attack via the queenside. } 19.
Bd3 Qa5+ 20. Ke2 Rxd3 { A nice shot. } 21. Kxd3
{ Or   21.Qxd3  Bc4  winning the queen. } 21... Rc3+ { Winning the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.a3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
11. Rc1
{ This is dubious as Black can take advantage of the light-square weaknesses on the queenside after }
11... Bd7
{ The threat of ...Ba4 is very strong, so White practically must take the pawn on d5. }
12. Qxd5 Rc8
{ Defending the knight on c5 and threatening ...Nd3. Another threat that is hard to deal with is the move ...Qb6, not only attacking the pawn on b2 but also liberating the d8-square for the rook. }
13. e4
{ Defending the rook on c1. In case of   13.Rd1  Qb6  with ...Rfd8 next. White's is on the verge of defeat. }
13... Qb6 { Attacking the pawn on b2 and threatening ...Rfd8. } 14. b4 Be6
{ A very important move, as the knight on c5 is practically taboo. In the model game, Duda-Grischuk, Black failed to remember his analysis and played the inferior   14...Rfd8 }
15. Qd4 Rfd8 { All of Black's pieces are included in the attack now. } 16. Qe3
h6
{ A difficult move that needs to be memorized! Black threatens ...g5, to remove the bishop on f4 from defending both the queen on e3 and the rook on c1. }
17. h4 { White must prevent ...g5. } 17... a5
{ Attacking White's queenside is a key theme for Black in this line. } 18. bxc5
Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Rxc5 { Threatening ...Qb1. } 20. Bd3 Qb3
{ Soon Black will return the material with interest. } 21. O-O
{ Finally reaching safety for the king. After   21.Qxc5  Qxd3  with ideas like ...Rc8 and ...Bc4, Black is winning. }
21... Rc3
{ The bishop on d3 is lost, so the best White can do is try to get something in return. }
22. Nd2 Qxa3 23. Nb1
{ With this maneuver, White manages to be only a pawn down. Still, after }
23... Rdxd3 24. Qxd3 Rxd3 25. Nxa3 Rxa3
{ The endgame gives Black excellent winning chances. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.a3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
11. Be5
{ White controls the long diagonal and defends the pawn on b2 in advance. Note that in case of   11.Be2  Bf6  12.Be5  we have a transposition to 11. Be5 Bf6 12. Be2. }
11... Bf6 { Black immediately challenges the centralized bishop. } 12. Be2
{ This is inferior as after the exchange on e5, Black gains a tempo with ...Re8. }
12... Bxe5 13. Nxe5 Re8
{ Gaining a tempo as the rook is useful on the e-file. } 14. Nf3 Qb6
{ In these IQP positions, Black is very active and this gives him good play. }
15. Rc1
{ Of course, the exchange   15.Qxd5  Qxb2  is favorable for Black who exchanged his IQP for the pawn on b2, obtaining a queenside majority. }
15... Ne6
{ Black renews the threat to take on b2 by removing the knight from the attacked c5-square. From e6, the knight also controls the blockading d4-square and can help the ...d4-push. }
16. Qd2
{ Playing   16.b4  will always give Black counterplay based on ...a5, for example  16...Rd8  threatening ...d4  17.Nd4  a5 }
16... Bd7
{ Black finishes development. He wants to play ...Rad8 and be ready to push ...d4. }
17. O-O { Again,   17.Qxd5  Qxb2  is good for Black. } 17... Rad8
{ The rook is behind the pawn and Black is fully prepared for central play. }
18. Nd4
{ This allows simplifications, but otherwise White doesn't really have useful moves. For example the natural   18.Rfd1  is met by  18...Ba4  19.Re1  d4  with Black solving their problems. }
18... Nxd4 19. exd4 Rxe2 { A simple combination that simplifies the position. }
20. Qxe2 Bb5 21. Qd2 Bxf1 22. Kxf1 Re8 { With an equal position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.a3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
11. Be5
{ White controls the long diagonal and defends the pawn on b2 in advance. Note that in case of   11.Be2  Bf6  12.Be5  we have a transposition to 11. Be5 Bf6 12. Be2. }
11... Bf6 { Black immediately challenges the centralized bishop. } 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 13. Qd4
{ White seeks the endgame in order to try to take advantage of the IQP on d5. While the endgame after the exchange on d4 is drawn with sensible play by Black, he is not forced to go for it. }
13... Qd6
{ Black now wants to combine the threat of ...Ne6 and ...d4 with active piece play, while the immediate threat is ...Nb3. }
14. Bd3
{ White defends against the threat of ...Nb3 indirectly, but the exchange of his light-squared bishop weakens the light squares. }
14... Nxd3+ { Of course,   14...Nb3  would be met by  15.Qh4  and then Rd1. }
15. Qxd3 Qf6 { Black would like to exchange his IQP for the pawn on b2. } 16.
Nd4
{ White's only idea in the position is to try to play against the IQP, maintaining a blockade on d4. In case of   16.Qd4  Black can play  16...Qa6  preventing castling. }
16... Qg5
{ Black creates enough counterplay due to the weakened white kingside. White now has problems to defend the g2-pawn. }
17. g3 { The only way, as   17.O-O  Bh3  wins the exchange for Black. } 17...
Bh3
{ Black prevents White's castling. It is clear that with an insecure king, White cannot hope to concentrate on the play against the IQP.  Black will always be able to create play against the king in the center by putting a rook on the e-file and possibly ...h5-h4. In case White plays f3, Black will likely double his rooks on the e-file. }
*

