{ White seeks the endgame in order to try to take advantage of the IQP on d5. While the endgame after the exchange on d4 is drawn with sensible play by Black, he is not forced to go for it. }
13... Qd6
{ Black now wants to combine the threat of ...Ne6 and ...d4 with active piece play, while the immediate threat is ...Nb3. }
14. Rd1 Rd8 { Defending the pawn on d5. } 15. Be2
{ White must try to finish development. } 15... Bf5
{ Black develops naturally and threatens ...Bc2. } 16. Qc3
{ This also prevents ...Bc2, but the queen is somewhat exposed on the c-file. }
16... Rac8
{ Placing the rook on the natural square, at the same time taking aim at the queen. }
17. Nd4 Be4 { Moving the bishop with tempo. } 18. O-O Na4
{ Black starts activity on the queenside. } 19. Qd2 Qb6
{ Putting pressure on the b2-pawn. } 20. b4 Qg6
{ Black provoked the b4-move and even though he cannot undermine that pawn by ...a5, what he got in return is the access to the c4-square for the ...Nb6-c4 maneuver. }
21. f3 Bf5
{ The position is complex, but the weakening of the e3-pawn coupled with the idea of ...Nb6-c4 gives Black good play. }
