[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.a3 #13"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. a3 { White anticipates Black's ...c5 and covers the b4-square in advance. }
7... c5 { Black follows up with his plan. } 8. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Exchanging one pair of knights is favorable for Black as it also liberates the f6-square for his bishop. }
9. Nxd5 exd5 10. dxc5 Nxc5
{ The knight is active on c5, from where it controls the key squares: e4, d3, and b3. It can also drop back to e6 to aid the ...d4-push. Black can also use the f6-square for the bishop. On the long diagonal, it will be very active and will control the blockading d4-square. Black also has the idea of ...Bd7-a4, to take advantage of the weakened light squares on White's queenside. All these factors indicate that Black has a comfortable version of the IQP. }
11. Be5
{ White controls the long diagonal and defends the pawn on b2 in advance. Note that in case of   11.Be2  Bf6  12.Be5  we have a transposition to 11. Be5 Bf6 12. Be2. }
11... Bf6 { Black immediately challenges the centralized bishop. } 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 13. Qd4
{ White seeks the endgame in order to try to take advantage of the IQP on d5. While the endgame after the exchange on d4 is drawn with sensible play by Black, he is not forced to go for it. }
13... Qd6
{ Black now wants to combine the threat of ...Ne6 and ...d4 with active piece play, while the immediate threat is ...Nb3. }
14. Rd1 Rd8 { Defending the pawn on d5. } 15. Be2
{ White must try to finish development. } 15... Bf5
{ Black develops naturally and threatens ...Bc2. } 16. Qd2
{ Preventing ...Bc2. } 16... Be4 { The bishop is very active on e4. After } 17.
O-O Qg6
{ White cannot move the knight from f3 due to the threat of mate on g2. The pin on the knight is very limiting for White so he must play... }
18. g3 { To liberate the knight, but after } 18... h5
{ followed by ...h4. Black obtains play on the kingside that gives him good chances in this balanced middlegame position. A sample line is }
19. Nd4 h4 20. g4
{ In order to play f3 and chase away the annoying bishop. Or   20.f3  Bf5  21.g4  Bd7  and White's exposed kingside is a source of counterplay for Black. }
20... Qf6 { Liberating the g6-square for the bishop. } 21. f3 Bg6 22. Kg2 Re8
{ The position is complex, but Black has good play against White's kingside and the fact that the king on g2 is not safe is a long-term factor in Black's favor. }
