1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. g4
{ This is quite an aggressive attempt by White this early in the opening, but even though not very likely to be played, it must be checked. }
7... Bb4
{ With this move, Black avoids the complications after taking the pawn or after allowing his knight to be stranded to h5 after g5. The pin on the knight on c3 secures the e4-square for the knight on f6. In fact, Black is playing along the classical maxim that play on the flank should be met by play in the center. }
8. g5 Ne4 9. Qc2 c5
{ Gives Black rich counterplay. He wants to take on d4 and then play ...b6 and ...Bb7. }
