[Black "Main Line 7.cxd5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. cxd5
{ White here transforms the structure, but after the exchange of knights on d5, Black has the option to be more active and play in the center. }
7... Nxd5 { Naturally, Black exchanges one pair of knights. } 8. Nxd5 exd5 9.
Bd3 c5
{ This is the more active approach than playing ...c6 with the typical Carlsbad structure, in line with the whole idea of the ...Nbd7 move - to push ...c5. }
10. dxc5 { Allows Black to active his pieces quickly after } 10... Nxc5
{ The bishops are coming out quickly and the immediate threat is ...Qa5, so White must allow the exchange of his light-squared bishop. }
11. O-O Bf6 { Hitting the pawn on b2 that is not so easy to defend. } 12. Rb1
{ Practically the only way. A move like   12.Bc2  @@StartBracket@@planning Qb1 to hit both h7 and the bishop on b2 if Black takes the pawn on b2@@EndBracket@@ allows the pin  12...Bg4  Similarly,   12.Be5  Bxe5  13.Nxe5  Qf6  continues the attack along the long diagonal. }
12... Bg4
{ Black wants to wreck White's structure by taking on f3 since the queen is overburdened defending both the bishop on d3 and the knight on f3. }
13. Be2 { Avoiding both captures. } 13... Rc8
{ Black has an excellent position as White is extremely short of constructive moves. For example, }
14. Nd4 Bxe2 15. Nxe2
{ If   15.Qxe2  Bxd4  16.exd4  Ne6  Black is left with the better minor piece in this position with a fixed center. }
15... Ne6
{ With ...d4 @@StartBracket@@or ...Nxf4 if White allows it@@EndBracket@@ next Black has no problems. }
