{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. h3
{ With this move, White will try to wait with the development of the bishop from f1 in the hope that Black will play ...Ba6 so he can take on a6 in one go, without moving the bishop from the initial square. }
8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Qc1 { The idea of this move is to prevent the immediate ...Ba6. } 11... Bb7
{ The immediate   11...Ba6?  would be bad in view of  12.Bxa6  Rxa6  13.b5!  Here we see the importance of the queen on the c-file, as it supports the c-pawn after  13...cxb5  14.c6  followed by Nxb5. That is why Black takes the slower approach, preparing ...Ba6 with the help of ...Qc8 first. }
12. Bd3 Qc8 { Black continues with the plan. } 13. O-O Ba6
{ Accomplishing the goal of exchanging the light-squared bishops. } 14. Bxa6
{ After   14.Qc2  Bxd3  15.Qxd3  Qb7  (@@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/3nbpp1/1pp1pn1p/p1Pp4/1P1P1B2/P1N1PN1P/5PP1/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 11@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the lines after  11.Bd3  Ba6  12.O-O  Qc8  13.Qc2  Bxd3  14.Qxd3  Qb7 }
14... Rxa6
{ Black takes with the rook so he can double on the a-file faster when the queen moves to b7. }
15. Qb2 Qb7
{ This is not only an automatic move that follows Black's plan, as Black is preventing b5 in view of the pin on the b-file and the undefended queen on b2. }
16. Rfb1
{ Protecting the queen. The immediate   16.b5?  would be bad as after  16...bxc5  the queen on b2 is undefended and White cannot take the rook on a6, thus simply losing a pawn. }
16... axb4
{ Since b5 was a threat, Black releases the tension on the queenside and wins control over the a-file. Usually this is Black's typical reaction when there is a looming threat of b5 - he takes on b4 and then either exchanges rooks on the a-file or closes the b-file by playing ... b5. }
17. axb4 Rxa1 18. Qxa1
{ Again not   18.Rxa1?  as after  18...bxc5  the queen on b2 is undefended again and Black wins a pawn after  19.dxc5  Nxc5 }
18... Ra8 { Obtaining control over the open a-file. } 19. Qb2 Nf8
{ Intending ...Ng6. Black is very comfortable here as he still keeps the option to either open or close the b-file @@StartBracket@@playing ...bxc5 or ...b5 respectively@@EndBracket@@ and his light pieces are well-placed. Depending on circumstances, he can play ...Bd8-c7 and aim for the ...e5 push. }
