{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. h3
{ With this move, White will try to wait with the development of the bishop from f1 in the hope that Black will play ...Ba6 so he can take on a6 in one go, without moving the bishop from the initial square. }
8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Be2 Ba6
{ Since White moved the light-squared bishop, Black plays ...Ba6 immediately. }
12. O-O Qc8 { Black plays the usual move, the queen is en route to b7. } 13.
Qc2
{ White needs to develop the queen in order to connect the rooks. This is usually a hint for Black to exchange the bishops. }
13... Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Qb7
{ After the exchange of bishops, Black prepares the doubling of the rooks on the a-file. }
15. Rfb1 Ra7
{ The rook is safer on a7 than on a6 here, avoiding a possible attack after b5. Black will continue with ...axb4 and ... Rfa8 with easy play, for example... }
16. Qc2 axb4 17. axb4 Rfa8 { When Black has no problems. } *

