1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. h3
{ With this move, White will try to wait with the development of the bishop from f1 in the hope that Black will play ...Ba6 so he can take on a6 in one go, without moving the bishop from the initial square. }
8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Bd3
{ With this move, White gives up the fight for tempo. He can try to postpone the development of the bishop, but Black simply develops following the rule of thumb: he plays ...Ba6 only when White has already moved the bishop, otherwise he prepares it with ...Bb7 and ...Qc8 first. }
11... Ba6
{ Since White moved his light-squared bishop, Black can play ...Ba6 immediately. }
12. Bxa6
{ Taking is an alternative, embarking on complications after b5 next. } 12...
Rxa6 13. b5
{ The only way to justify the capture on a6 as after   13.O-O  Qa8  The Black queen goes directly to a8 to fight for the a-file. However, the inclusion of the moves h3 and h6 works in Black's favor here, as we shall see. That is why if White goes for the complications, Bxa6 followed by b5, he does it without the inclusion of h3 and h6. }
13... cxb5 { Black must take the pawn. } 14. c6
{ This was White's idea, to liberate the path for the c-pawn. } 14... Qc8
{ The knight on d7 didn't have good squares to go to, as   14...Nb8?  15.c7  loses, so Black defends by pinning and attacking the pawn on c6, forcing it to move forward. }
15. c7 b4
{ The white knight was coming to b5 anyway, so Black avoids losing the b5-pawn by moving it to b4. }
16. Nb5 a4
{ An important move, preventing the move a4 which would have cemented the knight on b5. Now the knight is somewhat unstable, liable to attacks by ...Ra5 for example. }
17. Rc1 { White defends the pawn on c7 and threatens Nd6. } 17... Ne4
{ Preventing Nd6. Here we arrive at the moment where the difference of having a pawn already on h6 works in Black's favor. Without the pawn on h6, White could play Ng5 here and we analyze this move in the line after 8.Bd3. With a pawn on h6, he is forced to challenge the e4-knight from d2, allowing a favorable simplification. }
18. Nd2 Nc3
{ Black conveniently exchanges the active knight on b5 and regroups to safely blockade the c7-pawn. }
19. Nxc3 bxc3 20. Rxc3 Qb7
{ With the c7-pawn going nowhere, Black can start his own queenside play with ...b5-b4 or ...Nb6-c4. In addition to the weak pawn on a3, these factors give Black good chances. }
