8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Bd3
{ With this move, White gives up the fight for tempo. He can try to postpone the development of the bishop, but Black simply develops following the rule of thumb: he plays ...Ba6 only when White has already moved the bishop, otherwise he prepares it with ...Bb7 and ...Qc8 first. }
11... Ba6
{ Since White moved his light-squared bishop, Black can play ...Ba6 immediately. }
12. O-O
{ In case of   12.b5  Bb7  the exchanges that will ensue on the queenside will free Black's pieces. For example,  13.cxb6  Qxb6  14.O-O  Rfc8 }
12... Qc8
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  Black plays the usual moves and prepares ...Qb7. Note that the lines that follow are identical to the lines after   8.Bd3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  Ba6  11.O-O  Qc8  the only difference being that the pawns are on h3 and h6 here but this doesn't affect any variation. }
13. Rb1 { White removes the rook from the a-file and avoids exchanges. } 13...
axb4
{ Since White abandoned the a-file, Black opens it to activate the rook on a8. }
14. axb4 Bxd3
{ Black exchanges the bishops and follows up with ...Qb7 to enable the doubling of the rooks on the a-file. }
15. Qxd3 Qb7
{ Liberating the 8th rank so that the rook from f8 can come to a8. } 16. Rfc1
Ra7 { Preparing the doubling of the rooks. } 17. Qc2
{ This is a characteristic moment - when White has heavy presence on the b- and c-files, he often threatens b5 @@StartBracket@@while not quite in this case@@EndBracket@@. So as a rule of thumb, this is the moment when Black should close the b-file and play }
17... b5
{ This kills off White's queenside play and with the control of the a-file, Black is very comfortable. He will double the rooks on the a-file and then will play ...Nf8-g6 and possibly ...Bd8-c7 @@StartBracket@@whether he will exchange the bishops will depend on whether White tries to put a knight on a5 - if the knight goes to b3 then Black will prefer to keep his bishop on d8 so he controls the a5-square@@EndBracket@@. }
