[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.c5 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. h3
{ With this move, White will try to wait with the development of the bishop from f1 in the hope that Black will play ...Ba6 so he can take on a6 in one go, without moving the bishop from the initial square. }
8... b6 { Black continues with his plan to undermine White's queenside. } 9. b4
a5 10. a3 h6
{ Black also fights for the tempo. In fact, Black has more useful moves to make @@StartBracket@@like ...Bb7, ...Qc8@@EndBracket@@ because sooner rather than later White should castle and this means moving the bishop from f1. }
11. Bd3
{ With this move, White gives up the fight for tempo. He can try to postpone the development of the bishop, but Black simply develops following the rule of thumb: he plays ...Ba6 only when White has already moved the bishop, otherwise he prepares it with ...Bb7 and ...Qc8 first. }
11... Ba6
{ Since White moved his light-squared bishop, Black can play ...Ba6 immediately. }
12. O-O
{ In case of   12.b5  Bb7  the exchanges that will ensue on the queenside will free Black's pieces. For example,  13.cxb6  Qxb6  14.O-O  Rfc8 }
12... Qc8
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  Black plays the usual moves and prepares ...Qb7. Note that the lines that follow are identical to the lines after   8.Bd3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  Ba6  11.O-O  Qc8  the only difference being that the pawns are on h3 and h6 here but this doesn't affect any variation. }
13. Qc2
{ This is the most commonly played move. White accepts to lose a tempo as he needs to connect his rooks. }
13... Bxd3
{ Black naturally wins the tempo by forcing the queen to move again. } 14. Qxd3
Qb7 { The usual move. Black prepares for the doubling on the a-file. } 15. Nd2
{ With this move White wants to put the knight on b3 from where it will control both the c5 and a5-squares, but the drawback is that it weakens control of the e5-square. }
15... axb4 { Black exchanges on b4 and c5 in order to weaken the c5-pawn. } 16.
axb4 bxc5 17. bxc5 e5
{ This is the idea - by removing the pawn on b4 the pawn on c5 lacks protection and thanks to the central push, Black liberates his play. }
18. Rab1 Qc8
{ Removing the queen and now White must resolve the central confrontation. }
19. Bxe5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Nd7 { Black will return the pawn with excellent play. }
*

