[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 4: The Main Line: 5.Bf4"]
[Black "Main Line 7.c5 #12"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6 8. b4
{ This would most likely lead to a transposition, but there is one fresh idea here that gives the line some independent value. }
8... b6 9. h4
{ This was used twice by Caruana against Nakamura in the Carlsen Invitational online event played in April 2020. Otherwise after  9.Bd3  a5  10.a3  Ba6   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to our usual lines after  8.Bd3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  Ba6  The idea of the move is two-fold: to wait for Black to play ...Ba6 and take on a6 in one go @@StartBracket@@similar to the move 8. h3@@EndBracket@@ and to add some attacking ideas on the kingside like Ng5 or h5-h6. }
9... a5 { First Black plays the usual move, undermining White's queenside. }
10. a3 h6
{ Since White's  9.h4  was a semi-waiting move like  8.h3  , Black can play in the same semi-waiting manner and play a useful move @@StartBracket@@covering the g5-square and opening a luft for the king@@EndBracket@@ and wait for White to develop the light-squared bishop before playing ...Ba6. Nakamura played  10...Ne4  and while playable, the position after  11.Nxe4  dxe4  leaves Black's pawns somewhat exposed. Now after 10...h6, White is more or less forced to move the light-squared bishop after which Black will continue along the usual lines with ...Ba6. }
11. Qb1
{ Still trying to keep the bishop on  f1  . After  11.Be2  Ba6   or  11.Bd3  Ba6  play is analogous to the lines after   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  h6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  h6  the only difference being the White pawn on h4, which can be argued it's in Black's favor in view of the weakened square on g4.   It's important to note that aggressive moves like  11.g4?  backfire as Black can first clarify the situation on the queenside and then take the pawn, distracting the White queen in the process:  11...axb4  12.axb4  Rxa1  13.Qxa1  Nxg4  and with the queen on a1, White cannot hope to get anything from the g-file so he has no compensation for the pawn.   The move  11.h5  is met by  11...Ba6  and even though White can now take on a6 in one go, the pawn on h5 is hanging in case White castles. This gain of tempo didn't bring much to White. }
11... Bb7
{ Using the same ideas as in the lines after 8.h3 - since White waits with the development of the light-squared bishop. The queen on b1 enhances the b5-push after the exchange on a6, and Black prepares the ...Ba6 move with the help of ...Qc8. }
12. Bd3 Qc8
{ @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@ With ...Ba6 next, Black obtains the typical solid position. You can check the lines after  8.h3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  h6  11.Qb1  Bb7  12.Bd3  Qc8  as they are practically identical. }
*

