1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3
{ White usually develops both knights before developing the bishop to f4. }
4... Nf6 5. Bf4 O-O
{ Black played the usual moves and finished the development of the kingside. }
6. e3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/ppp1bppp/4p3/3p4/2PP4/2N5/PP2PPPP/R1BQKBNR w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@  The most common move. The other moves transpose to the lines after   4.Bf4  Nf6  5.e3  O-O }
6... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black wants to to play ...c5 and take on c5 with the knight. }
7. c5 { The most critical move. } 7... c6
{ Black fixes the queenside and now plans to undermine White's pawn chain by ...b6 and ...a5. When these moves are played, he will solve the problem of his bad bishop by playing ...Ba6. Now White has to make a choice - whether to continue naturally with  8.Bd3  or to try to win a tempo by playing 8.h3 and waiting for Black to play ...Ba6. White would want to play Bxa6 without having to move the bishop to d3 first. }
8. Bd3 { The natural development of the bishop. } 8... b6
{ Black undermines White's pawn on c5. } 9. b4 a5
{ Attacking the b4-pawn. It is important to note that it is Black who controls the tension on the queenside as it is he who decides when and if to take. Generally, White cannot wreck his structure by taking on a5 or b6. }
10. a3
{ The move  10.b5  is met by  10...Bb7  and Black doesn't mind the exchanges on the queenside. }
10... Ba6
{ Black continues with his strategic plan to exchange his bad bishop. } 11.
Bxa6
{ This move leads to very sharp play. The immediate   11.b5  is calmly met by  11...Bb7  when the exchanges of the b- and c-pawns on the queenside will give more space to Black's pieces, for example  12.cxb6  Qxb6  13.O-O  Rfc8  with comfortable play. }
11... Rxa6 12. b5
{ The only way for White. Otherwise, Black plays ...Qa8 and obtains a comfortable position as he immediately managed to put pressure on the a-file, without having to play ...Qc8-b7 and then double the rooks. }
12... cxb5 { Black had to take the pawn. } 13. c6
{ Now we see White's idea - he sacrifices material in order to obtain a strong passed pawn. }
13... Qc8
{ The knight on d7 didn't have good squares to go to, as   13...Nb8?  14.c7  loses, so Black defends by pinning and attacking the pawn on c6, forcing it to move forward.  @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/2Pp4/3P1B2/2N1PN2/PP3PPP/R2QKB1R w KQ - 0 8@@EndFEN@@  Black's play is identical to the line after  8.h3  b6  9.b4  a5  10.a3  h6  11.Bd3  Ba6  12.Bxa6  Rxa6  13.b5  only here the absence of a pawn on h6 gives White an additional @@StartBracket@@and better@@EndBracket@@ possibility. }
14. c7 b4
{ White wanted to play Nb5 anyway, so Black avoids losing the b5-pawn by moving it forward. }
15. Nb5
{ We can see White's idea now - he pins his hopes on the strong pawn on c7, which is well defended by the bishop on f4 and the knight on b5. Now he wants to cement the knight on b5 by playing a4, so Black's next move is logical. }
15... a4
{ Preventing a4 and without the pawn support the knight on b5 is less stable. For example, Black can attack it with ...Ra5. }
16. Rc1
{ White's play is straightforward. He intends to queen his c-pawn! With the rook on c1, he plans Bd6 to exchange the dark-squared bishops and allow for Nd6, which would control the c8-square and win material for White. }
16... Ne4 { Again logical, controlling the d6-square and preventing Bd6. } 17.
Nd2
{ As in the line after 8.h3, this is harmless. Black plays in the same manner: }
17... Nc3 { Exchanging the active knight on b5. } 18. Nxc3 bxc3 19. Rxc3 Qb7
{ With the c7-pawn going nowhere, Black can start his own queenside play with ...b5-b4 or ...Nb6-c4. In addition to the weak pawn on a3, these factors give Black good chances. }
