[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After this move-order, we will explore the plans where White develops the knight to d2 instead of c3. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. dxc5 { This resolution of the tension doesn't offer much. } 7...
dxc4 { Black opens the d-file in order to exchange queens. } 8. Qxd8
{ Otherwise, Black would take on d1. } 8... Rxd8 9. Bxc4 Bxc5
{ Black has no problems here. He will continue with ... b6 and ...Bb7 to develop the light-squared bishop, and then ...Nbd7 @@StartBracket@@or ...Nc6@@EndBracket@@ and ...Rac8 to finish development. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After this move-order, we will explore the plans where White develops the knight to d2 instead of c3. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. cxd5
{ The simplifications in the center offer White very little as Black finishes development comfortably. }
7... Nxd5 { Black recaptures with a piece, keeping his structure intact. } 8.
dxc5 Bxc5 { Again naturally taking the pawn. } 9. Bc4 b6
{ Black wants to develop with ...Bb7, ...Nd7 and ...Qe7, which would give him a very harmonious position. }
10. O-O
{ Note that giving away the light-squared bishop for the knight on d5 is not very good for White because after   10.Bxd5  exd5  Black follows up with ...Nc6 and ...d4 getting rid of the IQP and keeping the pair of bishops. }
10... Bb7 { Black continues with the planned development. } 11. Qe2 Nd7 12.
Nbd2 Qe7
{ Both sides finished development and Black can be content with the result of the opening. He has connected the rooks and the only thing he needs to be careful about is the possibility of Ne4, which would aim to exchange his dark-squared bishop. }
13. a3 { This prepares Ne4 as the immediate   13.Ne4  allows  13...Ba3 } 13...
a6 { Black prepares ...b5 in order to liberate the b6-square for the bishop. }
14. b4
{ In case of   14.Ne4  b5  15.Nxc5  Nxc5  White's light-squared bishop has no escape and after  16.Bd3  Nxd3  Black eliminates it, thus denying White the advantage of the bishop pair. }
14... Bd6 15. Ne4 Bb8
{ Black avoids the exchange of knight for bishop. He now has the idea of ...b5 and ...Ba7 or even the more aggressive one of ...f5 @@StartBracket@@which can continue to f4@@EndBracket@@, with or without ...e5 thrown in. The middlegame is very rich and Black can be optimistic about his chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After this move-order, we will explore the plans where White develops the knight to d2 instead of c3. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. Bd3 { This is the most common choice. } 7... cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 and after White takes with the pawn, the bishop on b2 will be rather passive. }
8. exd4 { Taking with knight runs into  8.Nxd4?!  e5 } 8... b6
{ Black develops the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nbd2
{ Note that after  10.Nc3   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ we will have a transposition to the lines after  4.Nc3  Be7  5.e3  By developing the knight on d2, White has the option to play Ne5 and Ndf3. For more information on these lines, clickhere. }
10... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. The knight on c6 puts pressure on d4 and can also go to b4 to harass the bishop on d3. Now White needs to decide whether to put the queen on e2 or not. }
11. Rc1
{ This is a useful move for White, lending more support to the c4-pawn and allowing the bishop from d3 to drop back to b1 without shutting the rook out. }
11... Rc8 { Black also centralizes the rooks. } 12. Re1 Re8
{ This is a typical move for Black in this line. It liberates the f8-square for the dark-squared bishop to allow for the regrouping ...Bf8, ...g6 and ...Bg7 which would strengthen Black's kingside. }
13. Ne5 { This is harmless as after } 13... dxc4
{ In view of the exposure of the d4-pawn, White is forced to simplify the position by exchanging his centralized knight for the one on c6. }
14. Nxc6 Bxc6 15. bxc4 g6
{ With a very good position for Black who will continue with ...Bf8-g7 and use the fianchettoed bishop to put pressure on White's hanging pawns. }
