[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After this move-order, we will explore the plans where White develops the knight to d2 instead of c3. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. Bd3 { This is the most common choice. } 7... cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 and after White takes with the pawn, the bishop on b2 will be rather passive. }
8. exd4 { Taking with knight runs into  8.Nxd4?!  e5 } 8... b6
{ Black develops the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nbd2
{ Note that after  10.Nc3   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ we will have a transposition to the lines after  4.Nc3  Be7  5.e3  By developing the knight on d2, White has the option to play Ne5 and Ndf3. For more information on these lines, clickhere. }
10... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. The knight on c6 puts pressure on d4 and can also go to b4 to harass the bishop on d3. Now White needs to decide whether to put the queen on e2 or not. }
11. Rc1
{ This is a useful move for White, lending more support to the c4-pawn and allowing the bishop from d3 to drop back to b1 without shutting the rook out. }
11... Rc8 { Black also centralizes the rooks. } 12. Re1 Re8
{ This is a typical move for Black in this line. It liberates the f8-square for the dark-squared bishop to allow for the regrouping ...Bf8, ...g6 and ...Bg7 which would strengthen Black's kingside. }
13. a3
{ With this move, White not only controls the b4-square, defending against ...Nb4 but also prepares a queenside expansion after c5 and b4. }
13... Bf8 { Black continues with the plan. } 14. c5 a5
{ Black prevents White's queenside expansion. } 15. Bb5
{ This is another typical move - White wants to eliminate the knight on c6, which controls the b4-square, so that he can push b4. Black agrees to this exchange because he obtains the bishop pair and control over the light squares. }
15... Nd7
{ Attacking the c5-pawn, so White is forced to take on c6 and defend the c5-pawn by b4. }
16. b4
{ White can also start by taking on c6, leading to a transposition anyway. }
16... axb4 { Forcing White to take on c6. } 17. Bxc6 Bxc6 18. axb4 Qc7
{ Black finished development. He is well-placed for the ensuing middlegame with good control over the light squares. He has the bishop pair and can aim to open the position by pushing ...e5 or to activate his light-square bishop with ...Bb5. }
