{ Black develops naturally. The knight on c6 puts pressure on d4 and can also go to b4 to harass the bishop on d3. Now White needs to decide whether to put the queen on e2 or not. }
11. Qe2 Re8
{ Putting the rook on the same file as the White queen and liberating the f8-square for the ...Bf8-g7 maneuver. Now White has a choice where to put the rooks: on e1 and d1 or d1 and c1. }
12. Rac1 Rc8
{ Black continues in the same manner - the queen's rook goes to c8 and then the bishop drops back to f8, en route to g7 after ...g6. }
13. Rfd1 Bf8 14. Nf1
{ The move   14.c5?!  leads to a great position for Black after  14...bxc5  15.dxc5  Nd7  as White has problems defending the c5-pawn and Black also threatens a central expansion by ...e5.  If White wants to prepare c5 by playing   14.a3  then Black can simply prevent that with  14...a5 }
14... g6 { Black continues with the typical plan. } 15. Ne3 Bg7 16. c5
{ Black's dark-squared bishop doesn't control the c5-square anymore so White advances. But in order to keep his queenside pawn chain, White will have to give away his important light-squared bishop. }
16... Nd7 { Intending to take on c5 and advance with ...d4. } 17. Bb5 a6
{ This forces the exchange of White's light-squared bishop. } 18. Bxc6
{ Taking on  a6  is bad as  18.Bxa6  Bxa6  19.Qxa6  bxc5  Black obtains a strong pawn center since White cannot take on c5 due to the undefended bishop on b2. }
18... Bxc6 19. b4
{ Taking on a6 is similarly sub-optimal for White after   19.Qxa6  bxc5  while taking on b6 gives Black good play after   19.cxb6  Qxb6  followed up by ...a5-a4. }
19... Qc7
{ Black finished development of all of his pieces and has a very compact position. He has the bishop pair and good control over the light squares, which also makes White's remaining bishop a bad one. He will prepare for an undermining of White's queenside by ...a5 @@StartBracket@@naturally avoiding b5 in the process@@EndBracket@@. His other ideas are ...h5 @@StartBracket@@to prevent Ng4@@EndBracket@@ with ...Bh6 or ...Bb5@@StartBracket@@a4@@EndBracket@@ with ...Nb8-c6 as follow up. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nf3 and 4.e3 #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ After this move-order, we will explore the plans where White develops the knight to d2 instead of c3. }
3... Nf6 4. e3 Be7 5. b3
{ White can start with moves like Bd3 or Nbd2, but in any case he's heading towards a set-up with bishops on d3 and b2 and a knight on d2. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2
{ After  6.Bd3  c5  7.O-O  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.Bb2  Bb7   we have a transposition to the lines starting with  6.Bb2  c5  7.Bd3  cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7 }
6... c5 7. Bd3 { This is the most common choice. } 7... cxd4
{ Black takes on d4 and after White takes with the pawn, the bishop on b2 will be rather passive. }
8. exd4 { Taking with knight runs into  8.Nxd4?!  e5 } 8... b6
{ Black develops the bishop on the long diagonal. } 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nbd2
{ Note that after  10.Nc3   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp2ppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ we will have a transposition to the lines after  4.Nc3  Be7  5.e3  By developing the knight on d2, White has the option to play Ne5 and Ndf3. For more information on these lines, clickhere. }
10... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally. The knight on c6 puts pressure on d4 and can also go to b4 to harass the bishop on d3. Now White needs to decide whether to put the queen on e2 or not. }
11. Qe2 Re8
{ Putting the rook on the same file as the White queen and liberating the f8-square for the ...Bf8-g7 maneuver. Now White has a choice where to put the rooks: on e1 and d1 or d1 and c1. }
12. Rad1 Bf8
{ Since there is no rook on c1, Black also postpones the development of the rook from a8 and fianchettoes the bishop first. }
13. Rfe1 g6 14. Bb1 Bg7
{ Finishing the kingside regrouping. The strong position of Black's kingside guarantees against any unpleasantries on the kingside. }
15. Ne5
{ This is a natural continuation. With the rooks concentrated in the centre White's play will happen there, though the idea of expansion with c5 should not be forgotten. }
15... Rc8 { Finally putting the rook on the c-file. } 16. Ndf3
{ This was one of White's main ideas when putting the knight on d2 - to come to f3 and support the other knight on e5. }
16... dxc4
{ Since Black is fully developed he starts active counterplay in the center. First, he creates hanging pawns on c4 and d4. }
17. bxc4 Nxe5 { Now he opens the c-file for the rook on c8. } 18. Nxe5
{ After  18.dxe5  Nd7  White has created pawn weaknesses on c4 and a2 and has given Black an excellent square on c5 for the knight, with no obvious compensation. }
18... Nd7
{ Black challenges the centralised knight. In case it is eliminated, the pawn on c4 will require protection after Black attacks it by ...Ba6 and possibly ...Qc7. }
19. f4 Ba6
{ Black is in no hurry to take on e5, he first increases the pressure on the c4-pawn. }
20. Bd3 Qc7
{ Black threatens to take the pawn on c4 now, after first taking on e5. In order not to be forced onto the defensive, White should sacrifice a pawn now. }
21. d5 exd5
{ Black takes everywhere - first on d5, then d3, and finally takes the knight on e5. }
22. cxd5 Bxd3
{ The bishop was hanging so Black takes on d3 first before taking on e5. } 23.
Qxd3 Nxe5 { Now Black wins a pawn. } 24. fxe5 Bxe5 25. Bxe5 Rxe5 26. Rxe5 Qxe5
{ Black won a pawn, but the passed d-pawn should give White compensation for equality. In any case, it is White who is trying to save the draw here and Black runs no risks. }
