{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. e3 O-O 6. a3
{ White wants to take on c5 and push b4 in case Black plays ...c5. } 6... b6
{ In return, Black doesn't hurry with ... c5 and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
7. cxd5 Nxd5 { Black keeps the long diagonal open. } 8. e4
{ White takes the center, but the lost tempo with e3 means that Black is comfortable. }
8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 c5 { The typical central push. } 10. Bd3 Ba6
{ Black exchanges the light-squared bishops because White's light-squared bishop is an important piece for him - in many lines it helps an attack on the kingside along the b1-h7 diagonal after e5. }
11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O Qc7
{ Black has easy play on the queenside. He can play ...Qb7 @@StartBracket@@to control the light-squares on the long diagonal and move the queen away from the c-file@@EndBracket@@, ...Rac8, ...Rfd8, take on d4 at some point and and then reroute the knight either via b8 @@StartBracket@@to c6, a5, and eventually c4@@EndBracket@@ or c7. He can also support his queenside play by advancing his majority there. }
