[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. e3 O-O 6. b3 c5 7. Bb2
{ White can also start with   7.Bd3  but play will transpose after  7...cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Bb2 }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nc6
{ Black develops in the same manner as in the lines where White put the knight on d2: the rooks will come to c8 and e8 and then he will execute the maneuver ...Bf8-g7 @@StartBracket@@after ...g6@@EndBracket@@. With a knight on c3 that blocks the c-file, the idea of a queenside advance of c5 is less dangerous; what is more threatening is the d5-break, which the knight on c3 supports. }
11. Qe2
{ This is dubious here as it allows Black to wreck White's kingside structure. }
11... Nb4 { Attacking White's most valuable light piece. } 12. Bb1
{ If White allows the exchange of his light-squared bishop for a knight, his position will simply become hopeless as he will lose control of the light squares and will obtain no compensation for Black's bishop pair. }
12... dxc4 { Opening the long diagonal. } 13. bxc4 Bxf3
{ This exchange forces White to take with a pawn. } 14. gxf3
{ The point is that the queen must remain on e2 to defend the bishop on b2, i.e.   14.Qxf3  Qxd4  just loses a pawn for no compensation. }
14... Re8
{ With the queen defending the bishop on b2, taking the pawn is bad:   14...Qxd4?  15.Nd5  and White wins. The rook move is a prophylactic one, defending the bishop on e7 and discouraging the d5-push by placing the rook on the same file as the White queen. }
15. Rd1 Bd6
{ Establishing control over the h2-b8 diagonal. Black threatens ... Nh5, ...Qh4 with dangerous threats. White on the other hand cannot use his bishops as d5 is discouraged and he still has a rook on a1 that needs to be developed. }
