[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 3.Nc3 and 5.e3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. e3 O-O 6. b3 c5 7. Bb2
{ White can also start with   7.Bd3  but play will transpose after  7...cxd4  8.exd4  b6  9.O-O  Bb7  10.Bb2 }
7... cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nc6
{ Black develops in the same manner as in the lines where White put the knight on d2: the rooks will come to c8 and e8 and then he will execute the maneuver ...Bf8-g7 @@StartBracket@@after ...g6@@EndBracket@@. With a knight on c3 that blocks the c-file, the idea of a queenside advance of c5 is less dangerous; what is more threatening is the d5-break, which the knight on c3 supports. }
11. Rc1
{ White can also start with   11.Re1  but in any case, he will put the other rook on c1 leading to a transposition after  11...Rc8  12.Rc1  g6 }
11... Rc8
{ Black places the rook on the c-file, which is the best place from where it is actively controlling the c-file. After an exchange on c4, the pawn on c4 will be vulnerable so the rook can help in the attack against it. }
12. Re1 g6
{ A precise move, and it's necessary to understand why it's preferred over the automatic placement of the rook on e8. With the rooks in the center, White is ready to start activities by taking on d5. Then in case, Black takes with a knight, White will exchange the knights. When the queen arrives on d5, he will play Be4 and push d5, opening up the game where his superior activity will require some precision from Black. In case Black takes on d5 with a pawn, White has the annoying move Bf5, attacking the rook on c8. It is this last point that prompts Black to play ...g6 first, covering the f5-square. Here's the illustrative line:   12...Re8  13.cxd5  Nxd5  or   13...exd5  14.Bf5  14.Nxd5  Qxd5  15.Be4  Qd6  16.d5 }
13. Bf1
{ By removing the bishop from d3, White defends the d4-pawn with his queen and intends to play Ne5. }
13... Re8 { Black continues with his plan of ...Bf8-g7. } 14. Ne5 Nxe5
{ Exchanging the centralized knight. } 15. dxe5 Ne4
{ Black establishes his own centralized knight that White has to exchange. }
16. Nxe4 dxe4
{ With both pairs of knights exchanged the position is equal, though Black's bishops are somewhat more active. }
