[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Qc2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to transpose to the Exchange Variation but with the queen on c2 preventing the development of the bishop on f5. }
5... c5
{ The most direct way, trying to take over the initiative immediately. With his last move, White weakened control over  d4  so Black takes immediate advantage. Another idea of White's 5.Qc2 is to move-order Black out of the intended repertoire in case of  5...O-O  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bxf6  Bxf6  as here Black has ...O-O instead of the preferred ...dxc4. }
6. cxd5 cxd4 { An intermediate move attacking the c3-knight. } 7. Nxd4
{ This is the more sensible approach for White, avoiding all the risks from the lines where he takes the pawn. }
7... O-O
{ The pawn on d5 is pinned so Black first castles to avoid any checks. } 8. Bg5
Nxd5 { Forcing simplifications. } 9. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ This prepares ...Nbc6 followed by ...e5. } 10. Rd1 Qc7
{ Black wants to develop with ...Bd7 and ... Nbc6 or with ...e5 and ...Nbc6. }
11. Ncb5
{ In case of  11.e3  Bd7  followed by ... a6 @@StartBracket@@to prevent Nb5@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nbc6. Black finishes development without problems. }
11... Qa5+
{ With this check, Black forces the return of the knight from b5 to c3, either with or without the exchange of queens. }
12. Qc3
{ After  12.Nc3  Bd7  followed by ...Rd8 @@StartBracket@@covering the bishop on d7 and liberating the e8-square for it, just in case@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nbc6, Black has easy play. }
12... Qxc3+ 13. Nxc3 Rd8
{ Black will continue with ...Nbc6 and ...Bd7, with an equal endgame ahead. } *

