[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Qc2 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to transpose to the Exchange Variation but with the queen on c2 preventing the development of the bishop on f5. }
5... c5
{ The most direct way, trying to take over the initiative immediately. With his last move, White weakened control over d4 so Black takes immediate advantage. Another idea of White's 5. Qc2 is to move-order Black out of the intended repertoire in case of   5...O-O  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bxf6  Bxf6  as here Black has ...O-O instead of the preferred ...dxc4. }
6. cxd5 cxd4 { An intermediate move attacking the c3-knight. } 7. Qa4+
{ With this check, White goes after the pawn, but he concedes the initiative to Black. }
7... Bd7 8. Qxd4 exd5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn for the initiative. The compensation consists of his quick development @@StartBracket@@and White's lag in it@@EndBracket@@ and the initiative thanks to his more active pieces. }
9. e3
{ White doesn't take the pawn on d5, but the time spent on moving the queen gives Black tempi for development and the activity of his pieces gives him a comfortable IQP position. }
9... Nc6 10. Qd3
{ From d3 the queen controls the e4-square, preventing a possible ...Ne4 jump. For example   10.Qd1  O-O  11.Be2  Be6  12.O-O  Ne4 }
10... O-O 11. Be2 Qc8
{ However, the queen on d3 is subject to an attack after ...Bf5. } 12. O-O
{ The pawn on d5 is taboo,   12.Nxd5?  Nxd5  13.Qxd5  Nb4  with the invasion on c2 netting the rook on a1. }
12... Bf5 { Attacking the queen and activating the bishop. } 13. Qd1 Rd8
{ Lending support to the pawn on d5. The rook is placed on the same file as the White queen, something that can come in handy in case of a ...d4 push. }
14. Nb5
{ White increases control over the d4-square, but leaves the e4-square without any. }
14... Ne4
{ Black naturally takes advantage of the undefended e4-square. He has a very good version of the IQP, with good development and central control. White still needs to develop the dark-squared bishop and if he develops it on d2 Black will obtain the pair of bishops by taking it. For example, }
15. Bd2 Nxd2 16. Qxd2 Be4
{ The bishop takes over from the knight and with the queen coming to f5 or g4 @@StartBracket@@then dropping back to g6 if needed@@EndBracket@@ and the rook from a8 to c8, Black has an excellent position with all his pieces very active. }
