1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to transpose to the Exchange Variation but with the queen on c2 preventing the development of the bishop on f5. }
5... c5
{ The most direct way, trying to take over the initiative immediately. With his last move, White weakened control over d4 so Black takes immediate advantage. Another idea of White's 5. Qc2 is to move-order Black out of the intended repertoire in case of   5...O-O  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bxf6  Bxf6  as here Black has ...O-O instead of the preferred ...dxc4. }
6. dxc5 d4 { Aggressively attacking White's pieces. } 7. Nb5 e5
{ Supporting d4 and sacrificing the e5-pawn for development, mostly for the opening of the h3-c8 diagonal. }
8. e3 { With this move, White tries to challenge the space-grabbing d4-pawn. }
8... Bxc5 { Black takes the pawn on c5 and defends his own on d4. } 9. Nxe5
{ White takes a pawn, but he cannot keep it for long. } 9... dxe3 10. Bxe3 Bxe3
{ By taking on e3, Black wrecks White's pawn structure by creating a pawn weakness on e3. }
11. fxe3 a6 { Chasing away the knight. } 12. Nc3 O-O
{ After castling, Black will use the e-file to put pressure on the e3-pawn. }
13. Be2 Qe7
{ Removing the queen from the d-file so she is not attacked by Rd1 and regaining the pawn after }
14. Nf3 Qxe3
{ With at least an equality for Black. White still needs to get his king to safety while Black develops easily with ...Nc6 and then the bishop develops on e6, f5 @@StartBracket@@in case the White queen moves from c2@@EndBracket@@ or g4. }
