1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. Qc2
{ White wants to transpose to the Exchange Variation but with the queen on c2 preventing the development of the bishop on f5. }
5... c5
{ The most direct way, trying to take over the initiative immediately. With his last move, White weakened control over d4 so Black takes immediate advantage. Another idea of White's 5. Qc2 is to move-order Black out of the intended repertoire in case of   5...O-O  6.Bg5  h6  7.Bxf6  Bxf6  as here Black has ...O-O instead of the preferred ...dxc4. }
6. dxc5 d4 { Aggressively attacking White's pieces. } 7. Nb5 e5
{ Supporting d4 and sacrificing the e5-pawn for development, mostly for the opening of the h3-c8 diagonal. }
8. Nxe5 a6 { Now the knight on b5 is forced to the rim. } 9. Na3
{ Note that   9.Nd6?  loses a piece to  9...Bxd6  10.cxd6  Qa5  and the knight on e5 is lost. }
9... O-O
{ Black has excellent compensation here. He will take on c5 soon and for only a pawn, he will have a strong initiative because White has difficulties developing his kingside. }
10. g3 { White tries to develop his kingside. } 10... Qa5+
{ Black wants to take on c5 with the queen in order to attack the knight on e5 and also to come to c6, preventing the development of White's light-squared bishop to g2. }
11. Bd2 Qxc5 12. Nd3
{ Putting the knight on f3 is worse, as   12.Nf3  Bf5  13.Qb3  Ne4  with the threat of ...d3 giving Black a tremendous initiative. }
12... Qc6
{ Hitting the rook on h1 and preventing the natural development of the light-squared bishop. }
13. f3
{ This keeps the right to castle. After   13.Rg1  Bf5  White has the extra problem of not being able to castle kingside to solve. }
13... Bf5
{ Black develops naturally. His play is easy as his pieces come out and put pressure on White's position. }
14. Bg2 Qe6
{ Preventing White's castling by keeping the king in the center as he has to defend the pawn on e2. Black is better here as his initiative is easy to handle while White finds it difficult to coordinate his pieces. }
