[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 5: The Main Line: 5.Various"]
[Black "White Plays 5.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. g3
{ With this move, White transposes to the Catalan, but with the queen's knight already on c3. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4
{ The problem for Black is that if he plays in the same way as in the Closed System of the Catalan with  6...c6  then after  7.O-O  Nbd7  White can use the free d2-square for the move  8.Nd2  and with e4 coming next, White can claim an advantage. By taking on c4, Black temporarily wins a pawn and forces White to be precise in order not to remain a pawn down for nothing. }
7. Ne5 { White wants to recapture on c4 immediately. } 7... Qd6
{ A somewhat surprising move. The idea is to remove the queen from the 8th rank and liberate the d8-square for the rook. As a matter of fact, the queen is pretty well placed on a6 from where she defends the b7-pawn @@StartBracket@@to allow for the development of the bishop from c8@@EndBracket@@ and controls the c4-square. }
8. Nxc4 Qa6 { Black continues with the plan. } 9. b3 Rd8
{ Black puts pressure on the d-file and threatens ...c5. } 10. a4
{ White prepares the move Nb5. In case of   10.O-O  c5  Black is fine. } 10...
Nd5
{ White planned to meet   10...c5  with  11.Nb5  so Black challenges the knight on c3. }
11. Bb2
{ In case of   11.Nxd5  exd5  Black has an excellent version of the Carlsbad structure, with the fianchettoed bishop on g2 particularly misplaced after Black plays ...c6. }
11... Nxc3 { Eliminating the knight so that after ...c5 there is no Nb5. } 12.
Bxc3 c5 { Now that White cannot play Nb5, Black executes the central thrust. }
13. O-O
{ White banks on his activity, but Black is extremely solid and without weaknesses can withstand the pressure. }
13... cxd4 14. Ba5 Rf8 15. Qxd4 Nc6
{ Black develops and wins the bishop pair after the queen retreats. } 16. Qd2
Nxa5 17. Qxa5 Qxa5 { The endgame is harmless for Black. } 18. Nxa5 Rb8
{ Removing the rook from the sensitive long diagonal and defending the pawn on b7. White cannot really increase his pressure as Black doesn't have weaknesses. He plans to open a luft for his king and then either offer an exchange of rooks on the d-file or chase away the knight on a5 after ...Bd8 or ...Bb4. }
*

