1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. g3
{ With this move, White transposes to the Catalan, but with the queen's knight already on c3. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4
{ The problem for Black is that if he plays in the same way as in the Closed System of the Catalan with  6...c6  then after  7.O-O  Nbd7  White can use the free d2-square for the move  8.Nd2  and with e4 coming next, White can claim an advantage. By taking on c4, Black temporarily wins a pawn and forces White to be precise in order not to remain a pawn down for nothing. }
7. Ne5 { White wants to recapture on c4 immediately. } 7... Qd6
{ A somewhat surprising move. The idea is to remove the queen from the 8th rank and liberate the d8-square for the rook. As a matter of fact, the queen is pretty well placed on a6 from where she defends the b7-pawn @@StartBracket@@to allow for the development of the bishop from c8@@EndBracket@@ and controls the c4-square. }
8. Nxc4 Qa6 { Black continues with the plan. } 9. Qb3 Nc6
{ Attacking the pawn on d4 and also liberating the b8-square for the rook. The rook from b8 not only leaves the sensitive h1-a8 diagonal, but also supports the ...b5 push. }
10. e3
{ Defending the pawn with bishop is dubious, as after  10.Be3  Nd5  the bishop on e3 is attacked, while taking the pawn on d5 is bad:  11.Nxd5?!  exd5  12.Bxd5  Nb4  13.Bg2  Be6  wins material for Black in view of the threat of ...b5, which would win the pinned knight. }
10... Rb8 { Threatening ...b5. } 11. a4 Bd7
{ Even though the immediate ...b5 was possible, Black finishes development first and will play ...b5 on the next move. }
12. Qb5 { Preventing ...b5. } 12... Nb4
{ Using the weakened b4-square and threatening ...Nc2. } 13. Qxa6 bxa6
{ This is the more dynamic recapture as it opens the b-file for Black. The doubled a-pawns don't matter much as it is Black who has the initiative on the queenside. He will continue with ...Rfc8 and ...c5 and exert pressure while White still needs to develop his dark-squared bishop. For example, }
14. O-O Rfc8 15. Rd1 c5 { With very active play in the endgame. } *

