1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. g3
{ With this move, White transposes to the Catalan, but with the queen's knight already on c3. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4
{ The problem for Black is that if he plays in the same way as in the Closed System of the Catalan with  6...c6  then after  7.O-O  Nbd7  White can use the free d2-square for the move  8.Nd2  and with e4 coming next, White can claim an advantage. By taking on c4, Black temporarily wins a pawn and forces White to be precise in order not to remain a pawn down for nothing. }
7. Ne5 { White wants to recapture on c4 immediately. } 7... Qd6
{ A somewhat surprising move. The idea is to remove the queen from the 8th rank and liberate the d8-square for the rook. As a matter of fact, the queen is pretty well placed on a6 from where she defends the b7-pawn @@StartBracket@@to allow for the development of the bishop from c8@@EndBracket@@ and controls the c4-square. }
8. O-O Qa6
{ Black continues with the plan to put the queen on a6 and at the same time defends the pawn on c4. }
9. a4 { White prepares Nb5. } 9... Nc6 { Challenging the knight on e5. } 10.
Nb5 Nxe5 { Eliminating the centralized knight. } 11. dxe5 Rd8
{ Attacking the queen and securing d5 for the knight. } 12. exf6
{ This is critical as it requires concrete knowledge by Black. In case of   12.Bd2  Ne8  @@StartBracket@@defending the c7-pawn@@EndBracket@@ followed by ...Bd7-c6. Black is fine. }
12... Rxd1
{ Black takes the queen, but he should be precise as White has some threats. }
13. Rxd1 Bd6 { Defending the c7-pawn. } 14. Bf4 Qa5
{ This is the precise move Black must know. The queen gets away from the fork on c7 and in case of an exchange on d6, will keep an eye on the d8-square, avoiding back-rank mates. }
15. Nxd6
{ White tries to play for more as   15.Bd2  Qa6  16.Bf4  Qa5  is a repetition,  while   15.Bxd6  cxd6  16.Nxd6  Bd7  allows Black to finish development. }
15... cxd6 16. Rxd6 gxf6
{ Not only taking the pawn but more importantly opening a luft for the king on g7. Black also wants to play ...e5 and ...Be6. }
17. Bh6 e5
{ Since the king cannot move to g7, Black needs to defend the 8th rank in another way. }
18. Rad1 Be6
{ Just in time to defend the 8th rank and finish development. The position is dynamically balanced, but playing with a queen is always easier. }
