1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6
{ Now White has 3 alternative moves to the main lines. These are 5.g3, 5.e3 and 5.Qc2. }
5. g3
{ With this move, White transposes to the Catalan, but with the queen's knight already on c3. }
5... O-O 6. Bg2 dxc4
{ The problem for Black is that if he plays in the same way as in the Closed System of the Catalan with  6...c6  then after  7.O-O  Nbd7  White can use the free d2-square for the move  8.Nd2  and with e4 coming next, White can claim an advantage. By taking on c4, Black temporarily wins a pawn and forces White to be precise in order not to remain a pawn down for nothing. }
7. O-O
{ In case of  7.Qa4  a6  8.Qxc4  b5  followed by ...Bb7 and ...c5. Black has no problems. }
7... Nc6
{ Developing the knight on c6 exerts pressure on d4 @@StartBracket@@thus preventing a move like Ne5@@EndBracket@@ and aims to push ...e5 after ...Bd6. When Black achieves this, he will have an excellent position as after ...e5, he will immediately solve the development of the light-squared bishop. }
8. e3
{ White cements the d4-pawn so he can move the queen or the knight from f3 to attack the pawn on c4. The move   8.e4  is only visually ambitious, as after  8...a6  with ...b5 next. Black safely keeps the extra pawn. He will develop the light-squared bishop to b7 and has the idea of ...Nb4-d3 further on in the middlegame. }
8... Bd6
{ Black is playing for quick development and central play with ...e5. } 9. Nd2
e5 { Black liberates his play. } 10. d5 Na5 { Defending the pawn on c4. } 11.
Qe2 Bg4
{ Black cannot defend the pawn on c4, but he forces a concession from White before giving it back. With this attack he provokes f3, which would close the long diagonal for the bishop on g2 and will weaken White's kingside. }
12. f3 Bd7 { The bishop from d7 supports ...c6. } 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Qxc4 c6
{ This eliminates the pawn on d5 that gave White a space advantage. } 15. dxc6
Bxc6
{ Black is even better here as his position is more compact and White's bishops are passive. }
