{ With active play on the queenside after ...a4 and ...Bd7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Nbd2, 8.cxd5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black castles, and on the next move he will play ...b6 to develop the light-squared bishop on b7. }
6. Bg2 b6 { The most natural way to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. O-O
Bb7 { Now White has a wide choice. } 8. cxd5 Bxd5
{ Black takes with a bishop and keeps control over the light squares in the center. }
9. Qc2 { White intends to push e4. } 9... Bxd2
{ An important exchange - Black fights for the light squares by eliminating a piece that controls them. }
10. Bxd2 Nc6
{ Black's strategy is a light-square one. The knight is safe on c6, defended by the bishop, and it exerts pressure on White's center. }
11. e3 { Defending the pawn on d4. } 11... a5 { Expanding on the queenside. }
12. Rfc1 Rc8
{ Defending the pawn on c7 in advance and allowing the knight from c6 to move to free the way for the ...c5 push. Note that White's bishop pair isn't felt - the dominant bishop on d5 limits the movement of both the knight on f3 and the bishop on g2 while the bishop on d2 is limited by both its own and Black's pawns. Black can continue to improve his position with moves like ...Qe7, ...h6, ...Rfd8 and then can try to push ...c5 by moving the knight from c6 to b8. }
*

