{ After   9.Rd1  Bd6  Black is ready to push ...c5, having retreated the bishop from b4 so it's not left stranded after the pawn comes to c5. If White plays  10.e4  now we have a very similar position as after   9.a3  Bd6  10.e4 }
9... Bd6 10. b4 c5 { Black is fully prepared for this confrontation. } 11. cxd5
exd5
{ Here it is ok to take with the pawn first because taking with a piece loses one after   11...Bxd5?  12.e4  and e5 next. Secondly, taking with the pawn offers Black good play because of the open files on the queenside. }
12. dxc5 bxc5 13. bxc5 Nxc5
{ With very active play for Black after putting the rooks on c8 and e8 and activating the bishop via a6. }
