{ Black finishes development and prepares ...c5. } 9. a3
{ After   9.Rd1  Bd6  Black is ready to push ...c5, having retreated the bishop from b4 so it's not left stranded after the pawn comes to c5. If White plays  10.e4  now we have a very similar position as after   9.a3  Bd6  10.e4 }
9... Bd6 10. e4 Nxe4 { Black exchanges everything on e4. } 11. Nxe4 dxe4 12.
Ng5 Nf6 13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Bxe4 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 Qd7
{ With an equal position. Black can try to use the light squares on the queenside by ...Qa4 or he can fix the d4-pawn by ...c6 and then start to attack it by doubling @@StartBracket@@or tripling@@EndBracket@@ on the d-file and ...Be7-f6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Nbd2, 8.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black castles, and on the next move he will play ...b6 to develop the light-squared bishop on b7. }
6. Bg2 b6 { The most natural way to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. O-O
Bb7 { Now White has a wide choice. } 8. a3 Be7
{ The bishop drops back all the way to e7 because of a detail in the line after 9.b4, which I point out. }
9. cxd5 exd5
{ A rare case where Black takes with a pawn, but the reason is that White is quick to push e4 after   9...Bxd5  10.Re1  with e4-e5 and Ne4 to come. Now Black wants to continue with ...c5 with active play. }
10. b4 { White tries to prevent Black's ...c5. } 10... a5
{ Attacking White's queenside. } 11. b5 c6
{ Black opens the game on the queenside. He will obtain good control over the light-squares there. }
12. bxc6 Nxc6 13. Bb2 a4
{ An important move - Black wants to push his queenside pawns, but the immediate   13...b5  is met by  14.Nb3  immediately targeting the weakened c5-square. Therefore, Black first takes away the b3-square from the White knight and only then pushes ...b5. }
14. Ne5 b5
{ Black expands on the queenside and establishes firm control over the light-squares. }
15. Qb1 { White tries to establish a blockade with Bc3-b4 } 15... Qb6
{ Attacking the pawn on d4. The immediate   15...Na5  is met by  16.Bc3 } 16.
Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Bc3 Rfc8
{ Black has good play here. He wants to double on the c-file and reroute the bishop from c6 to f5 via d7  @@StartBracket@@once the queen leaves the b1-h7 diagonal@@EndBracket@@. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Nbd2, 8.a3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black castles, and on the next move he will play ...b6 to develop the light-squared bishop on b7. }
6. Bg2 b6 { The most natural way to develop the light-squared bishop. } 7. O-O
Bb7 { Now White has a wide choice. } 8. a3 Be7
{ The bishop drops back all the way to e7 because of a detail in the line after 9.b4, which I point out. }
9. b4 c5
{ Black strikes in the center, preventing a further White expansion by c5. }
10. bxc5 bxc5 11. Rb1 Qc8
{ Defending the bishop and liberating the d8-square for the rook. The queen is a bit safer on c8 than on c7, avoiding possible attacks after Bf4. }
12. Bb2
{ It is in this position that the subtle point of 8...Be7 is revealed. Had the bishop been on d6, White could have played dxc5, attacking the bishop, and after ...Bxc5 then Nb3, continuing to attack the bishop and obtaining some initiative. Here however, with the bishop on e7, the move   12.dxc5  is met by  12...Nbd7  and then ...Nxc5 with very comfortable play for Black. }
12... Nbd7
{ Black is fully developed and ready for the middlegame. He can further improve his position by ...Rd8, ...Qc7 etc. A sample line is: }
13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Qc2 Ncd7
{ Opening the c-file so that there are no problems in case of Rc1 and cxd5. Black also wants to take on c4 and exchange queens. }
15. Rfc1 dxc4 16. Qxc4
{ White cannot take with knight because after   16.Nxc4?  Be4  he loses the exchange. }
16... Qxc4 17. Nxc4 Be4 { Removing the bishop from the open file with tempo. }
18. Ra1 Rfc8 { With equality in the endgame. } *

