10. cxd5 Nxd5
{ Following the principle not to take with pawn when the bishop is still on b7. }
11. Nxd7 { White exchanges on d7 to avoid ...Nxe5. } 11... Qxd7 12. e4 Nf6 13.
e5 Nd5 14. Ne4 Rad8
{ Black finished development and is ready for the middlegame. His ideas are to push ...c5, to push ...f5 @@StartBracket@@as a defence against a possible kingside attack@@EndBracket@@ or to use the queen on the queenside with ideas ...Qa4-c2 @@StartBracket@@naturally, when the white queen leaves d1@@EndBracket@@. A useful defensive idea is to drop back the bishop on a8 so that it is defended, thus avoiding possible tricks along the long diagonal. Here's a sample line: }
15. Re1 Ba8 { Now all Black's pieces are protected. } 16. h4 h6
{ Preventing a possible Bg5 or Ng5. } 17. Qg4 f5
{ A powerful defensive idea that kills off White's attack. } 18. exf6 Nxf6 19.
Nxf6+ Rxf6 20. Bxa8 Rxa8
{ Black has good play here. The pawns on d4 and e6 compensate each other and Black has the better bishop @@StartBracket@@all white pawns are on dark squares, thus limiting the white bishop@@EndBracket@@ and active play on the d- and f-files. Another important point is that Black can safely use the light squares on d5 and f5 thanks to the pawn on e6. }
