[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "White Plays 5.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Nc3 dxc4 { Black takes the pawn on c4 immediately. } 6. Bg2 Bd7
{ Without spending time on castling, Black wants to solve the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop by developing it on c6. }
7. Ne5
{ The only way for White to fight for an advantage is to exchange the bishop on c6 for a knight. }
7... Bc6
{ Black continues with the plan and doesn't mind the exchange because after }
8. Nxc6 Nxc6
{ He has successfully solved the development problems and all his pieces are active, exerting pressure on White's center. }
9. Qa4
{ This is an alternative, threatening to win a piece by taking on c6 with check and then taking the bishop on b4. }
9... Nd5 { Blocking the long diagonal and preventing White's threat. } 10. a3
{ After  10.O-O  O-O   @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp2ppp/2n1pn2/8/1bpP4/2N3P1/PP2PPBP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line starting with  9.O-O  O-O  10.Qa4  Nd5  for more information on this line, clickhere. }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Nb6
{ Black successfully managed to defend the pawn on c4 to not remain a pawn down. White is forced to take on c6 and enter an equal endgame. }
12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxc6+ Qd7 14. Qxd7+ Kxd7
{ The endgame is very good for Black because his knight has more prospects than White's bishop that is limited by its own pawns on dark squares. This also implies that White has light-square weaknesses, the b3-square in particular. }
*

