10... Nd5 { Shutting the long diagonal. } 11. Nc6 Qe8 12. a4
{ White finds it difficult to return the pawn, so he tries to obtain compensation by undermining Black's pawn chain. }
12... Ba6 { Black develops and defends the pawn on b5. } 13. b3 Nc3
{ Black establishes a strong knight on c3 that he will support with ...b4. This move also forces the white queen to go to e1. }
14. Qe1 cxb3 { Black first exchanges pawns and then supports his knight. } 15.
Nxb3 b4
{ Black has an excellent position. He is still a pawn up and all his pieces are active. He would like to continue with ...Nf6-d5. Note that White cannot take the exchange as after }
16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bxa8 { Because after } 17... Nxe2+
{ Black returns the exchange and wins another pawn in the process. } 18. Kg2
Nxf4+ 19. gxf4 Bxf1+ 20. Qxf1 Rxa8 { Black is two pawns up and is winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "Main Line 8.Bf4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 { This is the most popular choice. } 5... Be7
{ Having forced White to put the bishop on d2, Black retreats and continues with the usual development. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ...c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ... dxc4 and ...b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Bf4
{ White improves the position of the bishop immediately, but this is another line where having a knight on d7 instead of a pawn on c6 is in Black's favor. }
8... dxc4
{ Black takes the undefended pawn, which opens up two options for him. First, Black threatens to defend the pawn on c4 by ...b5, and second, the capture liberates the d5-square for the knight, from where it will attack the bishop on f4. }
9. a4
{ This stops ...b5, but Black can use the other idea of ...dxc4 - the d5-square for the knight. }
9... Nd5 { Attacking the bishop on f4. } 10. Qc1 c5
{ Here's another benefit from not rushing with ...c6. The pawn advances to c5 in one go. }
11. Rd1 Nxf4
{ Taking the bishop and forcing White to take with pawn because the queen needs to stay on c1 to keep an eye on the c4-pawn. }
12. gxf4 cxd4 { Releasing the tension in the center. } 13. Qxc4 Bf6
{ Black places the bishop on the long diagonal in order to support the ...e5-push. }
14. Nxd4 e5
{ After this liberating move, Black equalizes easily. Even more so, after } 15.
Nf3 exf4 16. Nc3 Bxc3
{ This forces White to wreck his structure because the queen wants to take the pawn on f4. }
17. bxc3 Qe7 { Moving away from the pin on the d-file. } 18. Qxf4 Nc5
{ Black can even claim a better pawn structure and a safer king. } *

