9. Qc2 { White goes after the pawn on c4. } 9... Nd5
{ With a queen on c2 that also looks down the b1-h7 diagonal, Black cannot keep the c4-pawn by   9...b5  because after  10.a4  c6?  11.axb5  cxb5  12.Ng5  wins for White - the rook on a8 has nowhere to go and the move  12...Nd5?  is met with  13.Qxh7# }
10. Qxc4 Nxf4 { Taking the bishop and doubling White's f-pawns. } 11. gxf4 b5
{ A strong move that immediately solves Black's problems with the light-squared bishop. }
12. Qxb5
{ If White doesn't take then Black has easy play after   12.Qc2  Bb7  With the bishop pair, he will follow up with ...c5 and will have a very good game. }
12... Rb8
{ Here's the move 7...Nbd7 helping again - the rook enters the game via the open b-file and attacks the pawn on b2. }
13. Qa4 Rxb2 { The pawn on e2 hangs, so White defends it with his next move. }
14. Nbd2 c5
{ Liberating Black's game. Black is at least equal here, he has the bishop pair, the better structure @@StartBracket@@now that the pawn on c7 is no longer a backward one@@EndBracket@@ and the safer king. Now Black wants to play ... Qc7, to defend the pawn on a7 and attack the pawn on f5. If White takes the a7-pawn, }
15. Qxa7 { Then after } 15... Rb7
{ Black's activity allows him to return the material. For example, } 16. Qa4
cxd4 { Black threatens ...Rb4. } 17. Qxd4 Rb4 18. Qe3 Bc5
{ The queen can no longer defend the pawn on f4. } *

