1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 { This is the most popular choice. } 5... Be7
{ Having forced White to put the bishop on d2, Black retreats and continues with the usual development. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ...c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ... dxc4 and ...b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. a4
{ White takes some space on the queenside. He prevents a possible ...b5 and wants to expand with a5. }
8... a5 { Black naturally stops White's expansion and fixes the hole on b4. }
9. Na3
{ White defends the pawn on  c4  . In case of  9.Qc2  c6   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnbppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP1BPPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 7 8@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the lines after  8.Qc2  c6  9.a4  a5 }
9... c6
{ Black continues with his intended development. He plans ...b6 and ...Bb7 or ...Ba6. }
10. Rc1
{ The move  10.Qc2   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pppnbppp/4pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PP1BPPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 7 8@@EndFEN@@ would again transpose to  8.Qc2  c6  9.a4  a5  10.Na3 }
10... Nb6
{ An important motif in these positions. Black attacks the pawn on c4 @@StartBracket@@he wants to take ...Bxa3 and win the pawn on c4@@EndBracket@@ and forces White to define the structure on the queenside. }
11. Ne5
{ Defending the pawn. After  11.c5  Nbd7  Black has great play as he undermines White's pawn chain by ...b6 next. This is particularly strong as White cannot play b4 to support his c5-pawn. }
11... Nfd7
{ Black continues the pressure on White's queenside by challenging the knight on e5 that defends the pawn on c4. }
12. Nxd7 Nxd7
{ Black takes with the knight as taking with another piece would render that knight awkward after c5 as it won't have a good square to go to. Now with one pair of light pieces exchanged, Black can be content with his position, as the lack of space isn't felt. He will continue with ... Nf6, ...Bd6, ...b6 and develop the light-squared bishop. }
