8. Na3 { White defends the pawn on c4. } 8... b6
{ Since there is no pressure in the center, Black can do without the move ...c6 and can develop the light-squared bishop to b7 faster. }
9. Rc1 Bxa3
{ An important exchange. Black doubles White's a-pawns and gains tempo for development. }
10. bxa3 Bb7 11. cxd5 Bxd5
{ The active bishop on d5 limits White's activity. Black has excellent control over the light squares, and he will follow up with ...c5. White's pair of bishops isn't felt because the bishop on g2 is out of play. If White wants to involve the g2-bishop, he must move the knight from f3, and this would lead to its exchange when White no longer has the pair of bishops. }
