9. Bc3
{ With wants to develop the knight to d2. Note that the move   9.Qc2  transposes to the lines after 8.Qc2. }
9... b6 { Black follows his plan. } 10. Nbd2 Bb7 11. e3 c5
{ Black achieved his aim - he developed harmoniously, solved the problem of the light-squared bishop and executed the liberating move ...c5. }
12. Qe2
{ White wants to put the rooks in the center, which would make the position of Black's queen somewhat unpleasant. That's what Black sets out to solve next. }
12... Rc8
{ The rook is placed on the c-file, and at the same time, Black intends to tuck away the queen by ...Qc7-b8, the same maneuver Black employs in the Reti Opening. }
13. Rfd1 Qc7 { Moving away from the d-file. } 14. Rac1 Qb8
{ Now moving away from the c-file. With ...Rfd8 next, Black is ready for any confrontation in the center. The only thing to remember is that Black should always recapture with a piece wherever White takes, c5 or d5. }
