8. Qb3
{ White defends the pawn on c4 just like after   8.Qc2  but this move allows Black to try to harass the queen by }
8... a5
{ Black plays a useful move on the queenside that also introduces a typical tactical idea. }
9. Nc3
{ This is a possibility allowed for by the queen on b3, as the queen defends the pawn on c4 and the knight can be developed on the most natural square. However here, Black uses the tactical transformation that is made possible by the pawn being on a5. }
9... c6 { First, Black defends the attacked pawn on d5. } 10. Rfd1 a4
{ This is the tactical possibility that allows Black to favorably transform the position. }
11. Nxa4 dxc4 { Black exchanged his a-pawn for White's c-pawn. } 12. Qc2
{ Obviously,   12.Qxc4?  b5  wins a piece for Black - this is the justification of the move 10...a4. }
12... b5
{ Black defends the pawn on c4 and liberates the b7-square for the bishop. }
13. Nc3 Bb7
{ Black finished development and has good prospects in the following complex middlegame. His main idea is to push ...c5, but this needs to be prepared by ...Qb6 first. If White advances in the center with e4-e5, then Black will obtain the d5-square for his knight, for example }
14. e4 h6
{ A useful move, opening luft for the king, controlling the g5-square and awaiting White's advance. }
15. a4 { An attempt to undermine Black's queenside. } 15... b4 16. e5 Nd5
{ The knight slots in nicely on d5. } 17. Ne4 c5
{ Starting immediate central counterplay. The point is that after } 18. Qxc4
Ba6 { Black regains the pawn because the queen cannot defend the pawn on d4: }
19. Qb3 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Nxe5 { With very active play for Black. } *

