{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. Rd1 b6 { Continuing with the usual plan of development. } 10. b3
{ The moves  10.a4  a5  11.b3  Ba6  transpose to the lines after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PPQBPPBP/RN3RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.a4  a5  10.b3  b6  11.Rd1  Ba6   while the move  10.Bf4  transposes to the lines after 9.Bf4. }
10... a5
{ A useful move for Black that keeps the option to develop the bishop to both b7 and a6. Now White needs to decide where to develop the bishop from d2: to c3 or to f4. }
11. Bc3 Bb7
{ Since now White can comfortably defend the pawn on c4 by Nbd2, Black develops the bishop on b7. }
12. Nbd2 Qc7
{ Black prepares ...c5, avoiding the complications after  12...c5  13.Ne5 } 13.
e4 { This is the main idea of White's set-up. } 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 c5
{ This move frees Black's position as it opens the light-squared bishop. } 15.
Nxf6+ Bxf6
{ This is the precise recapture, keeping control over the e5-square and exerting pressure on the pawn on d4. Now Black wants to take on d4 forcing simplifications and it's important that White's attempt to punish Black with }
16. d5 { Backfires after } 16... exd5 17. cxd5 Rad8
{ As now Black threatens to take on c3 and play ...Nf6, when the pawn on d5 turns out to be very difficult to defend. }
