1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 { This is the most popular choice. } 5... Be7
{ Having forced White to put the bishop on d2, Black retreats and continues with the usual development. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ...c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ... dxc4 and ...b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. a4 a5 { Black stops the advance of the a-pawn and fixes the hole on b4. }
10. Bf4 b6
{ The bishop on f4 is exposed to an attack by ...Nd5, so Black can continue with ...b6 because after }
11. cxd5 Nxd5 { He threatens the bishop on f4. } 12. Qxc6
{ This is critical, but Black has enough activity as compensation. In case of   12.Nc3  Nxf4  13.gxf4  Bb7  Black is compact with the bishop pair and the better pawn structure. }
12... Ba6
{ Threatening both ...Rc8 and ...Bxe2, so White's next move is forced. } 13.
Qc2 Rc8 { Black has a tremendous initiative. } 14. Nc3 N7f6
{ Piling up the pressure, the threats are many: ...Bb4, ...Nxc3 @@StartBracket@@or ...Nxf4@@EndBracket@@ and ...Nd5. }
15. Rfc1 Bb4 16. Bd2 Bxe2
{ Black regained the pawn with an excellent position. His pieces are very active and he has great activity in this position with an IQP. }
