8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. a4 a5 { Black stops the advance of the a-pawn and fixes the hole on b4. }
10. Rc1
{ Similar to the line 9.Rc1, White anticipates the opening of the c-file. }
10... h6
{ A difficult move at first sight, but the logic is the following: since White has a strong presence on the c-file, Black doesn't want to play ...b6 just yet. Instead, he plays a useful move @@StartBracket@@a luft for the king@@EndBracket@@ and will adjust his reaction based on White's moves, which, surprisingly, allow for a more comfortable version of the ...b6 plan. To illustrate the point, the immediate   10...b6  is met by  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  Ba6  13.Nb5  Rc8  14.Qb3  with initiative. }
11. Bf4 Ne4
{ Black cannot play ...b6 with the bishop being active on f4, so he activates the knight from f6. }
12. Na3 Bb4
{ The bishop finds a comfortable spot on b4. Black slowly untangles and wants to develop the queen to e7. The aggressive options of ...f5 and ...g5 can also be played in certain positions. Without ...b6, White's play on the queenside is at a dead end, so he needs to start reshuffling his pieces. }
13. Rd1 Qe7
{ Black moved his pieces forward and now with their more active placement, he can continue with ...b6, not fearing problems along the c-file. }
14. Rac1 b6 15. Ne5
{ Now   15.cxd5  cxd5  16.Nb5  Ba6  is harmless because Black's rooks are already connected and he can play ...Rc8 next. }
15... Nxe5 16. Bxe4 { Or   16.Bxe5  Nd6  attacking the pawn on c4. } 16... Bxa3
{ The pawn on c4 is hanging so White must take the knight on e5. } 17. Bxe5 Bb4
{ With an equal position as Black develops his light-squared bishop next. For example, }
18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bd3 Bd7 { With no problems for Black. } *

