{ A difficult move at first sight, but the logic is the following: since White has a strong presence on the c-file, Black doesn't want to play ...b6 just yet. Instead, he plays a useful move @@StartBracket@@a luft for the king@@EndBracket@@ and will adjust his reaction based on White's moves, which, surprisingly, allow for a more comfortable version of the ...b6 plan. To illustrate the point, the immediate   10...b6  is met by  11.cxd5  cxd5  12.Nc3  Ba6  13.Nb5  Rc8  14.Qb3  with initiative. }
11. Na3
{ White keeps the knight ready to jump to b5, but the knight's position allows for a tactical solution for Black's problems. }
11... b6 { This is possible thanks to a small tactical detail. } 12. cxd5 Nxd5
{ With the weakened b4-square this is the logical recapture, especially as taking with the c-pawn allows Nb5. }
13. e4
{ If   13.Qxc6  Ba6  threatens both ...Rc8 to trap the queen and ...Bxe2, so Black is assured to regain the pawn. }
13... Nb4 { Black defends the pawn on c6 and attacks the queen. } 14. Bxb4 axb4
{ This is the tactical detail that justifies Black's 11...b6. Recapturing with the pawn wins a tempo by attacking the knight on a3, thus avoiding the loss of the c6-pawn. }
15. Nc4 Qc7
{ Black has the bishop pair and a compact position. He will play ...Bb7, ...Rfd8, ...Qb8 and will seek ways to open the game by pushing ...c5 at an appropriate moment. }
