1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 { This is the most popular choice. } 5... Be7
{ Having forced White to put the bishop on d2, Black retreats and continues with the usual development. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ...c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ... dxc4 and ...b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. Bf4
{ White activates the bishop, but there are also quite a few alternatives. }
9... b6 { Black continues with the plan to develop the light-squared bishop. }
10. Nbd2 { White plans e4, but keeps the pawn on c4 protected. } 10... Bb7
{ Black finishes development and is now ready to push ...c5. } 11. e4
{ If White takes one more move by playing   11.Rfd1  then after  11...c5  Black solves his problems immediately. }
11... dxc4
{ Black takes on c4 in order to keep White's pawn on e4, which he will attack after ...c5 comes on the next move. }
12. Nxc4 c5
{ Black is fine already, having accomplished the liberating ...c5, though he should know the follow-up because White can try to use the d6-square. }
13. Rfe1 cxd4 14. Nd6
{ Black was threatening ...Rc8, so there was no time for   14.Nxd4?  Rc8  with ...Ba6 and ...b5 to come. }
14... Bxd6 15. Bxd6 Rc8
{ Black develops the rook with tempo before dealing with the attack on f8. }
16. Qd3 { If   16.Qa4  Nc5  17.Qxd4  we transpose back to the same line. }
16... Nc5
{ The knight is very good on c5, it also attacks the pawn on e4, which becomes relevant when Black moves the rook on the next move. }
17. Qxd4 Re8
{ Now Black threatens to take on e4, so White doesn't have a choice but to advance the pawn. }
18. e5 Nfe4 { Black makes sure that the bishop on d6 is eliminated. } 19. b4
Nxd6 { Capturing the active bishop. } 20. exd6
{ In case of   20.bxc5  Nf5  Black is more than fine. } 20... Nd7
{ Black's position is very compact. His plan is to round up the pawn on d6 by ...Bd5 and ...Nf6. In case of mass exchanges, the pawn on d6 may easily become weak in the endgame as Black's king is closer to it than White's. }
