[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6: The Catalan"]
[Black "Main Line 8.Qc2, 9.Bf4 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
{ White can also start with  3.g3  Nf6  4.Bg2  but after  4...Bb4  we will have a transposition to the usual lines after White plays Nf3. }
3... Nf6 4. g3
{ The Catalan Opening is one of the most popular choices for White against the QGD. It is a complex opening full of subtleties where inexperienced players easily go astray. The proposed repertoire aims to simplify Black's task by going for a universal set-up, already seen in the main line with 5.Bf4: after castling Black puts the queen's knight on d7 and then in the majority of cases goes ...c6 and ...b6, developing the light-squared bishop on b7. }
4... Bb4+
{ This is the first subtlety. The idea of the check is to force a white piece on d2, neither of which will be well-placed: the bishop will have to move again later and the knight will be rather passive. The third option, 5.Nc3, makes it difficult for White to recapture the pawn on c4 after Black plays ...dxc4. }
5. Bd2 { This is the most popular choice. } 5... Be7
{ Having forced White to put the bishop on d2, Black retreats and continues with the usual development. }
6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O Nbd7
{ The second subtlety. Black doesn't rush with ...c6 and first develops the knight in order to have options like ... dxc4 and ...b5, in which case the free b8-square for the rook comes in handy. The knight also supports the ...c5 push in one go. }
8. Qc2 { The most common move, but White has a wide choice here. } 8... c6
{ Black strengthens the center and prepares the fianchetto of his light-squared bishop. }
9. Bf4
{ White activates the bishop, but there are also quite a few alternatives. }
9... b6 { Black continues with the plan to develop the light-squared bishop. }
10. Rd1
{ The rook on the d-file discourages attempts based on ...c5 because after the opening of the d-file, the black queen on  d8  may turn out to be vulnerable. Note that after  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Rc1  Bb7   @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/pp1nbppp/2p1pn2/3p4/2PP4/5NP1/PPQBPPBP/RN3RK1 w - - 0 9@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the lines after  9.Rc1  b6  10.cxd5  cxd5  11.Bf4  Bb7   Another transposition is  10.b3  which after  10...a5  11.Rd1  Ba6   transposes to  9.Rd1  b6  10.b3  a5  11.Bf4  Ba6   The move  10.Nc3  allows  10...dxc4  and after  11.Nd2  Nd5  12.Nxc4  Nxf4  13.gxf4  Bb7  14.Rfd1   we have a transposition to the line after  10.Rd1  Bb7  11.Nc3  dxc4  12.Nd2  Nd5  13.Nxc4  Nxf4  14.gxf4 }
10... Bb7 { Black finished development and now his aim is to push ...c5. } 11.
Ne5 Nxe5
{ Black takes the centralized knight. The most popular move here is  11...Nh5  but that allows a repetition after  12.Bd2   12.Bc1  12...Nhf6  13.Bf4  and this may sometimes be a problem for the Black player. }
12. dxe5
{ White opens the d-file and plans to attack Black's pawn on d5 by e4. } 12...
Nd7 { Covering the d-file. } 13. cxd5
{ The immediate  13.e4?  allows  13...dxc4  14.Qxc4  Qc7  when White has problems with the e5-pawn. Therefore, White takes on d5 to avoid the capture on c4. }
13... exd5
{ The more combative recapture. Now the structure is asymmetrical and Black will have counterchances thanks to his queenside majority and good central control. Black can certainly play for equality after the more common  13...cxd5  Here are a few illustrative lines:  14.e4  dxe4  15.Bxe4  Bxe4  16.Qxe4  Nc5  17.Qf3  Qe8  18.Nc3  a5!  @@StartBracket@@preventing b4 and securing the knight's position on c5@@EndBracket@@ when Black should hold the balance.     White can also try  14.e4  dxe4  15.Nc3  Qc8  16.Bxe4  Nc5  17.Bxb7  Qxb7  18.b4  Nd7  19.Qe4  Qxe4  20.Nxe4  Rfd8  when the endgame is equal as Black will undermine that pawn on e5 with ...f6 next. These lines are relatively safe for Black, while with the more dynamic recapture, Black obtains more practical chances. }
14. e4 { White continues with his plan to attack down the d-file. } 14... d4
{ Black doesn't want to activate White's light-squared bishop by taking on e4. He will regain the pawn as the one on e5 is impossible to defend. }
15. Rxd4 Bc5 { Liberating the e7-square for the queen. } 16. Rd2
{ This will allow White to double the rooks later on. } 16... Qe7
{ Black regains the pawn and now a complex middlegame ensues. } 17. e6 fxe6
{ A dynamic recapture that opens the f-file for counterplay. } 18. Na3
{ The natural  18.Nc3?  would be a mistake as after  18...e5  the bishop on f4 is short of squares, as going to e3 allows for the doubling of White's pawns after  19.Be3  Bxe3  20.fxe3  Nf6  which is quite ugly for White. }
18... Nf6
{ Now after  18...e5  White has  19.Be3  Bxe3  20.Qb3  and then Qxe3. Here we see the idea behind 18.Na3, which was go leave the 3rd rank open. }
19. Nc4 Rad8
{ Challenging the d-file. Black has good counterchances here, he has ideas like ...Bd4 and ...c5. }
