[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "White Plays 2.Bf4, 3.c3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. c3
{ The move  3.Nc3   is a transposition to theJobava Variation that is analyzed after  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3 }
3... c5
{ Black plays the same move as in the main line, attacking the center with the c-pawn before developing the knight on c6. }
4. Bxb8
{ Exchanging the only developed piece is very risky, as taking the pawn gives Black a dangerous initiative. }
4... Rxb8 5. dxc5 { This is another way to take a pawn, but after } 5... e5
{ Black has the full center, the bishop pair and development advantage as compensation. }
6. b4
{ The only way to defend the pawn on  c5  . In case of  6.Qa4  Bd7  7.Qxa7  Qc8  White's queen is in grave danger as Black threatens ...Bxc5 or ...Ra8-a6. }
6... Bd7
{ The idea of this move is to play ...b6 next, and prevent the pawn from c5 advancing to c6 in that case. }
7. e3 { If  7.Nf3  then  7...Qc7  followed by ...b6. } 7... b6 8. cxb6 Rxb6
{ Black eliminated the space-grabbing pawn on c5 and can now develop his dark-squared bishop on the active d6-square. }
9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Be2 O-O
{ Black has excellent play here. Apart from the full center and the bishop pair, he can exert pressure on the queenside along the c-file, and targeting the backward pawn on c3. This makes it difficult for White to create any active play. }
*

