{ The move  3.Nc3   is a transposition to theJobava Variation that is analyzed after  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3 }
3... c5
{ Black plays the same move as in the main line, attacking the center with the c-pawn before developing the knight on c6. }
4. Bxb8
{ Exchanging the only developed piece is very risky, as taking the pawn gives Black a dangerous initiative. }
4... Rxb8 5. Qa4+ { This wins the pawn on a7, but it sidelines the queen. }
5... Bd7 6. Qxa7 Ra8 { Now whichever pawn White takes, he is in trouble. } 7.
Qxb7 { After  7.Qxc5  e5  the queen is trapped. } 7... cxd4 8. cxd4
{ After  8.Nf3  Rb8  followed by ...Rxb2. Black has fantastic activity as compensation. }
8... e5
{ Opening the diagonal for the bishop on f8. Black plays in typical open-game fashion when the opponent has neglected development: he speeds up his own development and doesn't mind material sacrifices to do so. An illustrative line is }
9. dxe5 Rb8 10. Qa6 Ne4
{ With threats like ...Rxb2 and ...Bb4, Black is winning. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "White Plays 2.Bf4, 3.c3 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. c3
{ The move  3.Nc3   is a transposition to theJobava Variation that is analyzed after  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3 }
3... c5
{ Black plays the same move as in the main line, attacking the center with the c-pawn before developing the knight on c6. }
4. dxc5
{ This is a better version to take a pawn, but it still gives Black excellent compensation. }
4... Nc6 { Threatening ...e5. } 5. b4
{ White defends the pawn on  c5  in advance. In case of  5.Nf3  e6  6.b4  a5  7.b5  Ne7  followed by ...Ng6. Black will capture the c5-pawn with excellent development. }
5... g6
{ With his last move, White weakened the long diagonal and Black immediately takes advantage of it. The fianchettoed bishop will be very strong and the immediate threat will be ...Ne4. }
6. Nf3 Bg7
{ Now Black threatens ...Ne4 or ...Nh5, hitting the pawns on c3 and b4 @@StartBracket@@thanks to the pin on the long diagonal@@EndBracket@@. }
7. b5
{ White removes the pawn on b4 where it would hang after Black moves the knight from f6. }
7... Na5 { Still threatening ...Ne4. } 8. Be5
{ White takes control of the long diagonal. } 8... O-O
{ Black has almost finished development, and next, he will develop the light-squared bishop to g4 to liberate the c8-square for the rook to attack the pawn on c5. }
9. e3 Bg4 10. Qd4
{ The only way for White to defend the pawn on c5, but it's apparent that his position is overstretched. }
10... Bxf3 { Black ruins White's structure even more. } 11. gxf3 a6
{ An important move, regaining access to the c6-square. } 12. Nd2
{ After  12.bxa6  Nc6  Black wins as the queen cannot defend the bishop after  13.Qf4  Nh5 }
12... axb5 13. Bxb5 Nc6
{ Forcing White to take on c6, thus connecting the pawn structure. } 14. Bxc6
bxc6
{ Black will follow up with ...Nh5 and after the exchange on g7, his knight will land on e6 from where it will attack the weak pawn on c5. Sooner or later one @@StartBracket@@or more@@EndBracket@@ of White's queenside pawns will fall. }
