1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ Note that in this position  4.Nd2  would lead us to the tabiya after  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.c3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  Therefore, we look at the alternatives. }
4. Nc3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This looks unaesthetic, but it has been tried by Carlsen and also by Jobava and Rapport. The move needs to be taken seriously, especially when White treats it in an aggressive manner and also because it can be a transposition from the Jobava line after  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3 }
4... cxd4 { Immediately releasing the central tension. } 5. exd4 a6
{ An important move, preventing any Nb5 ideas. } 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Nce2
{ This has been played by Carlsen, but it is harmless as Black can exchange the light-squared bishops. }
7... Bg4 { With the idea of ...Bh5-g6, exchanging the bishops. } 8. c3 e6 9.
Qd2 Bh5 10. Bg5 Bg6
{ Black accomplished his plan and has a very solid position. After } 11. Nf4
Bxd3 12. Nxd3 Be7 { Threatening ...Ne4. } 13. Qe2 Ne4 14. Bxe7 Nxe7
{ With an equal position. Black will keep an eye on the squares e5 and c5, and will try to organize a minority attack. }
