1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ Note that in this position  4.Nd2  would lead us to the tabiya after  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.c3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  Therefore, we look at the alternatives. }
4. Nc3
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This looks unaesthetic, but it has been tried by Carlsen and also by Jobava and Rapport. The move needs to be taken seriously, especially when White treats it in an aggressive manner and also because it can be a transposition from the Jobava line after  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  3.Bf4  c5  4.e3 }
4... cxd4 { Immediately releasing the central tension. } 5. exd4 a6
{ An important move, preventing any Nb5 ideas. } 6. Nf3 Nc6
{ This is a safer approach than the typical  6...Bg4  which after  7.h3  Bxf3  8.Qxf3  e6  allows  9.g4  when White's attack is rather annoying. }
7. Ne5
{ The only move to pose problems. The tame  7.Be2  Bf5  is problem-free for Black. }
7... Bd7
{ The bishop supports the knight on c6 and avoids the creation of a backward pawn in case of the exchange of knights. }
8. Be2
{ If White takes the bishop pair with  8.Nxd7  then after  8...Qxd7  9.Be2  e6  10.O-O  Bd6  Black has a very harmonious position. If White tries to keep the bishop pair and plays  11.Bg5  then  11...Qc7  12.h3  Qb6  puts pressure on White's center. }
8... e6 9. O-O
{ If White wants to castle queenside and plays  9.Qd3  then it is he who runs the risk to come under attack after  9...Qb6  10.O-O-O  Rc8  when Black's pieces are ready to start activities on the queenside with ...Bb4, ...Na5-c4, etc. }
9... Qb6
{ This move is an unpleasant one to meet as it attacks both d4 and b2. } 10.
Nxc6 Bxc6 11. Rb1 { Avoiding any weaknesses on the queenside. } 11... Be7
{ Black has no problems here as his position is without weaknesses, and he has smooth development. He will castle and put a rook on c8. Then, Black will try to activate the light-squared bishop via b5 or organize a minority attack on the queenside. }
