1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ Note that in this position  4.Nd2  would lead us to the tabiya after  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.c3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  Therefore, we look at the alternatives. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. Bd3
{ With this move, White prevents the development of the bishop on f5, but allows the development on g4. Again  5.Nd2  would lead to the tabiya after  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6 }
5... Bg4 6. Nf3 e6 7. Nbd2 Bd6 { Black easily finishes development. } 8. h3
Bxf3 { Not wasting time, Black simplifies the position. } 9. Qxf3 Bxf4 10. Qxf4
Qb6
{ Attacking b2 and since castling queenside would be risky, White must defend the pawn with the rook. }
11. Rb1 O-O
{ Black has an easy to play position. He will put a rook on c8 and can aim for the ...e5 push by supporting it with ...Nd7 and ...Rfe8. }
