[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "White Plays 2.Bf4, 3.e3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ Note that in this position  4.Nd2  would lead us to the tabiya after  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.c3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  Therefore, we look at the alternatives. }
4. dxc5
{ If White doesn't want to play the tabiya, this move is the most testing one. }
4... Nc6 { Threatening ...e5, so White's next is forced. } 5. Bb5
{ In case of  5.Nf3  e6  Black recaptures the pawn on c5 on the next move. }
5... Bd7
{ A rare move, but one that avoids the masses of theory after  5...Qa5   or  5...e6 }
6. a3 { Is a similar, but inferior, attempt to keep the pawn. } 6... e6
{ Note that the move  6...a5  which we play against 6.c3, is not that good here as it allows White to take advantage of the vacant c3-square for the Nc3-a4 maneuver. This sequence would defend the c5-pawn and target the b6-square. }
7. b4 a5
{ This typical undermining move is very common in these lines and here we see why 6.a3 is inferior to 6.c3. Now, Black threatens to take on b4 and the rook on a1 hangs. }
8. Bxc6
{ White tries to keep the pawn at all costs. In case of  8.Nd2  b6  White's queenside falls apart and Black returns the pawn. For example:  9.c4  axb4  10.cxb6  Qxb6  11.axb4  Rxa1  12.Qxa1  Bxb4  with equality. }
8... Bxc6 9. Nd2 b6
{ White's queenside is under immense pressure, so he must take on b6, and then defend the pawn on b4 by c3. }
10. cxb6 { Threatening Bc7 so Black needs to take on b6. } 10... Qxb6
{ Now the pawn on b4 is under attack, so White's next move is forced. } 11. c3
axb4 { Opening the a-file for the rook. } 12. cxb4
{ This is again forced for White who cannot play  12.axb4?  in view of  12...d4  when both g2 and c3 are hanging. }
12... Qa6
{ A multi-purpose move: it threatens ...Bxb4 and it also takes control of the f1-a6 diagonal, making White's castling very difficult to achieve. }
13. Nb3 { Defending the rook on a1 and preventing ...Bxb4. } 13... Bb5
{ Enhancing Black's control over the important f1-a6 diagonal and making sure White doesn't castle. }
14. Ne2 Be7 { Finishing development. } 15. Ned4 Ba4
{ Black has excellent compensation here. White's queenside pawns are not going anywhere as they are blockaded on the light squares that Black dominates on. White has problems with the king stuck in the center while Black has the bishop pair and the idea to castle and play ...Nd7 to push ...e5. }
