1. d4 d5 2. Bf4
{ This is an alternative move-order, that will often lead to the tabiya that arises after Black's 8th move. Black is not bothered by the various move orders. Interestingly, Black concentrating on studying the tabiya is a practical aspect of this variation against the London System. Here, we will take a look at alternative White attempts that do not transpose to the mainline. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 c5
{ Note that in this position  4.Nd2  would lead us to the tabiya after  4...cxd4  5.exd4  Nc6  6.c3  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Ngf3  e6  Therefore, we look at the alternatives. }
4. dxc5
{ If White doesn't want to play the tabiya, this move is the most testing one. }
4... Nc6 { Threatening ...e5, so White's next is forced. } 5. Bb5
{ In case of  5.Nf3  e6  Black recaptures the pawn on c5 on the next move. }
5... Bd7
{ A rare move, but one that avoids the masses of theory after  5...Qa5   or  5...e6 }
6. c3
{ After abandoning the center by taking on c5, White's only positional trump is the extra pawn, so he tries to defend it by pushing b4. }
6... a5
{ An important move, preventing b4 and ensuring that Black recaptures the pawn after ...e6 and ... Bxc5. }
7. Nf3
{ Note that White cannot defend the pawn on c5 by means of  7.Nd2  e6  8.Bxc6  Bxc6  9.b4  in view of  9...d4  and Black wins thanks to the weakness of the g2 and c3 pawns. }
7... e6 8. c4
{ White cannot defend the pawn on c5, so he becomes active in the center. In case of  8.Bxc6  Bxc6  9.b4  axb4  10.cxb4  b6  White's queenside collapses and Black will get the pawn back with a better position. }
8... Bxc5
{ Black regained the pawn and has a good position with smooth development, somewhat resembling the lines from the QGD. }
9. Nc3 dxc4
{ Releasing the tension in the center and gaining tempo to castle. } 10. Bxc4
O-O 11. O-O Ne7
{ A good move. The knight is transferred to g6 from where it will still control the e5-square, and it liberates the c6-square for the light-squared bishop. }
12. Ne5 Be8
{ The bishop retreats temporarily as Black's next will be ...Ng6, challenging the knight on e5. With ...Bc6 soon to follow, with other ideas being ...a4 and ...Qa5 or ...Qb6, Black has no problems. }
