1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. dxc5
{ is the only independent try, but it's dubious. White advances with the pawns too early and they can only be attacked by Black later on. The following analysis shows that Black has easy play that can quickly give him an advantage. }
5... e6 6. b4 a5 { Attacking White's queenside in typical fashion. } 7. Nd4
{ is an attempt to keep the extra pawn, but it leads to a lost position for White. }
7... axb4 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. cxb4 Ng4
{ An important move, the threat is ...Qf6, hitting the bishop on f4 and the rook on a1. }
10. Qd4 { Defending against ...Qf6, but running into } 10... e5 11. Bxe5 Nxe5
12. Qxe5+ Be7
{ White cannot take on g7 because of...Bf6, winning a rook. On his next move, Black will castle, and his initiative will be overwhelming after ...Re8, ...Bf6, ...Bf5, and so on. A sample line is }
13. a3 O-O 14. Qg3 Re8
{ The rook occupies the semi-open e-file and this will introduce ...d4 ideas. }
15. e3 Bf6 16. Ra2 Bf5 17. Nd2 Bc3
{ And with ...d4 next. Black crashes through. } *

