1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. c3 Nc6 5. dxc5
{ is the only independent try, but it's dubious. White advances with the pawns too early and they can only be attacked by Black later on. The following analysis shows that Black has easy play that can quickly give him an advantage. }
5... e6 6. b4 a5 { Attacking White's queenside in typical fashion. } 7. b5 Ne7
{ Now, Black wants to move the knight from e7 to g6/f5 and capture on c5, when he is clearly better because of White's weaknesses of his prematurely-advanced queenside. White can try several moves here, but he is worse everywhere. }
8. e3
{ A few words about the alternatives. These are minor lines and this is for illustrative purposes to show the difficulties White is in. In case of  8.Nbd2  Ng6  9.Be3  White still doesn't succeed in keeping the pawn after  9...e5  threatening ...Ng4  10.h3  a4  controlling the b3-square and not allowing a4 and Nb3 with ...Qc7 and ...Bc5 next.   The move  8.Bd6  is met by  8...Ne4  while   8.b6  is met by  8...Nc6  9.Bc7  Qd7  with ...Bxc5 next. }
8... Ng6 9. c6
{ If the bishop moves,  9.Bg3  Bxc5  Black has great play after ...O-O, ...b6, and ...Bb7 when he has smooth development and play against White's queenside weaknesses. }
9... bxc6 10. bxc6 Nxf4 11. exf4 Bc5
{ Placing the bishop on an active square and threatening ...Qb6. } 12. Bd3 Qb6
{ A double attack on f2 and c6. } 13. O-O Qxc6
{ Black regained the pawn and stands better. He has the better structure and the bishop pair, while White needs to find out what to do with the weak pawn on c3. }
