[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "Kamsky's 5.Bb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Bb5
{ This is considered dubious after the famous Kamsky-Gelfand game from their Candidates match in 2007. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Qa5+
{ A necessary check that forces the knight to come to c3, thus disturbing the harmony of White's position. In this reversed Carlsbad structure, the desired move is c3. }
7. Nc3 Bg4
{ Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6. } 8.
O-O e6
{ The position resembles a reversed Ragozin where Black has easy play on the queenside, while White still needs to reroute the awkward knight on c3. Please see the model game,Kamsky-Gelfand, to see how Black should play these positions. }
