1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Be2 { This is harmless as after the typical development } 5... cxd4
6. exd4 Bf5 7. c3 e6
{ We have arrived at the tabiya where White has prematurely developed his bishop on e2. }
8. Nh4
{ In case of  8.Nbd2  Black has time for  8...h6  to secure the position of his bishop. }
8... Nh5 { A nice retort worth remembering. } 9. Bxh5 Qxh4
{ With no problems whatsoever, Black will easily finish development by dropping back the queen and developing the dark-squared bishop. }
