1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ White has a few alternatives that avoid the tabiya, but they are not very promising. So, for example, the move  5.Nc3  allows Black to develop comfortably with  5...Bg4  followed by ...e6.   Or the move  5.c3  after  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Nbd2  e6  is a transposition that leads to the tabiya.   In case of  5.dxc5  e6  Black recaptures on c5 on the next move with ...Bxc5. }
5... cxd4
{ Black releases the tension in order to speed up his development and not think about a possible capture on c5. }
6. exd4 Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain and plans to play ...e6 next. }
7. Bb5
{ This is a recent attempt and one that deserves attention as White's plan is different than in the usual lines. In this variation, he plays for quick development and his idea is to push c4 and put pressure on Black's center. }
7... e6 { Black develops normally. Now White must act quickly. } 8. Ne5 Qb6
{ Defending the knight and attacking both the bishop on b5 and the pawn on d4. }
9. c4
{ Things are getting entangled in the center. White defends the bishop and threatens to take on c6 and push c5, obtaining a strong queenside majority. }
9... dxc4
{ Preventing White's threat and again renewing the attack on the bishop. } 10.
Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Ndxc4 Qa6
{ Even though both sides still need to finish development, we will have an interesting middlegame position. Both sides have a weak pawn, White has an IQP on d4 and Black has the isolated pawn on c6. Black also has the bishop pair and two semi-open files to put his rooks on. }
12. Qe2
{ Threatening Nd6 to win the undefended queen on  a6  . In case of  12.O-O  Be7  Black will castle next and will try to push ...c5, getting rid of the c6-pawn. Note that in case of an exchange of the pawns on c6 and d4, Black would be better because of his bishop pair in an open position. }
12... Bb4+
{ Black develops with tempo as he rushes to get the king to safety. } 13. Bd2
Bxd2+
{ Black no longer has the bishop pair, but he gained time to finish development and castle. }
14. Nxd2
{ In case of  14.Qxd2  O-O  Black follows up with ...Rfd8 with comfortable play. }
14... Qb7
{ The queen is active on the b-file, so Black avoids the exchange. If the queens are to be exchanged, Black would like to do it under his own terms. For example, by exchanging them on b5 so that after Qxb5 cxb5, he improves his structure. }
15. Ndc4 O-O { Black finished development and has a comfortable position. } 16.
O-O Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Be4
{ The middlegame is balanced with chances for both sides. Black will use the strong square on d5 for one of his pieces @@StartBracket@@now the bishop is headed there, but in the future any piece will be well-placed on d5@@EndBracket@@ and will attempt to push ...c5. He will also use the d- and b-files for his rooks. An additional idea for Black is to push the a-pawn in order to pin down White's queenside pawns. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "Main Line 9.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ White has a few alternatives that avoid the tabiya, but they are not very promising. So, for example, the move  5.Nc3  allows Black to develop comfortably with  5...Bg4  followed by ...e6.   Or the move  5.c3  after  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Nbd2  e6  is a transposition that leads to the tabiya.   In case of  5.dxc5  e6  Black recaptures on c5 on the next move with ...Bxc5. }
5... cxd4
{ Black releases the tension in order to speed up his development and not think about a possible capture on c5. }
6. exd4 Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain and plans to play ...e6 next. }
7. c3 { The most common move, leading to the tabiya on move 8. } 7... e6 8. Qb3
{ After  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qb3  Qc8  we have a transposition. } 8... Qc8
{ This is the tabiya that will most likely arise if you play against a dedicated 'Londoner'. It is worth discussing the pawn structure in this variation. As you can see, it is a reversed Carlsbad structure. The general and long-term plan for Black is to organize a minority attack by pushing the pawns to a5 and b4. Black then takes on c3 to create a backward pawn on c3 and a weak square on c4. That would be an ideal scenario for Black. But if White knows what he's doing, this will be difficult to achieve.    Alternative ideas for Black are the ...Ne4 jump to force some exchanges and the ...e5 push, with or without the preparatory ...f6 move, and the exchange of the dark-squared bishops to obtain more control of the dark squares on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
9. Be2
{ This is slow as Black can play his next move to secure the position of his light-squared bishop. }
9... h6 { preserving his bishop. } 10. O-O Be7 11. h3 O-O { After } 12. Ne5
Nxe5 13. Bxe5 { A very instructive maneuver to remember is } 13... Nd7 14. Bf4
Nb8
{ With the knight coming to c6, it can continue the journey to a5 and c4, and support the minority attack. }
