[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "Main Line 9.Nh4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ White has a few alternatives that avoid the tabiya, but they are not very promising. So, for example, the move  5.Nc3  allows Black to develop comfortably with  5...Bg4  followed by ...e6.   Or the move  5.c3  after  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Nbd2  e6  is a transposition that leads to the tabiya.   In case of  5.dxc5  e6  Black recaptures on c5 on the next move with ...Bxc5. }
5... cxd4
{ Black releases the tension in order to speed up his development and not think about a possible capture on c5. }
6. exd4 Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain and plans to play ...e6 next. }
7. c3 { The most common move, leading to the tabiya on move 8. } 7... e6 8. Qb3
{ After  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qb3  Qc8  we have a transposition. } 8... Qc8
{ This is the tabiya that will most likely arise if you play against a dedicated 'Londoner'. It is worth discussing the pawn structure in this variation. As you can see, it is a reversed Carlsbad structure. The general and long-term plan for Black is to organize a minority attack by pushing the pawns to a5 and b4. Black then takes on c3 to create a backward pawn on c3 and a weak square on c4. That would be an ideal scenario for Black. But if White knows what he's doing, this will be difficult to achieve.    Alternative ideas for Black are the ...Ne4 jump to force some exchanges and the ...e5 push, with or without the preparatory ...f6 move, and the exchange of the dark-squared bishops to obtain more control of the dark squares on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
9. Nh4 { The only critical move, otherwise Black has very easy play. } 9... Bg4
{ With this move, Black forces White to weaken his kingside by pushing g4 if he is to obtain the bishop pair. }
10. Bd3
{ Here we will take a look what happens if White doesn't play h3 or f3. } 10...
Be7 11. Nhf3 Bh5
{ Black follows up with the main idea to exchange the light-squared bishops. }
12. O-O Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6
{ Black wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops, but he should be careful about castling kingside as White has an aggressive plan if Black does so prematurely. }
14. Rae1
{ White piles up his pieces in the center and kingside. Curiously enough, he is a tempo down compared to the Caro-Kann with  3.exd5  dxd5  4.Bd3  as there he already has played h4. Naturally, being a tempo up means that Black is quite comfortable. On the other hand, if White plays carelessly he can come under attack, for example  14.Ne1  Nh5  15.Bg3  Nxg3  16.hxg3  Qc7  with ...O-O-O next, and an attack along the open h-file.     In case White starts with  14.h4  then Black can also start his play on the queenside with  14...a6  followed by ...b5, ...Qb7, ...Rc8, and then either ...b4 or ...Na5-c4 with good play. }
14... Nh5
{ Black uses the extra tempo to chase away the active bishop. He keeps his king in the center so as not to provoke an attack after h4, g3, Kg2, Rh1, Bg5xf6, and h5. This attack can prove very strong because of the stability that White enjoys in the center. }
15. Be3
{ Going to g5 would only help Black,  15.Bg5  f6  16.Be3  g5  and it will be Black who will start expanding on the kingside.   The same applies to  15.Be5  f6  16.Bg3  g5 }
15... Bd6
{ With the white bishop forced back to e3, Black takes control over the h2-b8 diagonal. }
16. g3
{ White limits the activity of the bishop on  d6  . In case of  16.c4  Black will drop the knight back to f6 to support the center,  16...Nf6  and if  17.c5  then after  17...Bc7  Black will start undermining White's queenside by ...b6. }
16... Qd7
{ The queen liberates the eighth rank but is careful not to go to c7 to take away that square from the bishop. As we saw in the previous comment about c4-c5, the bishop needs to be able to drop back to c7. }
17. Kg2 O-O-O
{ The middlegame is quite rich. With opposite-side castling, it can become sharp. Since White's pieces are concentrated in the center and kingside, White finds it hard to create queenside activity. Black now wants to expand with ...f6 and ...g5. }
18. h4 { Preventing Black's plan. } 18... Kb8
{ Black takes time to consolidate his queenside by moving the king away from the c-file and liberating the square for the rook. Play is complex, Black can try to force through ...f6 and ...e5, or he can reroute the knight to g4 or e4 via f6. He also keeps an eye on the queenside so ideas like ...Na5-c4 are also possible. }
