{ After  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qb3  Qc8  we have a transposition. } 8... Qc8
{ This is the tabiya that will most likely arise if you play against a dedicated 'Londoner'. It is worth discussing the pawn structure in this variation. As you can see, it is a reversed Carlsbad structure. The general and long-term plan for Black is to organize a minority attack by pushing the pawns to a5 and b4. Black then takes on c3 to create a backward pawn on c3 and a weak square on c4. That would be an ideal scenario for Black. But if White knows what he's doing, this will be difficult to achieve.    Alternative ideas for Black are the ...Ne4 jump to force some exchanges and the ...e5 push, with or without the preparatory ...f6 move, and the exchange of the dark-squared bishops to obtain more control of the dark squares on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
9. Nh4 { The only critical move, otherwise Black has very easy play. } 9... Bg4
{ With this move, Black forces White to weaken his kingside by pushing g4 if he is to obtain the bishop pair. }
10. h3
{ White can try four set-ups here:    1. He can play f3 and g4    2. He can play h3 and g4    3. He can play h3 and Bd3    4. He can play only Bd3 without h3. The more critical ones are when White doesn't push g4. }
10... Bh5 11. g4 { is an alternative, but after } 11... Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6
{ White's kingside expansion doesn't improve his position while Black stays solid. }
13. Bg2
{ White can also play  13.Be2  but it doesn't change much. Black continues with  13...Qd7  14.O-O-O  Bd6  with similar play to the line   @@StartFEN@@r1q1kb1r/pp3ppp/2n1pn2/3p4/3P1BbN/1QP5/PP1N1PPP/R3KB1R w KQkq - 4 10@@EndFEN@@  10.f3  Bh5  11.g4  where it's dangerous for White to take on d6 and b7 in view of an attack along the open files while in case he plays  15.Be3  then after  15...O-O-O  Black has comfortable development. One idea is to play ...Qc7 and ...Bf4 to force the exchange of the dark-squared bishops in order to increase their dark-square control. }
13... Qd7
{ Black plays with the same ideas in mind: to play ...Bd6 and to castle symmetrically. Whichever way White goes, O-O-O or O-O, Black will do the same. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 7: The London System"]
[Black "Main Line 9.Nh4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 { Black attacks the center and develops freely. }
4. e3
{ The most common move. The capture on  c5  gives Black easy play after  4.dxc5  e6  followed by ...Bxc5, ...Nc6, ...O-O, etc. White cannot defend the c5-pawn with  5.b4  in view of  5...a5  6.c3  axb4  7.cxb4  b6  and Black will return the pawn. }
4... Nc6 5. Nbd2
{ White has a few alternatives that avoid the tabiya, but they are not very promising. So, for example, the move  5.Nc3  allows Black to develop comfortably with  5...Bg4  followed by ...e6.   Or the move  5.c3  after  5...cxd4  6.exd4  Bf5  7.Qb3  Qc8  8.Nbd2  e6  is a transposition that leads to the tabiya.   In case of  5.dxc5  e6  Black recaptures on c5 on the next move with ...Bxc5. }
5... cxd4
{ Black releases the tension in order to speed up his development and not think about a possible capture on c5. }
6. exd4 Bf5
{ Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain and plans to play ...e6 next. }
7. c3 { The most common move, leading to the tabiya on move 8. } 7... e6 8. Qb3
{ After  8.Nh4  Bg4  9.Qb3  Qc8  we have a transposition. } 8... Qc8
{ This is the tabiya that will most likely arise if you play against a dedicated 'Londoner'. It is worth discussing the pawn structure in this variation. As you can see, it is a reversed Carlsbad structure. The general and long-term plan for Black is to organize a minority attack by pushing the pawns to a5 and b4. Black then takes on c3 to create a backward pawn on c3 and a weak square on c4. That would be an ideal scenario for Black. But if White knows what he's doing, this will be difficult to achieve.    Alternative ideas for Black are the ...Ne4 jump to force some exchanges and the ...e5 push, with or without the preparatory ...f6 move, and the exchange of the dark-squared bishops to obtain more control of the dark squares on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
9. Nh4 { The only critical move, otherwise Black has very easy play. } 9... Bg4
{ With this move, Black forces White to weaken his kingside by pushing g4 if he is to obtain the bishop pair. }
10. h3
{ White can try four set-ups here:    1. He can play f3 and g4    2. He can play h3 and g4    3. He can play h3 and Bd3    4. He can play only Bd3 without h3. The more critical ones are when White doesn't push g4. }
10... Bh5 11. Bd3 Be7
{ Black finishes development and prepares his next move. } 12. O-O Nd7
{ Black uses the fact that the knight is still on h4 and gains a tempo to increase control of the e5-square. }
13. Nhf3 O-O
{ Black is in no rush to exchange the bishops on g6. He plans to do so by the help of the maneuver ... Re8 and ...Nf8. In this way, he will avoid the doubling of the pawns on g6, thus eliminating White's plan of attack consisting of g3, Kg2, h4, Rh1, Bg5xf6 and h5 before it even starts. }
14. Rae1 { White concentrates his forces in the center. } 14... Re8
{ Black continues with his plan. } 15. Re3
{ Black's plan takes time so White manages to avoid the exchange of the light-squared bishops. }
15... Nf8 16. Rfe1 Bg6 17. Bf1
{ Of course, the exchange on g6 after  17.Bxg6  Nxg6  is great for Black as he avoided the ...hxg6 capture. }
17... h6
{ A useful move to create luft for the light-squared bishop. The middlegame is very complex with both sides having chances. Black's plan is to play ...Bd8-c7 and fight for the dark squares before starting the minority attack on the queenside by ...a6, ...b5, ...Na5-c4, etc. It is important to know that the knight jump on e5 is harmless for Black. }
18. Ne5 Nxe5 19. dxe5
{ Taking with the bishop allows  19.Bxe5?  Bg5  when White is in trouble as the rook cannot move to e2 in view of ...Bd3 while  20.f4  is met by  20...Be7  followed by ...f6 as the centralized bishop is trapped. }
19... Qc7
{ With the intention to play ...Nd7-c5, with excellent play as all Black's pieces are well-placed. }
