1. c4
{ The English Opening doesn't have an independent value for the QGD player as after }
1... e6
{ Play will transpose elsewhere, for example   2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  Be7  are the main lines of the QGD,  or   2.Nf3  d5  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  is covered after the move order   1.Nf3  d5  2.c4  e6  The only independent try is }
2. e4
{ Which basically is a rare French Defence after 1.e4 e6 2.c4. Obviously this gives Black easy play after the normal }
2... d5 3. exd5 exd5
{ Now White has a choice, whether to go   4.d4  or to take on d5 with   4.cxd5 }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black develops actively. Soon we will have a position with an IQP on d4 against which Black will have a comfortable game in view of his harmonious development. }
6. Bd3 O-O 7. Nf3
{ This is an alternative, but it allows an unpleasant pin on the d1-h5 diagonal. }
7... Bg4 8. O-O dxc4
{ Gaining a tempo to develop the knight on c6 and attack the IQP on d4. } 9.
Bxc4 Nc6
{ The knight puts extra pressure on White's center. Now White must always be careful about ... Bxf3 and ...Nxd4 or ...Qxd4. }
10. Bg5 { White responds with a pin of his own. } 10... h6
{ Chasing away the bishop and creating luft, eliminating back-rank issues forever. }
11. Bh4 Be7
{ Breaking the pin and keeping the tension in the position. Black could have taken on f3 and d4 but that simplifies the position. With the better structure and good development Black can continue to play normally and perhaps for more than just equality. A sample line is }
12. d5 Ne5 13. Be2 Ng6 14. Bg3 Bd6 { With a complex middlegame. } *

