1. c4
{ The English Opening doesn't have an independent value for the QGD player as after }
1... e6
{ Play will transpose elsewhere, for example   2.Nc3  d5  3.d4  Be7  are the main lines of the QGD,  or   2.Nf3  d5  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  is covered after the move order   1.Nf3  d5  2.c4  e6  The only independent try is }
2. e4
{ Which basically is a rare French Defence after 1.e4 e6 2.c4. Obviously this gives Black easy play after the normal }
2... d5 3. exd5 exd5
{ Now White has a choice, whether to go   4.d4  or to take on d5 with   4.cxd5 }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4
{ Black develops actively. Soon we will have a position with an IQP on d4 against which Black will have a comfortable game in view of his harmonious development. }
6. Bd3 O-O 7. Ne2
{ With the development of the knight, White avoids the pin on the d1-h5 diagonal. }
7... dxc4 { Winning a tempo to create an IQP and continue development. } 8.
Bxc4 Nbd7
{ Black doesn't move the knight to c6 but develops the knight to d7 instead. This is done because there is no pin on a f3-knight. From d7, the knight will to go b6 to increase the control over the blockading d5-square. }
9. O-O Nb6 10. Bb3
{ In case of  10.Bd3  h6  Black will continue with his play with ... Re8, ...c6, and so on. }
