{ Here in case of  10...h6  White could put a queen on d3 and a bishop on c2 in order to try to use the slight weakening of the light squares. Therefore, Black keeps the pawn on h7 for now. }
11. Bg5
{ This pin isn't problematic as Black can either break it with ...Be7 or move the queen from d8 to d6. }
11... Re8
{ Black has comfortable play here. He can put the queen on d6 in order to play ...Nfd5. The light-squared bishop can go to g4, f5 or e6. With all his pieces harmoniously developed, Black has good play against the IQP on d4. }
