[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Reti/KIA Mix #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. b3
{ In most cases, this will transpose to the lines after 2.c4 when White ultimately plays c4. Here we will take a look at a rare plan when White mixes the Reti and the King's Indian Attack. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2 b6 7. d3 Bb7 { Black develops in the usual Reti manner. } 8.
Nbd2 Nbd7
{ A small subtlety. The knight goes to d7 anyway in the Reti, and here the idea is to see what White's plan is. White can still go c4, and we are in the Reti, while if he is to play for e4, then he must support that move with Re1 or Qe1 since the e4-square is controlled by Black for now. The subtlety consists in the fact that in case of   8...c5  the move  9.e4  immediately is possible:  9...dxe4  10.dxe4  Nxe4  11.Ne5  Nd6  12.Bxb7  Nxb7  13.Qg4  with unpleasant threats. With a knight already on d7, Black would have the move ...Nf6 here. }
9. e4 { This is premature and it gives Black great play. } 9... dxe4 10. Ng5
{ Otherwise, Black is a pawn up. } 10... Rb8
{ Defending the bishop on b7 - another benefit from the early development of the knight from b8. }
11. Ngxe4 Nxe4 12. Nxe4 c5
{ Black has an excellent position with the clear plan to put a knight on d4. }
