1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. b3
{ In most cases, this will transpose to the lines after 2.c4 when White ultimately plays c4. Here we will take a look at a rare plan when White mixes the Reti and the King's Indian Attack. }
5... O-O 6. Bb2 b6 7. d3 Bb7 { Black develops in the usual Reti manner. } 8.
Nbd2 Nbd7
{ A small subtlety. The knight goes to d7 anyway in the Reti, and here the idea is to see what White's plan is. White can still go c4, and we are in the Reti, while if he is to play for e4, then he must support that move with Re1 or Qe1 since the e4-square is controlled by Black for now. The subtlety consists in the fact that in case of   8...c5  the move  9.e4  immediately is possible:  9...dxe4  10.dxe4  Nxe4  11.Ne5  Nd6  12.Bxb7  Nxb7  13.Qg4  with unpleasant threats. With a knight already on d7, Black would have the move ...Nf6 here. }
9. Qe1
{ White supports the e4-push and keeps the rook on the f-file in case the position closes. It is here that a future f4-f5 will be supported by the rook. }
9... a5
{ Since White showed his cards that he was playing for e4, Black immediately starts queenside action. The idea is to play ...a4 and possibly ...a3. }
10. e4
{ In case of   10.a3  a4  11.b4  c5  it's clear that Black's queenside play starts faster than White's central attempt. After  12.b5  Ne8  intending ...Nd6 and ...f5 @@StartBracket@@to prevent e4@@EndBracket@@ Black has excellent play. }
10... a4 11. e5
{ Continuing in KIA-style, but in sub-optimal circumstances. The queen will lose a move to go to e2 to connect the rooks and the bishop on b2 would rather be on f4 where it cannot be shut out by ...d4. From f4, it still supports the e5-pawn while at the same time looks towards Black's kingside. }
11... Ne8 12. Qe2 c5
{ Liberating the c7-square for the knight. Then, Black can continue with ...d4 and ...Nd5. }
13. c4
{ A typical move for White in the KIA. Most importantly it takes away the d5-square from Black @@StartBracket@@as Black could have played ...d4, ... Nc7-d5@@EndBracket@@, but on the other hand it speeds up Black's queenside play after ...b5. }
13... Nc7
{ Supporting the ...b5-push and liberating the 8th rank. Black has several constructive ideas in this complex middlegame: he can push ...b5, he can reroute the knight from d7 to c6 via b8 and he can double on the a-file by playing ...Ra7 and ...Qa8. The position is very rich and Black has very good chances here. }
