1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. d4
{ Note that  5.d3  O-O  leads to the chapter on theKing's Indian Attack   while  5.c4  d4  transposes to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. After 5.d4, White threatens to play c4 transposing to a Catalan line that it outside of our proposed repertoire. }
5... b5
{ An obligatory move by Black because of the possibility of c4 and a transposition to the Catalan line with the bishop already on e7 and the d2-square vacant. }
6. Ne5 { White can also start with   6.Nbd2  O-O  7.Ne5 } 6... O-O 7. Nd2
{ White is rerouting his knights to either establish central control with Ndf3 or Nb3 or to push e4. After   7.a4  b4  8.c4  bxc3  9.Nxc3  Nfd7  we have a transposition to the line starting with   @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/p1p1bppp/4pn2/1p1p4/3P4/5NP1/PPP1PPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@  6.a4  b4  7.c4  bxc3  8.Nxc3  O-O  9.Ne5  Nfd7 }
7... c5 { Black naturally plays the liberating ...c5-push. } 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. e4
{ Now White wants to move the knight from e5 and push e5 or to take on d5 and exert pressure on the long diagonal. So, Black develops the bishop on b7 to strengthen the d5-pawn. If   9.Nd3  first then after  9...Bb6  10.e4  Bb7  we have a transposition. }
9... Bb7 10. Nd3 { White gains a tempo to push e5. } 10... Bb6
{ Keeping the bishop on the active diagonal. } 11. e5 Nfd7 12. Qg4
{ At first sight, it appears that White can create threats on the kingside with Nf3, Bh6, h4-h5, etc., but in fact, Black can easily control this, and his own queenside play along the c-file is coming fast. }
12... Nc6
{ Attacking the e5-pawn, so White defends it, at the same time opening the diagonal for the bishop on c1. }
13. Nf3 Ne7
{ This is the key move for Black. It is a multi-purpose move: first, it defends the kingside in view of the possibilities of ...Ng6 or ...Nf5; second, it opens the c-file for Black's counterplay where his ideas are ...Rc8-c4 or ... Qc7-c4 harassing the queen on g4. White doesn't really have threats while Black's queenside play along the c-file is annoying. }
