[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Preventing the Catalan 6.Qd3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. d4
{ Note that  5.d3  O-O  leads to the chapter on theKing's Indian Attack   while  5.c4  d4  transposes to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. After 5.d4, White threatens to play c4 transposing to a Catalan line that it outside of our proposed repertoire. }
5... b5
{ An obligatory move by Black because of the possibility of c4 and a transposition to the Catalan line with the bishop already on e7 and the d2-square vacant. }
6. Qd3
{ The idea of the move is not so much to threaten the pawn on b5 @@StartBracket@@since after ...Ba6, Black will take the pawn on e2@@EndBracket@@, but to support the e4-push. }
6... O-O
{ Thanks to the vulnerability of the pawn on e2, Black can castle and avoid spending a move on the defence of the b5-pawn. }
7. Bg5
{ Taking the pawn on b5 is met by   7.Qxb5  Ba6  8.Qa5  Bxe2  9.Re1  Bxf3  10.Bxf3  c5  with excellent play. }
7... h6
{ Immediately forcing White to take on f6 if he is to continue with his plan of pushing e4. }
8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. e4
{ White eliminated the defender of the e4-square, the knight on f6, and managed to push e4, but he had to give away the bishop pair in return. }
9... b4 { Threatening ...Ba6 to win the exchange. } 10. Rd1 Bb7
{ Putting pressure on White's center. } 11. exd5 Bxd5
{ The bishop is very strong on d5. If White wants to get rid of it, he must isolate his d4-pawn. }
12. c4 bxc3 13. Nxc3 c6
{ Strengthening the bishop. Now in case of an exchange on d5, Black will straighten up his structure with ...cxd5. He will finish development with ...Nd7 and will have a very harmonious position with ideas to use the b-file with ...Rb8 and a possible knight transfer to c4 via b6. }
