[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Preventing the Catalan 6.a4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. d4
{ Note that  5.d3  O-O  leads to the chapter on theKing's Indian Attack   while  5.c4  d4  transposes to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. After 5.d4, White threatens to play c4 transposing to a Catalan line that it outside of our proposed repertoire. }
5... b5
{ An obligatory move by Black because of the possibility of c4 and a transposition to the Catalan line with the bishop already on e7 and the d2-square vacant. }
6. a4
{ With this move, White forces Black to play ...b4 and achieves the c4-push. }
6... b4 7. c4 bxc3 8. Nxc3
{ In case of  8.bxc3  Ba6  followed by ...O-O, Black will try to push ...c5. }
8... O-O { Black tucked away the king and is now ready to play in the center. }
9. Ne5
{ This is the main alternative. White centralizes the knight, opens the long diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop, and prepares the e4-push. }
9... Nfd7 { Black immediately challenges the knight on e5. } 10. e4
{ White advances in the center. } 10... c6
{ Black must strengthen the d5-pawn since the immediate   10...Nxe5  runs into  11.exd5  with problems on the long diagonal. Now Black wants to take on e5, so White removes the knight. }
11. Nd3
{ From here, the knight controls the dark squares on the queenside, most importantly c5 and b4. }
11... a5
{ Fixing the b4-square. Black now wants to use the a6-square for the development of his light pieces: ...Na6-b4 and ...Ba6. }
12. Re1 Ba6
{ The bishop on a6 is active and it discourages White from taking on d5 because after   13.exd5  cxd5  the bishop controls the b5-square. Additionally, in case White takes on d5, the c6-square will be liberated for the knight on b8. }
13. Bf4 Ra7 { Activating the rook. } 14. Rc1 Rb7
{ The middlegame is complex with chances for both sides. Black has two ideas how to develop the knight from b8. One is to play ...Bc4 and ...Na6-b4, the other is to play ...Nf6 to provoke e5 and then go back with ...Nfd7, to push ...c5 and develop the knight on c6. If White doesn't play e5, Black can consider taking on e4 and putting the knights on d5 and d7 when the strong position of all Black's pieces and the IQP on d4 compensate for the isolated pawn on c6. }
