[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Preventing the Catalan 6.a4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3
{ With this move-order, we will take a look at the lines where White doesn't play c4. }
2... Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O
{ In case of  4.c4  d4  we have a transposition to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. }
4... Be7 5. d4
{ Note that  5.d3  O-O  leads to the chapter on theKing's Indian Attack   while  5.c4  d4  transposes to the lines analyzed after 2.c4. After 5.d4, White threatens to play c4 transposing to a Catalan line that it outside of our proposed repertoire. }
5... b5
{ An obligatory move by Black because of the possibility of c4 and a transposition to the Catalan line with the bishop already on e7 and the d2-square vacant. }
6. a4
{ With this move, White forces Black to play ...b4 and achieves the c4-push. }
6... b4 7. c4 bxc3 8. Nxc3
{ In case of  8.bxc3  Ba6  followed by ...O-O, Black will try to push ...c5. }
8... O-O { Black tucked away the king and is now ready to play in the center. }
9. Bf4
{ In case of  9.a5  preventing Black's ... a5  9...Ba6  followed by ...c5 and ...Nbd7 or ...Nc6. Black is quite fine. }
9... a5 { Fixing the b4-square. } 10. Rc1
{ In case of  10.Ne5  Nfd7  11.Nd3  c6  12.e4  Ba6  13.Re1  Ra7  we have a transposition to the line starting with 9.Ne5. Now White threatens Nb5. }
10... c6 { Strengthening the center and controlling the b5-square. } 11. e4
{ A direct move creating central tension. White doesn't really want to push e5 because after ...Nfd7, Black has the clear plan of pushing ...c5, but Black should be careful about exd5 and be ready and know how to recapture. After  11.Ne5  the standard reaction is  11...Nfd7  followed by ...Ba6. }
11... dxe4
{ Black takes the pawn and now White will seek compensation along the long diagonal. }
12. Ne5 Nd5 { Black uses the liberated d5-square to attack the bishop on f4. }
13. Nxe4 Nxf4 { Black wrecks White's structure. } 14. gxf4 Ra7
{ A good move. Black develops the rook since the other pieces cannot easily come into play. The position is interesting: Black is a pawn up, has the bishop pair and the better pawn structure, while White has very active pieces. This activity should be enough to return the extra material. Even then, White cannot change how weak his king is. So Black is not against simplifying the position by returning the pawn as Black will always have counterplay against White's king. }
15. Nc5
{ White's knights look impressive, but with his next move Black gets rid of one. Note that White cannot take on  c6  as after  15.Nxc6  Nxc6  16.Rxc6  Rd7  he has problems with the pawn on d4. }
15... f6 { Getting rid of one of the knights. } 16. Nxc6
{ Taking the pawn leads to simplifications, which suit Black. Notice that Black exchanges his knight from b8 making its first move for a knight that came all the way from g1. }
16... Nxc6 17. Bxc6 Qd6 { Attacking both the bishop on c6 and the pawn on d5. }
18. d5 Qxf4
{ With this capture, Black emphasizes the weakness of White's king. He wants to play ...Bd6 and create threats on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
19. Nxe6 Bxe6 20. dxe6 Bd6 21. Qh5 { Defending the h2-pawn. } 21... g6
{ Chasing away the queen and forcing her to go to h3. } 22. Qh3 Rc7
{ The position is double-edged. Black is a pawn down, but that is irrelevant because the extra pawn White has on the queenside will never materialize into a passed pawn as the move b4 will never happen. On the other hand, Black has the better king and the better bishop, with White's queen tied down to the defense of the h2-pawn. It's a dynamically balanced position that Black can play on without any risk. He can double on the c-file, play ...f5, ...Kg7, and so on, slowly improving his position. }
