11... Nc6
{ Black develops naturally, controlling the d4-square. If allowed to play ...Qd7, ...Rfd8, and ...Rac8, he will stand better due to his space advantage and superior central control. }
12. Qb2 Bf6 { Forcing the exchange of White's most active pieces. } 13. Bxf6
Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6
{ The endgame is equal. The doubled f6-pawn has the useful task of controling the e5-square. Black will either put his rooks in the center with ...Rac8 and ... Rfd8, or can play ...Rab8 @@StartBracket@@defending the bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ and play ...Rfd8 and ... Nd4, with no problems whatsoever in both cases. }
