1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. b3
{ Here we will take a look at the plans with White's double fianchetto that can also arise from other move-orders. }
4... Be7 5. Bg2 O-O { Black develops in the usual QGD style. } 6. O-O b6
{ Black immediately solves the problem of the light-squared bishop. } 7. Bb2
Bb7
{ Here White needs to make a principled choice - whether to go for slower play with e3, Qe2 etc. or to take on d5 and engage in central play. The move  8.d4?  is not very good as after  8...dxc4   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2P5/1P3NP1/P2PPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line  7.d4  Bb7  8.Bb2  dxc4  9.bxc4  c5 }
8. cxd5 { This is the central approach. } 8... Nxd5
{ As usual, Black takes on d5 with a piece to keep the long diagonal open for the light-squared bishop. }
9. d4 { This is the natural way to take the center. } 9... c5
{ Immediately striking in the center. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Here White has tried several moves but neither promises much. } 11. a3 a5
{ Preventing b4 and securing the position of the bishop on c5. Now White needs to decide where to develop the knight from b1. }
12. Nbd2 Nf6
{ The knight opens the long diagonal for the bishop and prevents the move Ne4. This move also prevents the move Nd4 as now both the d8-queen and the c5-bishop control that square. }
13. Nc4 { After  13.Rc1  Qe7  attacking the pawn on a3, Black is fine. } 13...
Nbd7
{ Finishing development in the usual way. Now Black will play ...Qe7 or ...Qb8. }
14. Nd4
{ White is aiming the c6-square, but Black keeps his queen close. In case of  14.Rc1  Qb8  with ...Rd8 or ...Rc8 next. Black nicely covers all the vulnerable squares. }
14... Qc8
{ Controlling the c6-square and threatening to take on g2 and push ...b5, thanks to the check on the long diagonal. }
15. a4 { Preventing Black's idea to advance with ...b5. } 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2
Qb7+ { Black connects the rooks with tempo. } 17. f3 Rfd8
{ Black has no problems in this position. He can play ...Rac8 and all his pieces will be well-placed. One curious idea is the ... Nb8-c6 maneuver, in order to get the knight to b4. }
