{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. b3
{ Here we will take a look at the plans with White's double fianchetto that can also arise from other move-orders. }
4... Be7 5. Bg2 O-O { Black develops in the usual QGD style. } 6. O-O b6
{ Black immediately solves the problem of the light-squared bishop. } 7. Bb2
Bb7
{ Here White needs to make a principled choice - whether to go for slower play with e3, Qe2 etc. or to take on d5 and engage in central play. The move  8.d4?  is not very good as after  8...dxc4   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2P5/1P3NP1/P2PPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line  7.d4  Bb7  8.Bb2  dxc4  9.bxc4  c5 }
8. cxd5 { This is the central approach. } 8... Nxd5
{ As usual, Black takes on d5 with a piece to keep the long diagonal open for the light-squared bishop. }
9. d4 { This is the natural way to take the center. } 9... c5
{ Immediately striking in the center. } 10. dxc5 Bxc5
{ Here White has tried several moves but neither promises much. } 11. Nbd2 Nf6
{ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb3ppp/1p2p3/2bn4/8/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ Black plays the same with the line  11.a3  a5  included. With this move, he controls both e4 and d4 so neither Ne4 or Nd4 are possible. }
12. Rc1
{ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb3ppp/1p2p3/2bn4/8/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ Compared to the line with  11.a3  a5  inserted, this makes more sense now as, after ...Qe7, there is no pawn on a3 to hang. }
12... Qe7
{ Even though there is no attack on a pawn on a3, Black develops the queen on the most natural square. Now White can try several knight moves. }
13. Ne5 { The knight is active on e5 and can also drop back to d3. } 13... Bxg2
{ This exchange is welcome as it liberates the b7-square for the queen. Why this is important can be seen soon. }
14. Kxg2 Rd8 { Pinning the knight on d2. } 15. Nd3 Qb7+
{ Here we see the importance of the b7-square. The queen liberates the e7-square with a tempo so that the attacked bishop on c5 can safely return. }
16. Nf3 Be7
{ The bishop is safe on e7, it also covers the knight on f6 and avoids the doubling of the pawns in case White plays Bxf6. }
17. Qc2 { White gets away from the pin and increases control over the c-file. }
17... Ne8
{ A nice move, covering the entry point on c7. Black's position has no weaknesses and he can take the time to cover the vulnerable squares first before completing his development with ...Na6. }
18. Rfd1 Na6
{ Black stands well here. He will play ...Rac8 next, and neutralize White's pressure on the c-file. }
