{ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb3ppp/1p2p3/2bn4/8/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ Black plays the same with the line  11.a3  a5  included. With this move, he controls both e4 and d4 so neither Ne4 or Nd4 are possible. }
12. Rc1
{ @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/pb3ppp/1p2p3/2bn4/8/1P3NP1/PB2PPBP/RN1Q1RK1 w - - 0 11@@EndFEN@@ Compared to the line with  11.a3  a5  inserted, this makes more sense now as, after ...Qe7, there is no pawn on a3 to hang. }
12... Qe7
{ Even though there is no attack on a pawn on a3, Black develops the queen on the most natural square. Now White can try several knight moves. }
13. Nc4 Nc6
{ Black develops the knight to c6 in order to keep the d-file open. An additional idea is the move ...Nb4, attacking the a2-pawn and rerouting the knight to d5. }
14. Ne1 { The idea is to attack the bishop on c5 with Nd3. } 14... Rfd8
{ Attacking the queen and targeting the d3-square in case White plays Nd3. }
15. Nd3
{ After  15.Qc2  Nd4  Black simplifies the position to avoid any issues. }
15... Nb4
{ Here we see Black's active counterplay based on the jump to b4. Don't forget that the pawn on a2 is hanging too. }
16. Bxb7 Qxb7 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Nxc5
{ Thanks to this move, White avoids problems on the d3-square, but he ends up losing the pawn on a2. }
18... bxc5 19. Nd2 Qd5
{ White has problems on the d-file, so the knight must move. But then, after the exchanges, the pawn on a2 falls. }
20. Nf3 Qxd1 21. Rfxd1 Rxd1+ 22. Rxd1 Nxa2
{ Black is a pawn up in the endgame and only he can play for a win. } *

