Bb7
{ Here White needs to make a principled choice - whether to go for slower play with e3, Qe2 etc. or to take on d5 and engage in central play. The move  8.d4?  is not very good as after  8...dxc4   @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/p1p1bppp/1p2pn2/3p4/2P5/1P3NP1/P2PPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line  7.d4  Bb7  8.Bb2  dxc4  9.bxc4  c5 }
8. e3
{ This is a slower set-up for White. He intends to play Qe2, and then he will have two plans at his disposal: Rd1 followed by taking on d5 and pushing d4 or d3 with the idea of Ne1 @@StartBracket@@or Nh4@@EndBracket@@ and then f4, g4, etc. }
8... c5 { Black expands in the center. } 9. Nc3
{ White's set-up is very flexible, so he can start with other moves as well, though more likely than not they will lead to a transposition. For example, after  9.Qe2  Nbd7  10.Rd1  Qc7  11.Nc3  Rac8  we have a transposition to the line starting with 9.Nc3.   A move like  9.d3  is met with the same set-up of  9...Nbd7  followed by ...Qc7, ...Rac8 and ...Qb8. }
9... Nbd7
{ With this move, Black intends a very harmonious regrouping: the queen will go to c7, the rook from a8 will come to c8 or d8, and then the queen will drop back to b8, thus removing herself from the central files. From b8, the queen controls the e5-square and can also go to a8 to increase Black's control over the long diagonal. }
10. Qe2 Qc7
{ Now White has to decide whether to go for central or kingside play. } 11.
Rac1
{ Attacking the queen with  11.Nb5  is met by  11...Qb8  followed by ...a6 and then ...Qc7, ...Rad8 etc. }
11... Rad8 { Now the queen won't shut the rook out on a8. } 12. Rfd1
{ Taking on  d5  is always met by recapturing with a piece,  12.cxd5  Nxd5  when Black will continue with the plan of ...Qb8. }
12... Qb8
{ With the queen out of the central files, Black has no problems whatsoever. A sample line how the game can continue is }
13. cxd5
{ If  13.d3  then a useful move like  13...h6  can be made. Black has other useful moves that he can play in case White maneuvers: ...Qa8, ...Rfe8, ...a6 @@StartBracket@@perhaps intending ...b5@@EndBracket@@ and so on. }
13... Nxd5 14. Nxd5 { Or  14.d3  Nxc3  15.Bxc3  Qa8 } 14... Bxd5 15. d4 Qb7
{ With excellent control over the long diagonal. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Black Advances 4...d4 5.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 { After  4.d4  Bb4  we have a transposition to the Catalan. }
4... d4
{ White was threatening to play d4 with a transposition to the Catalan when Black would not have been able to play the proposed line with 4...Bb4. Therefore, Black prevents d4 by pushing ...d4 himself, grabbing central space. What is important to remember here is that Black's plan is to play ...Nc6 and ...e5, to open the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and thus obtain comfortable development with good central control. }
5. b4
{ Only this move has an independent value, but the line actually is risky for White who can easily end up worse. }
5... Bxb4 { Black takes the pawn. His defence hinges on his 7th move. } 6. Qa4+
Nc6 { Covering the check and defending the bishop. } 7. Ne5 Rb8
{ The only move, but it suffices. Black prepares to defend the bishop on b4 when the b-file opens. }
8. Ba3
{ White wants to exchange his passive bishop on  c1  . Otherwise it's stuck on  c1  , for example after  8.a3  Bd6 }
8... Bxa3 9. Nxc6
{ If White plays  9.Nxa3  then Black simply castles,  9...O-O  when  10.Bxc6  bxc6  11.Nxc6  doesn't win an exchange in view of the pin  11...Qe8 }
9... bxc6 10. Qxa3 { White prevents Black's castling. } 10... Rb6
{ Black defends the pawn on c6. He is still a pawn up and wants to play ...Ra6 to defend the pawn on a7. }
11. Qxa7 Ra6 12. Qc5
{ In case of  12.Qb8  O-O  The queen will have to lose more time to drop back along the b-file, while Black will play ...e5, and then either play for the ...e4 push or for queenside play along the a and b-files. }
12... Qd6 13. Qg5
{ The endgame after  13.Qxd6  cxd6  is better for Black. He will play ...Bd7, ...Kd7, and use the rooks for play along the a- and b-files. }
13... O-O { Finishing development and defending the pawn on g7. } 14. d3 e5
{ Black stands better here - he will develop the bishop and then play ...Rfa8 with pressure on the queenside. For example, }
15. O-O Bg4 16. Re1 Rfa8
{ With strong pressure. Once the queen moves from g5, he can place his knight on c5 and then perhaps try to push ...e4. }
*

