[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Black Advances 4...d4 5.0-0 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 { After  4.d4  Bb4  we have a transposition to the Catalan. }
4... d4
{ White was threatening to play d4 with a transposition to the Catalan when Black would not have been able to play the proposed line with 4...Bb4. Therefore, Black prevents d4 by pushing ...d4 himself, grabbing central space. What is important to remember here is that Black's plan is to play ...Nc6 and ...e5, to open the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and thus obtain comfortable development with good central control. }
5. O-O
{ White can start with other moves but the majority will transpose as he has to castle sooner rather than later. For example  5.e3  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.e3  Nc6   Similarly,  5.d3  Be7  6.O-O  Nc6   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  Nc6   The move  5.a3  is met with the natural  5...a5 }
5... Be7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This line can also arise from the move-order where Black had already played  ...Be7  , for example  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  e6  4.O-O  Be7  5.c4  d4  so in order to be practical and avoid possible move-order issues Black plays the same ...Be7 in this position. }
6. e3 Nc6 { Black plays for piece control of the center. } 7. exd4
{ The pawn sacrifice  7.b4?!  is not entirely sound as simply taking the pawn is fine for Black:  7...dxe3  8.fxe3  Nxb4  with ...c5 and ...O-O next. It's not clear what White's compensation will be. }
7... Nxd4
{ Now White can try several set-ups, but they all evolve around the d4-square and the d4-push. }
8. d3
{ White wants to develop with Nc3 and Be3 and force Black to take on  f3  . Starting with  8.Nc3  will transpose after  8...O-O  9.d3 }
8... O-O
{ After moving the king away from the center, Black can take on f3 and push ...e5. }
9. Nc3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 e5
{ Black opened the diagonal for the bishop and would like to play ...c6 and then develop the bishop to f5, targeting the pawn on d3. }
11. Re1 Bd6 { Defending the pawn on e5. Black's next move will be ...c6. } 12.
Be3
{ Taking the bishop on  d6  only helps Black:  12.Nb5  c6  13.Nxd6  Qxd6  and with ...Bf5 and ...Rad8 coming, Black has excellent play on the d-file. }
12... c6 13. d4 { Opening the game, as White doesn't really have other plan. }
13... exd4 14. Bxd4
{ In case of  14.Qxd4  Be7  Black forces the exchange of queens and will finish development with ...Be6 next. }
14... Be7
{ A good move, by taking aim at the bishop on d4, Black limits the movement of the White queen. }
15. c5
{ An ambitious attempt, taking space on the queenside. Otherwise Black will play ...Be6, ...Re8, and will be fine. }
15... Re8
{ Black wants to neutralize White's pressure on the e-file and plans ...Bf8. That is why he is not closing the e-file with ... Be6 just yet. }
16. Qa4 Bf8 17. Rxe8 Nxe8
{ Avoiding the wrecking of the structure in case of  17...Qxe8  18.Bxf6 } 18.
Rd1 Qe7
{ With comfortable play for Black. He has no weaknesses, and will play ... Bf5 or ...Be6 next. The knight can return to f6 later. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Black Advances 4...d4 5.0-0 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 { After  4.d4  Bb4  we have a transposition to the Catalan. }
4... d4
{ White was threatening to play d4 with a transposition to the Catalan when Black would not have been able to play the proposed line with 4...Bb4. Therefore, Black prevents d4 by pushing ...d4 himself, grabbing central space. What is important to remember here is that Black's plan is to play ...Nc6 and ...e5, to open the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and thus obtain comfortable development with good central control. }
5. O-O
{ White can start with other moves but the majority will transpose as he has to castle sooner rather than later. For example  5.e3  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.e3  Nc6   Similarly,  5.d3  Be7  6.O-O  Nc6   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  Nc6   The move  5.a3  is met with the natural  5...a5 }
5... Be7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This line can also arise from the move-order where Black had already played  ...Be7  , for example  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  e6  4.O-O  Be7  5.c4  d4  so in order to be practical and avoid possible move-order issues Black plays the same ...Be7 in this position. }
6. e3 Nc6 { Black plays for piece control of the center. } 7. exd4
{ The pawn sacrifice  7.b4?!  is not entirely sound as simply taking the pawn is fine for Black:  7...dxe3  8.fxe3  Nxb4  with ...c5 and ...O-O next. It's not clear what White's compensation will be. }
7... Nxd4
{ Now White can try several set-ups, but they all evolve around the d4-square and the d4-push. }
8. b3
{ This hasn't been played, but it is the engine suggestion. White plans to play Bb2 and control the d4-square. }
8... O-O 9. Bb2 Nxf3+
{ Ths simplest solution. Black gains tempo to develop the bishop on the long diagonal since pushing ...e5 with a bishop on b2 is difficult. }
10. Qxf3 Rb8
{ This is Black's plan. He removes the rook from the long diagonal in order to play ...b6 and ...Bb7. White cannot prevent this plan. }
11. Qe2 b6 12. d4 Bb7
{ Black has no problems here. After the exchange of the light-squared bishops, he will aim for the ...c5 push. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8: Reti Opening"]
[Black "Black Advances 4...d4 5.0-0 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 { After  4.d4  Bb4  we have a transposition to the Catalan. }
4... d4
{ White was threatening to play d4 with a transposition to the Catalan when Black would not have been able to play the proposed line with 4...Bb4. Therefore, Black prevents d4 by pushing ...d4 himself, grabbing central space. What is important to remember here is that Black's plan is to play ...Nc6 and ...e5, to open the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and thus obtain comfortable development with good central control. }
5. O-O
{ White can start with other moves but the majority will transpose as he has to castle sooner rather than later. For example  5.e3  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.e3  Nc6   Similarly,  5.d3  Be7  6.O-O  Nc6   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  Nc6   The move  5.a3  is met with the natural  5...a5 }
5... Be7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This line can also arise from the move-order where Black had already played  ...Be7  , for example  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  e6  4.O-O  Be7  5.c4  d4  so in order to be practical and avoid possible move-order issues Black plays the same ...Be7 in this position. }
6. e3 Nc6 { Black plays for piece control of the center. } 7. exd4
{ The pawn sacrifice  7.b4?!  is not entirely sound as simply taking the pawn is fine for Black:  7...dxe3  8.fxe3  Nxb4  with ...c5 and ...O-O next. It's not clear what White's compensation will be. }
7... Nxd4
{ Now White can try several set-ups, but they all evolve around the d4-square and the d4-push. }
8. Nxd4 Qxd4 9. d3 e5
{ Opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop and increasing control over the d4-square. }
10. Na3 { This is an attempt to play slowly, not rushing with d4. } 10... c6
{ Controlling the b5-square and limiting the activity of the bishop on g2. }
11. Nc2 Qd6
{ Since the e-file is open and White will play Re1, Black defends the pawn on e5 in advance. }
12. Re1 O-O 13. b3
{ White wants to put pressure on the e5-pawn. An additional idea is the Ba3 move. }
13... Bg4
{ Developing with a tempo and connecting the rooks. White has a clear weakness on d3 so Black wants to play ...Rad8. }
14. Qd2 Rad8
{ Attacking the pawn on d3 before White is organized to attack the pawn on e5. }
15. Ba3 { White must seek exchanges to ease the pressure on the d-file. } 15...
Qd7 { Keeping the attack on the pawn on d3. } 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. d4
{ White must try to get rid of the backward pawn because if Black consolidates, the pawn will become a chronic weakness. }
17... Qc7
{ Removing the queen from the pin on the e-file. Now White needs to decide what to do with the tension on the d-file. }
18. Qc3
{ Getting away from the pin. Staying on the d-file would lose the d-pawn, for example after  18.d5  cxd5  19.cxd5  Be6  20.Ne3  e4 }
18... exd4 19. Nxd4 Qd6
{ Forcing the knight to move from the central position. } 20. Nf3 Bxf3
{ An interesting and instructive decision. Black plays for activity of his rooks and also the fact that once the knight is transferred to c5, it won't be worse than the limited bishop on f3 @@StartBracket@@the pawns on b7 and c6 doing a great job of limiting the scope of the bishop@@EndBracket@@. }
21. Bxf3 Qd3 { Forcing the exchange of queens. } 22. Qxd3 Rxd3 23. Kg2 Rfd8
{ With an excellent endgame for Black. One of the ideas is the mentioned knight transfer to c5 @@StartBracket@@after proper preparation@@EndBracket@@, while the others are the typical endgame ideas of centralization of the king and possible exchanges of rooks. }
