1. Nf3 d5 2. c4
{ The main distinction here is whether and when White plays c4. With this move-order, we will look at all of the lines where c4 is played. While with the 2.g3 move-order, we will look at the variations where White doesn't @@StartBracket@@or is not allowed to@@EndBracket@@ play c4. The move  2.e4?!  is dubious, to say the least, as White wastes time recapturing the pawn and plays with the only developed piece, the knight, too many times. After  2...dxe4  3.Ng5  e5  4.Nxe4  Nc6  followed by ... f5, ...Bd6, ...Nf6 etc. Black has an excellent game. }
2... e6 3. g3
{ After  3.e3  Nf6  4.b3  we have a transposition to the lines analysed after 1.b3 in the chapter on the  Nimzowitsch/Larsen Opening. }
3... Nf6 4. Bg2 { After  4.d4  Bb4  we have a transposition to the Catalan. }
4... d4
{ White was threatening to play d4 with a transposition to the Catalan when Black would not have been able to play the proposed line with 4...Bb4. Therefore, Black prevents d4 by pushing ...d4 himself, grabbing central space. What is important to remember here is that Black's plan is to play ...Nc6 and ...e5, to open the h3-c8 diagonal for the bishop and thus obtain comfortable development with good central control. }
5. O-O
{ White can start with other moves but the majority will transpose as he has to castle sooner rather than later. For example  5.e3  Nc6  6.O-O  Be7   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.e3  Nc6   Similarly,  5.d3  Be7  6.O-O  Nc6   transposes to theline starting with  5.O-O  Be7  6.d3  Nc6   The move  5.a3  is met with the natural  5...a5 }
5... Be7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ This line can also arise from the move-order where Black had already played  ...Be7  , for example  1.Nf3  d5  2.g3  Nf6  3.Bg2  e6  4.O-O  Be7  5.c4  d4  so in order to be practical and avoid possible move-order issues Black plays the same ...Be7 in this position. }
6. d3 Nc6 { Following the plan. } 7. Na3
{ The typical plan in these structures. White intends to play Nc2 and then push b4 and/or e3, the knight on  c2  supporting both moves. After  7.e3  O-O  8.exd4  Nxd4   @@StartFEN@@rnbqk2r/ppp1bppp/4pn2/8/2Pp4/5NP1/PP1PPPBP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@ we have a transposition to the line  6.e3  Nc6  7.exd4  Nxd4  8.d3  O-O }
7... O-O
{ Black castles, removing the king from the center and avoiding checks from  a4  , like for example after  7...e5  8.b4  Bxb4  9.Nxe5  Nxe5  10.Qa4 }
8. Nc2 a5 { Preventing b4. Now White can try to play for either e3 or b4. } 9.
e3 dxe3 { Transforming the structure and gaining tempo for the ...e5 move. }
10. Bxe3 { If  10.fxe3  e5  Black stands well. } 10... e5
{ Black achieved his aim and now threatens ...Bf5 to attack the pawn on d3. So, White doesn't have a choice but to push it. }
11. d4 Ng4
{ Attacking the bishop on e3 and opening the path for the f-pawn. This will be important when White closes the position after d5. }
12. d5
{ Exchanges on  e5  bring nothing to White,  12.dxe5  Ngxe5  13.Nxe5  Nxe5  with excellent play for Black. }
12... Nb4
{ Now Black would like to take on e3 since the dark-squared bishop is controlling the important dark squares and is the most valuable minor piece in these structures @@StartBracket@@the bishop on g2 is limited by its own pawns on c4 and d5@@EndBracket@@. }
13. Bd2
{ After  13.Bc1  Black continues in the same vein with  13...e4  14.Nfd4  f5 }
13... e4 { Gaining central space. } 14. Nfd4 f5
{ With excellent play for Black. He has good control in the centre and the dark squares in particular. His knights can jump to d3, e5 or c5 @@StartBracket@@via a6@@EndBracket@@ and the dark-squared bishop will be very good on either f6 or c5. }
