8. Nc2 a5 { Preventing b4. Now White can try to play for either e3 or b4. } 9.
a3 e5
{ Expanding in the center. Now Black's ideal plan is to push ...e4 with the help of ...Bf5, ...Re8, and ...Bf8 @@StartBracket@@c5@@EndBracket@@. }
10. Rb1 a4
{ Black prevents b4 and in case White insists on it, he will open the a-file by taking en passant and obtain the c5-square for his pieces. }
11. Bd2
{ Preparing Nb4. The immediate  11.Nb4  leads to a good position for Black as it opens the e-file for him after  11...Nxb4  12.axb4  Bxb4  13.Nxe5  Re8 }
11... Re8
{ Always a useful move as it either supports the ...e4-push, or lends extra support to the e5-pawn after the bishop moves. }
12. Nb4 e4
{ Accomplishing one of the main ideas for Black in these positions - the ...e4-push. }
13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. dxe4 { After  14.Ne1  Bf5  Black is in control. } 14... Nxe4
15. Ne5 { White's plan is to take advantage of the doubled c-pawns, but after }
15... Bf5 { Defending the knight and eyeing the rook on b1. } 16. Nxc6 Qd7 17.
Nxe7+ Qxe7
{ With ...c5 and ...Rad8 to come, Black has fantastic compensation due to his central presence and pressure along the e-file. }
