[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Black "The Plan With 6.Nc3"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7
{ Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 5. d3 O-O 6. Nc3
{ is also aiming for e4, but is much less popular. } 6... Nc6
{ Black continues in the same manner, aiming for ...e5. } 7. e4 dxe4
{ Releasing the tension in the center and closing the diagonal for the bishop on g2 by forcing White to put a pawn on e4. }
8. dxe4 e5
{ Theoretically speaking, in a symmetrical position, Black is marginally better as the g2-bishop is passive. Meanwhile, Black's bishop on e7 can be activated via the c5-square. }
9. h3 { Securing e3 for the bishop and preventing ... Bg4 and ...Nd4 ideas. }
9... Be6 { Black develops naturally. He doesn't fear Ng5 as he has ...Bc4. }
10. Qe2
{ White's plan is to play Rd1 and Nd5. In case of  10.Be3  Bb4  White has problems defending the e4-pawn and preventing the damage to his structure after ...Bxc3. }
10... Nd4
{ With this active jump, Black activates his queen and gains access to the c4-square. }
11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Be3 Qc4 { The endgame is very comfortable for Black. } 13.
Qxc4 Bxc4 14. Rfd1 Bb4
{ Black wants to take on c3 and damage White's structure. He can also take control over the d5-square with ... c6 and put a rook on d8 to fight for the open d-file. It is apparent that he has no problems here. }
