[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Black "White Plays 7.d4 #1 "]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7
{ Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This is the beginning of the King's Indian Attack @@StartBracket@@KIA@@EndBracket@@. The idea is to push e4-e5 and then develop with Re1, Nf1, h4-h5, N1h2-g4, Bf4, and obtain a threatening position on the kingside. This is all very automatic for White so it makes practical sense not to enter these waters. Black's next move is aimed at precisely that - to change the character of the position so White cannot play his well-rehearsed set-up. }
6... Nc6
{ The idea of this move is to play ...e5, thus stopping White's plan of e4-e5 in its tracks. }
7. d4
{ This move is the other critical option. It changes White's strategy completely, abandoning ideas of an attack, but it does prevent ...e5. }
7... b6 { Black prepares to develop the bishop on b7. } 8. b3
{ This is an alternative, but now with precise play, Black makes it difficult for White to push c4. }
8... Na5
{ This strong move turns White's c4 in Black's favor. The point is that after }
9. Bb2
{ The immediate  9.c4  runs into  9...dxc4  10.bxc4  Ba6  and the pawn on c4 is under attack. He will further fix it with ...c5 and will play ...Rc8 to increase the pressure. }
9... Bb7 10. c4
{ In case of  10.Ne5  Black plays his liberating move  10...c5  with comfortable play. }
10... dxc4 11. bxc4 c5
{ This is the move that was made possible by the timely movement of the knight to a5. Black fixes the c4-pawn and plans to attack it with ...Rc8 and ...Ba6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 9: The King's Indian Attack"]
[Black "White Plays 7.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7
{ Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This is the beginning of the King's Indian Attack @@StartBracket@@KIA@@EndBracket@@. The idea is to push e4-e5 and then develop with Re1, Nf1, h4-h5, N1h2-g4, Bf4, and obtain a threatening position on the kingside. This is all very automatic for White so it makes practical sense not to enter these waters. Black's next move is aimed at precisely that - to change the character of the position so White cannot play his well-rehearsed set-up. }
6... Nc6
{ The idea of this move is to play ...e5, thus stopping White's plan of e4-e5 in its tracks. }
7. d4
{ This move is the other critical option. It changes White's strategy completely, abandoning ideas of an attack, but it does prevent ...e5. }
7... b6 { Black prepares to develop the bishop on b7. } 8. c4
{ White must push this immediately if he is to challenge Black's center. } 8...
a5 { Black wants to disrupt White's comfortable development with b3 and Bb2. }
9. b3
{ After  9.cxd5  exd5  10.Nb1  is an attempt to reroute the knight to the more active square to c3, but Black has  10...Ne4  preventing that development and with ...Bf5 or ...a4 to come next, he has very comfortable development. The idea of ...a4 is to start play on the queenside with the ...Na5-c4 maneuver. }
9... a4
{ Black must act quickly, otherwise White would play a3 and meet ...a4 with b4. }
10. bxa4
{ More or less forced, otherwise Black could play ...a3, and the bishop would never come to b2. }
10... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop on the long diagonal and opening the eighth rank. Black now wants to double on the a-file with ...Ra7 and ...Qa8. }
11. Bb2 Ra7 12. cxd5
{ Releasing the tension in the center so that the knight from b1 can move. Ideally it would like to come to c3 via b1. }
12... exd5 13. e3
{ Strengthening the center. In case of  13.Nb1  Black again has  13...Ne4  and the knights will be exchanged when White plays Nc3. Then, Black will continue with his plan to double on the a-file, take on a4, and exert pressure on a2. }
13... Qa8 14. Nb1
{ White continues with his plan to activate the limited knight from d2. } 14...
Ne4
{ The typical reaction, in case the knight comes to c3, Black will take it. Taking on a4 is premature as it allows White to expand on the queenside after  14...Rxa4  15.Nc3  Ra5  16.a4 }
15. Nfd2 { White still fights for the c3-square. } 15... Nb4
{ Since White must take on e4 to develop the knight to c3, Black targets the d3-square that he will control after the pawn from d5 takes on e4. }
16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Nc3 Nd3
{ The knight is very strong on d3. Now Black wants to play ...Bb4, to attack the defender of the a4-pawn. }
18. Rb1 Bb4 19. Nb5
{ White tries to counterattack, but Black's pieces are the more active ones. After }
19... Rxa4 20. Nxc7 Qa5
{ Black's activity more than compensates for the pawn. A sample line is } 21.
a3 b5
{ Playing for a blockade. Taking on a3 would let the knight out after Bxa3 and Nb5. }
22. Nxb5 Qxb5 23. axb4 Bd5
{ With total domination as the bishop on b2 will never see the light of day. }
