1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7
{ Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2
{ This is the beginning of the King's Indian Attack @@StartBracket@@KIA@@EndBracket@@. The idea is to push e4-e5 and then develop with Re1, Nf1, h4-h5, N1h2-g4, Bf4, and obtain a threatening position on the kingside. This is all very automatic for White so it makes practical sense not to enter these waters. Black's next move is aimed at precisely that - to change the character of the position so White cannot play his well-rehearsed set-up. }
6... Nc6
{ The idea of this move is to play ...e5, thus stopping White's plan of e4-e5 in its tracks. }
7. e4
{ This is the KIA move, still aiming for reversed King's Indian positions. The move  7.c4  is inferior as after  7...d4  followed by ...e5. Black will have good central control while White's counterplay is lacking. }
7... dxe4
{ This exchange makes sure that a pawn will stand on e4, thus closing the long diagonal for the bishop on g2. }
8. dxe4 e5
{ This was Black's idea that started with the move 6...Nc6. The bishop on g2 is passive and Black's dark-squared bishop can be activated via c5. }
9. c3
{ White controls the d4-square and prepares for a possible queenside expansion with b4. }
9... a5 { Preventing b4. } 10. a4 Bc5 { Activating the bishop. } 11. Qc2 Be6
{ Preventing Nc4. } 12. Ng5 Bd7
{ Black will play ...h6 next to chase away the knight, and then he will return with the bishop on e6. }
13. Nc4 h6 14. Nf3 Qe7 { Defending the pawn on e5 and connecting the rooks. }
15. Ne3
{ One of White's main ideas in these structures is to try to obtain control and perhaps put a piece on d5 or f5. }
15... Be6
{ Black's bishop on e6 is ideally placed to control both these squares. } 16.
Nh4 { White continues with his plan. } 16... Rfd8
{ Liberating the f8-square for the queen. After } 17. Nhf5 Qf8
{ Black wants to double on the d-file while he can challenge the knight on f5 by playing ...Ne7. At some point, he may consider the typical idea of ...Kh7 and ...g6, to take control over the f5-square. }
