1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6
{ Note that the move  3.Bf4  after  3...c5  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6  would transpose to the London System,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  As seen in the line  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6 }
3. e4 { The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit is unsound in more than one way. } 3... dxe4
4. f3 exf3 5. Nxf3 c6
{ Black's plan is to play ...c6 and ...e6 after getting the bishop outside the pawn chain. }
6. Bc4
{ In case of  6.Bd3  preventing ...Bf5 then  6...Bg4  followed by ...e6. } 6...
Bf5 7. O-O e6 8. Ng5
{ This is an unsound sacrificial attempt. The threat is to take on  f7  , but Black parries it with the retreat of the bishop. After  8.Ne5  Bg6  we transpose to the line starting with 7.Ne5,   while  8.Bg5  Be7  also gives White nothing. }
8... Bg6 9. Bxe6 { This doesn't work, the refutation is straightforward. } 9...
fxe6 10. Nxe6 Qd6
{ Putting the queen on d6 leaves the d7-square for the knight from b8. } 11.
Qe2 Kf7 12. Ng5+ Kg8 13. Qc4+ Nd5 { The checks ended and Black is winning. } *

