[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Veresov Attack #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6
{ Note that the move  3.Bf4  after  3...c5  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6  would transpose to the London System,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  As seen in the line  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6 }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. It is not very popular nowadays, and the reason is that the main idea of the opening, to push e4, backfires for White in all the lines. In fact, White's best play is to play slowly with Nf3 and e3, but then why put the knight on c3? }
3... c6
{ This is actually a small provocation, as Black can also start with  3...Nbd7  and then most lines probably transpose to the lines we analyze. The point of the provocation is to nudge white to take on f6, which some Veresov players like to do, but then Black has excellent play with a clear plan in mind. Another point of the move is that it opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen so she can come to b6 or a5. }
4. Qd3
{ This is another attempt to push e4, but again this is not very effective. White should switch to slower play if he is to obtain a normal game. }
4... Nbd7 { Developing and preparing ...e5. } 5. e4 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7. Qxe4
Qb6 { An unpleasant move for White to meet. } 8. Bc1
{ The point of Black's last move was that in case of the natural  8.O-O-O  Black has the double attack  8...Qa5  hitting the bishop on g5 and the pawn on a2.  The move   8.b3  is ugly, weakening the dark squares, which can be seen after  8...Nf6  9.Bxf6  Qa5  and the king is forced to move when Black will recapture on f6 with a better position after  10.Kd1  gxf6 }
8... Nf6 9. Qe5 Ng4
{ Black wants to chase away the queen from e5 so as to be able to develop by ...g6 and ...Bg7. }
10. Qe4 g6
{ with very good play for Black after ...Bg7 and ...O-O. White still needs to finish development and his queen is exposed to attacks. }
*

