3... c6
{ This is actually a small provocation, as Black can also start with  3...Nbd7  and then most lines probably transpose to the lines we analyze. The point of the provocation is to nudge white to take on f6, which some Veresov players like to do, but then Black has excellent play with a clear plan in mind. Another point of the move is that it opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen so she can come to b6 or a5. }
4. Qd3
{ This is another attempt to push e4, but again this is not very effective. White should switch to slower play if he is to obtain a normal game. }
4... Nbd7 { Developing and preparing ...e5. } 5. Nf3
{ Castling long with  5.O-O-O  only exposes the king to an attack after  5...b5  followed by ...Qa5, ... b4, ...Nb6, etc. }
5... h6
{ It's useful to include this move. In the future, Black may expand with ...g5. }
6. Bf4
{ Controlling the e5-square. Black would develop in the same manner after  6.Bh4 }
6... g6
{ This is a typical development of the bishop when the knight is on d7. Black avoids ...e6 in order to leave the h3-c8 diagonal open for the light-squared bishop. }
7. h3 { Opening a luft for the bishop on f4. } 7... Bg7 8. e3 O-O
{ Black finished the development of his kingside, and now his plan is to try to push ...e5. He plans to do that by playing ...Re8, ...Nh5, and ...e5. }
9. Ne5
{ White prevents Black's plan, but now after the exchange of the knight on d7, the bishop from c8 can be developed to f5. }
9... Nxe5 10. Bxe5 b5
{ Black can develop the bishop at any moment. With this advance, he grabs space on the queenside and prevents White's long castle. }
11. Be2 a5 12. O-O Bf5 13. Qd1 a4
{ The middlegame is complex. Black has good chances as he has good development and still wants to push ...e5 by exchanging the bishops after ...Nd7. }
*

