[Black "Veresov Attack #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nc3 Nf6
{ Note that the move  3.Bf4  after  3...c5  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6  would transpose to the London System,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  As seen in the line  2.Bf4  Nf6  3.e3  c5  4.Nc3  cxd4  5.exd4  a6 }
3. Bg5
{ The Veresov Attack. It is not very popular nowadays, and the reason is that the main idea of the opening, to push e4, backfires for White in all the lines. In fact, White's best play is to play slowly with Nf3 and e3, but then why put the knight on c3? }
3... c6
{ This is actually a small provocation, as Black can also start with  3...Nbd7  and then most lines probably transpose to the lines we analyze. The point of the provocation is to nudge white to take on f6, which some Veresov players like to do, but then Black has excellent play with a clear plan in mind. Another point of the move is that it opens the a5-d8 diagonal for the queen so she can come to b6 or a5. }
4. e3 { This is objectively best for White, but it doesn't pose any problems. }
4... Qb6
{ This is another small advantage of playing c6 - the queen can quickly get to b6 to attack the b2-pawn. Now in order to defend that pawn, White must lose the right to castle long. }
5. Rb1
{ Playing  5.b3  would weaken the dark squares which again would mean that castling long is out of the question. Black then continues with  5...Nbd7  with the idea of ...e5 and ...Bb4. }
5... Nbd7 { Connecting the knights. } 6. Nf3 g6
{ The only way to develop the bishop if Black doesn't want to close the h3-c8 diagonal. }
7. Bd3 Bg7 8. O-O O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and now wants to push ...e5 immediately, as he can recuperate the pawn after ...Ng4. }
9. h3 { Preventing ...Ng4 and ...e5. } 9... Re8 { Still aiming for ...e5. } 10.
Bf4 { White also fights for control over the e5-square. } 10... Nh5
{ By gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop on f4, Black finally manages to push ...e5. }
11. Bh2 e5 { Black fulfills his plan and he is comfortably equal here. } 12.
Be2 exd4
{ By taking on d4, Black makes the d4-pawn a target, using the fact that the knight on c3 cannot easily move and the move c3 isn't available. }
13. exd4 a5
{ A useful move, grabbing some space on the queenside, wanting to push further ...a4 and liberating the a7-square for the queen, so she can stay on the g1-a7 diagonal @@StartBracket@@for example if she is attacked by Na4@@EndBracket@@. Black now wants to increase the pressure on the d4-pawn by playing ...Nf8-e6. }
