[White "Chapter 10: Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Trompowsky #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky move is less effective when the knight is still on g8. } 2...
h6 { A useful move to insert. } 3. Bh4 c6
{ Black's plan is simple: he will play...Qb6, to allow the e7-pawn to move. Then, if ...e5 is possible, he will play it or develop the bishop to f5 and play ...e6. Now White has two options, to allow ...e5 or not. }
4. e3
{ This allows Black to push ...e5 in view of the undefended bishop on h4, and the lack of control over the e5-square. }
4... Qb6 5. Qc1
{ Or  5.b3  e5  6.Nf3  exd4  7.exd4  Bg4  with ...Be7 next with a comfortable position for Black. }
5... e5
{ The point is that the pawn cannot be taken in view of ...Qb4, and the bishop on h4 is lost. }
6. Nf3 exd4
{ This is the simplest in the symmetrical position. Black has comfortable development. }
7. exd4
{ Taking with the knight allows  7.Nxd4  c5  gaining more central space. } 7...
Be7
{ Developing with tempo as now, White needs to decide whether to take or go to g3. }
8. Bg3
{ In case of  8.Bxe7  Nxe7  9.Bd3  O-O  10.O-O  Bf5  Black exchanges the rather limited light-squared bishop and has no problems. }
8... Bf5 { Preventing the development of the White bishop to d3. } 9. Be2 Nf6
10. O-O O-O
{ Black has a very good position here. He is well-developed and can try to obtain the bishop pair by ...Nh5 or ...Ne4. }
*

