1. d4 d5 2. Bg5
{ The Trompowsky move is less effective when the knight is still on g8. } 2...
h6 { A useful move to insert. } 3. Bh4 c6
{ Black's plan is simple: he will play...Qb6, to allow the e7-pawn to move. Then, if ...e5 is possible, he will play it or develop the bishop to f5 and play ...e6. Now White has two options, to allow ...e5 or not. }
4. Nf3 { This move controls the e5-square, thus preventing ...e5. } 4... Qb6
{ Now again White needs to decide how to defend the pawn on b2, either by Qc1 or by b3. }
5. b3 Bf5
{ Black's development is easy. The bishop goes outside the pawn chain, and then ...e6 followed by ...Be7. }
6. e3 e6 7. Bd3
{ The move  7.Be2  doesn't change Black's plan of  7...Be7  with similar play. }
7... Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Be7 9. Bg3
