[Black "Trompowsky #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. c3 Nf6 3. Bg5 { is a very rare version of the Trompowsky idea. }
3... Ne4 { Attacking the bishop and gaining tempo. } 4. Bf4
{ The usual retreat in the Trompowsky. Going to h4 is dubious in view of  4.Bh4  g5  5.Bg3  h5  and the bishop is in trouble.   The move  4.h4  can also be met by  4...c5  with good play as the queen comes out to b6 and the knight to c6. }
4... c5 5. e3
{ White is playing a London System but with Black's knight on  e4  rather than on f6, which is obviously in Black's favor. After  5.Nf3  cxd4  6.cxd4  Nc6  7.Nc3  White has wasted a tempo on Bg5-f4 and is in fact a tempo down compared to the usual Exchange Slav. This gives Black easy play after  7...Nxc3  8.bxc3  g6  with ...Bg7, ...O-O to come, and then play against the backward c3-pawn and the weak c4-square. }
5... Nc6 { Black develops normally. } 6. Nd2 Nxd2
{ This is the simplest, gaining a tempo to develop the light-squared bishop. }
7. Qxd2 Bf5 8. Nf3 e6
{ Black has no problems whatsoever. He will finish development with ...Be7 or ...Bd6, and ...O-O and will play on the queenside, with or without taking on d4 first. }
