[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "The Colle System"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. e3
{ This is the Colle System, but after Black's next move, play resembles the London System as we reach the reversed Carlsbad structure. }
4... cxd4 5. exd4 Bf5
{ Black tries to prevent the development of the White bishop to d3. } 6. Bb5+
{ This disruptive check is the only way to create problems. The alternatives are either harmless or transpose to the London System. For example,  6.Bf4  Nc6  7.Qb3  Qc8  is the main line of theLondon System;   6.Qb3  Qc7  prevents the development of the bishop on f4;   6.Nh4  Bg4  7.Qb3  Qc7  is similar.   The move  6.Ne5  is met by  6...e6  and if  7.Bb5  Nfd7  with ...Bd6 and ...O-O next. }
6... Nbd7
{ The knight is better protected on d7, so there are no Ne5 ideas, which would have been annoying if the knight went to c6. }
7. Nh4
{ Again the only way for White, before Black manages to secure the bishop with ...h6. }
7... a6 { A good zwischenzug, to get rid of the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal. } 8.
Be2
{ Exchanging the bishops with  8.Nxf5  axb5  is obviously in Black's favor as he can use the b-pawn to execute the minority attack with ...b4, or in case of a3, the b5-pawn would provide better control over the c4-square. }
8... Bxb1
{ Perhaps a surprising decision, but since the bishop was going to be exchanged for a knight anyway, Black decides to avoid the doubling of the pawns on the g-file after Nxg6 hxg6. As it is mentioned in the chapter on the London System, this structure with pawns on g7 and g6 allows White the long-term plan of g3, h4, Kg2, Rh1, Bg5xf6 and h5, creating attack on the kingside. }
9. Rxb1 e6
{ Now we have a calm reversed Carlsbad structure where Black develops comfortably. }
10. Nf3 Bd6
{ An active development of the bishop that also prevents the development of the White bishop to f4. }
11. O-O O-O 12. Bd3 Qc7
{ Black finished development and has a very solid position. His plan in this structure is to organize the minority attack with ...b5-b4 @@StartBracket@@perhaps aided by ...a5 or putting a rook on b8 and/or c8@@EndBracket@@. His other ideas include putting a knight on e4 or c4, exchanging the dark-squared bishop by ...Bf4, or sometimes pushing ... e5 in order to obtain active piece play. }
