1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. dxc5
{ White has a couple of transpositions at his disposal. After   4.Bf4  Nc6  we have the London System;  after   4.Bg5  Ne4  5.Bf4  cxd4  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line mentioned in the comments to White's 5th move after   2.c3  Nf6  3.Bg5  Ne4  4.Bf4  c5  where White is a tempo-down spent on Bg5-f4 compared to the usual Exchange Slav. }
4... a5 { Preventing b4. Now White has several options. } 5. c4
{ This is an attempt to play in the center, but it's obvious that with a tempo down spent on c3-c4, White cannot count on much. }
5... e6 { Black wants to develop the bishop by taking on c5. } 6. Be3
{ White cannot really defend the pawn, as after } 6... Na6
{ Now White cannot add one more defender to defend the c5-pawn. } 7. cxd5 Qxd5
8. Bd4
{ The idea is to prevent the exchange of queens and play Nc3 next, attacking the queen on d5. }
8... Bxc5 { Black develops with tempo and wants to castle next. } 9. Nc3 Qd8
{ Black wants to exchange on d4 now. } 10. e4 Bxd4 11. Qxd4 Qxd4 12. Nxd4 Ke7
{ With an equal endgame as Black has a solid position after ... Bd7, followed by ...Rhd8 and ...Rac8. If necessary, the bishop can drop back to e8 in order not to block the d-file. }
