1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. dxc5
{ White has a couple of transpositions at his disposal. After   4.Bf4  Nc6  we have the London System;  after   4.Bg5  Ne4  5.Bf4  cxd4  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line mentioned in the comments to White's 5th move after   2.c3  Nf6  3.Bg5  Ne4  4.Bf4  c5  where White is a tempo-down spent on Bg5-f4 compared to the usual Exchange Slav. }
4... a5 { Preventing b4. Now White has several options. } 5. e4
{ This is a rather surprising engine suggestion that leads to sharp play. }
5... Nxe4
{ Black avoids the exchange of queens because then he loses the right to castle and White can attack with Ng5 and so on. }
6. Bb5+ Bd7
{ Black sacrifices a pawn for the bishop pair and control over the light squares. The move  6...Nc6  runs into  7.Ne5 }
7. Qxd5 Bxb5 8. Qxe4 Bc6
{ This is simpler than  8...e6  which sacrifices a second pawn on b7. } 9. Qe2
e6
{ If Black is allowed to regain the pawn, he will stand better because of the bishop pair, so White must defend the c5-pawn. }
10. b4 axb4 11. cxb4 Na6
{ This is a key move that exerts unpleasant pressure on White's queenside. The tactical point is that the move b5 is always met with ...Bxf3, attacking the queen, and ...Nxc5 regaining the pawn with a good position. }
12. Bd2 { The only decent way to defend the pawn on b4. } 12... Be7
{ Black develops and threatens ...Bf6. } 13. a4
{ Liberating the a2 and a3 squares for the rook. } 13... Bf6 14. Ra3 O-O
{ Black finished development and will continue attacking the queenside pawns. }
15. O-O Qd7
{ White cannot defend his queenside pawns anymore. For example, after } 16. b5
Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nxc5 18. Bb4 Rfc8
{ Black has no problems and will continue to play against White's advanced queenside pawns. }
