1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. dxc5
{ White has a couple of transpositions at his disposal. After   4.Bf4  Nc6  we have the London System;  after   4.Bg5  Ne4  5.Bf4  cxd4  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line mentioned in the comments to White's 5th move after   2.c3  Nf6  3.Bg5  Ne4  4.Bf4  c5  where White is a tempo-down spent on Bg5-f4 compared to the usual Exchange Slav. }
4... a5 { Preventing b4. Now White has several options. } 5. e3
{ With this move, White signals that he will try to defend the c5-pawn by pushing b4. By moving the e-pawn, he opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop in order to be able to develop it on b5. }
5... e6 { Black continues normally, attacking the c5-pawn. } 6. b4 b6
{ Attacking White's exposed queenside. } 7. a4 bxc5 8. b5
{ White obtained a protected passed pawn on b5, but after } 8... c4
{ This is an important move, as it prevents c4, takes away d3 from White's bishop, and liberates the c5-square for the Black knight. }
9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O Qc7 { Black develops naturally. } 12. Qc2 Bd6
{ With very smooth play for Black. The b5-pawn is not going anywhere as it's controlled, and White's pieces cannot support it while Black has excellent development and central control that he can use to expand in the center with ...e5, and then use that center to create an attack on the kingside. }
