1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c3 c5 4. dxc5
{ White has a couple of transpositions at his disposal. After   4.Bf4  Nc6  we have the London System;  after   4.Bg5  Ne4  5.Bf4  cxd4  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 2@@EndFEN@@)  we have a transposition to the line mentioned in the comments to White's 5th move after   2.c3  Nf6  3.Bg5  Ne4  4.Bf4  c5  where White is a tempo-down spent on Bg5-f4 compared to the usual Exchange Slav. }
4... a5 { Preventing b4. Now White has several options. } 5. e3
{ With this move, White signals that he will try to defend the c5-pawn by pushing b4. By moving the e-pawn, he opens the diagonal for the light-squared bishop in order to be able to develop it on b5. }
5... e6 { Black continues normally, attacking the c5-pawn. } 6. b4 b6
{ Attacking White's exposed queenside. } 7. cxb6
{ After  7.Bb5  Bd7  8.Bxd7  Nfxd7  White's queenside pawn structure collapses. }
7... axb4 8. Qd4
{ For the time being this defends the b6-pawn, but it's clear that a pawn so deep in enemy territory cannot last for long. }
8... b3
{ The pawn on b4 was hanging so Black uses the pin on the a-file to keep his own advanced pawn alive. }
9. a4 Nbd7
{ Attacking the b6-pawn. Note that White cannot defend it by  10.a5  since after  10...Nxb6  Black takes it anyway in view of the pin on the a-file and the undefended rook on a1. }
10. Bb5 Ba6
{ Now Black attacks the bishop on b5, again thanks to the pin on the a-file. }
11. c4
{ After  11.Bxa6  Rxa6  the pawn on b6 falls. This defends the bishop but after }
11... dxc4 12. Bxa6 Rxa6 13. Qxc4 Rxb6
{ Black captured the b6-pawn while at the same time keeping his b3-pawn alive. He will finish development with ... Be7 and ...O-O and will play on the queenside, supporting the advanced pawn. }
