{ This is less good than the London System because it improves the position of the Black knight - it's obvious it is more active on e4 than on f6. }
3... Ne4 4. Bf4 c5 { Black plays the same ...c5 as against the London System. }
5. e3 cxd4
{ Clarifying the structure in the center and transposing to a reversed Carlsbad structure, just like in the London System, only in a more favorable version for Black because of the more active knight on e4. }
6. exd4 Nc6 7. c3 Bg4
{ Black is more ambitious here thanks to the active centralized knight. } 8.
Qb3 Qd7
{ The queen defends both pawns on b7 and d5, and now Black wants to take on f3. }
9. Nbd2 Nxd2 10. Nxd2 Bf5
{ Preventing Bd3 with very easy play for Black. He simply develops with ...e6, ...Be7, and ...O-O. }
