1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bg5
{ This is less good than the London System because it improves the position of the Black knight - it's obvious it is more active on e4 than on f6. }
3... Ne4 4. Bh4 c5 5. e3 { In case of  5.Nbd2  Qb6  attacks both d4 and b2. }
5... Qb6 6. Nc3
{ This is the only move for White. The move  6.b3  is ugly as after  6...Nc6  the weaknesses of the dark squares on the queenside will tell after ideas like ...cxd4 and ... e5, followed by ...Bb4. }
6... Nxc3 { This is the simplest, immediately doubling White's c-pawns. } 7.
bxc3 Qa5
{ Moving away from the b-file and attacks with Rb1 and attacking the pawn on c3. }
8. Qd2 Nc6
{ Black develops and his plan is to play ...c4 and ...e6 @@StartBracket@@the bishop needs to stay on c8 to defend the b7-pawn as White's rook can attack it from b1@@EndBracket@@ which would be a favorable French structure for him. First, he would have the dark-squared bishop so there won't be any dark-square weaknesses. Second, White's pawn is on e3 and not on e5 as in the French, which is apparently in Black's favor. }
9. c4
{ Attempting to change the character of the game. In case of  9.Be2  c4  10.O-O  e6  11.a4  Bd6  Black will castle and will prepare his queenside expansion by ...b5, and then ...b4. }
9... Qxd2+ 10. Kxd2 dxc4
{ The pawn on d5 was hanging, so Black takes on c4 in order to speed up his development. }
11. Bxc4 e6
{ Black is somewhat lagging back in development so he doesn't open the game by taking on d4, and intends to develop with ...Be7 and ...Bd7. }
12. c3
{ If  12.d5  exd5  13.Bxd5  f6  @@StartBracket@@limiting the knight on f3 and the bishop on h4@@EndBracket@@ and then Black can develop easily with ...Bd7, ...Be7, and ...O-O-O. }
12... Bd7 13. Rab1 f6
{ Again limiting the knight on f3 and bishop on h4. Note that White cannot take on b7 in view of the fork on a5, hitting the bishop on c4 and the rook on b7. The endgame is fine for Black, who has a solid position and can castle long and finish development with ...Be7. }
