[White "Chapter 10: Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Colle/Zukertort Systems #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. Nbd2 cxd4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ Black again strives for the reversed Carlsbad structure. This line is similar to the one starting with  3.c3  c5  4.e3  cxd4  the difference being that here the knight is on d2 and the pawn is still on c2 @@StartBracket@@there the pawn was on c3 and the knight was on b1@@EndBracket@@. This difference means that the queen has no access to the d1-a4 diagonal, so Black has less worries about possible pins and checks. }
5. exd4 Bf5 6. Bb5+ { is another possibility. } 6... Nbd7
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ Just like in the line  3.c3  c5  4.e3  cxd4  5.exd4  Bf5  6.Bb5  Black covers with a knight on d7, avoiding unpleasant pins with Ne5, when a knight on c6 would be attacked. }
7. O-O
{ In case of  7.Nh4  Bg4  we see the problem for White not having moved the c2-pawn: the queen cannot go to b3 or a4. }
7... e6 8. c4
{ White attacks the center immediately, before Black finishes development with ...Bd6 and ...O-O. }
8... dxc4
{ After this capture, White has an IQP, which means that he mustn't allow Black to calmly finish development and castle. In that case, Black would simply be better because of his better structure. }
9. Nxc4 Be7
{ Black is one step away from castling, so White must act urgently. } 10. Bxd7+
{ The only way to try to make something of his active knights and seek compensation for the IQP. }
10... Qxd7
{ Black wants to castle next, so White must continue his tempo play. } 11. Nfe5
Qb5 { The queen must stay on the a4-e8 diagonal to prevent a check from a4. }
12. a4 Qa6
{ Here the queen cannot be attacked immediately, but White continues with his tempo play. }
13. b4 { Threatening b5 to trap the queen. } 13... b5
{ Preventing b5 and giving the queen some breathing space. } 14. Ne3 Be4
{ The bishop moves on the long diagonal from where it exerts more control over the blockading d5-square. }
15. f3 Bd5
{ There will never be a d5-break in this position, so White must continue to attack as if allowed to castle. In that case, Black will simply have a strategically winning position. This is due to his better structure, White's pawn weaknesses on b4 and d4, and the accompanying light-square weaknesses on d5 and c4. }
16. Qe2 O-O { Finally finishing development. After } 17. Qxb5 Qxb5 18. axb5
Rfb8
{ Black will regain the pawn and can play for a win thanks to his better structure and White's weak pawns. }
