[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. Nbd2 cxd4
{ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@ Black again strives for the reversed Carlsbad structure. This line is similar to the one starting with  3.c3  c5  4.e3  cxd4  the difference being that here the knight is on d2 and the pawn is still on c2 @@StartBracket@@there the pawn was on c3 and the knight was on b1@@EndBracket@@. This difference means that the queen has no access to the d1-a4 diagonal, so Black has less worries about possible pins and checks. }
5. exd4 Bf5 6. Ne5
{ This is the critical move. The tame  6.c3  gives nothing as it doesn't put any pressure on Black's position so he can develop smoothly with  6...Nc6  7.Bb5  Qb6  8.Qe2  e6  followed by ...Bd6, ...0-0 and so on. }
6... Nbd7
{ As mentioned before, putting the knight on d7 makes it less susceptible to Bb5 pins. }
7. g4
{ In case of  7.Ndf3  e6  followed by ...Be7 and ...O-O. Black has no problems as he comfortably finishes development and can then exchange on e5 with ...Nxe5 and start organizing his queenside minority attack. }
7... Nxe5
{ Moving the bishop to e6 or g6 would invite a pawn storm with f4 and h4, so Black eliminates the centralized knight and ruins White's structure in the process. }
8. gxf5 Nc6
{ Black will attack the f5-pawn by ...g6 and would like to exchange it. After fxg6 hxg6, he would have a compact pawn structure and the open h-file, while White's isolated h2- and f2-pawns will need constant attention. }
9. Nb3
{ White defends the pawn and opens the c1-h6 diagonal for the bishop on  c1  . In case of  9.c3  g6  Black wants to exchange the dark-squared bishops after ...Bh6, and continue with ...Qd6 and ...O-O-O, followed with the ...Nh5-g7 maneuver, to put pressure on the f5-pawn. }
9... g6 10. Qf3
{ White's plan is to keep the pawn on f5 and defend it with Bd3 or Bh3. } 10...
gxf5
{ Since White won't take on g6, Black takes on f5 to gain time to speed up his development. }
11. Qxf5 e6 12. Qf3 Ne4
{ Centralizing the knight and intending ...Qf6 or ...Qh4. } 13. Be3
{ After  13.Bd3  Qh4  Black threatens ...Nb4 when White will have problems defending both the bishop on d3 and the pawn on c2, while  14.a3  f5  with ...Bh6 next. This gives Black great play thanks to the centralized knight on e4. }
13... Qf6
{ After the exchange of queens, Black will have a very comfortable endgame. }
14. Qxf6 Nxf6 15. c3 Bd6
{ With ...Ke7 and ...Rag8 next. Black has very good play on the kingside where White has two isolated pawns, on h2 and f2. }
