1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. Bd3 Nc6
{ Natural development of the knight in absence of any pressure from White. } 5.
O-O cxd4
{ Black fixes the structure and enters the reversed Carlsbad, with its known ideas and plans. }
6. exd4 Bg4
{ Since the development of the bishop on f5 isn't possible, Black develops it on g4, pinning the knight on f3. This means that the pawn on d4 is hanging now so White must defend it. }
7. c3 e6 8. h3 Bh5
{ For the time being Black keeps both options, to take on f3 and to play ...Bg6, exchanging the light-squared bishops. }
9. Bf4 Bd6
{ A known motif, exchanging the dark-squared bishops allows Black to use his queen to control the dark squares, thus increasing her activity. }
10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Nbd2 O-O
{ Black has excellent play here. White's opening is harmless so Black can start preparing the usual plan in these structures, the minority attack, with ...a6, ...b5, ...Rab8, ...a5, ...b4, etc. }
