[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. c4
{ This move gives Black easy play as in the resulting positions, Black's development is smooth, and he has a clear-cut plan. }
4... cxd4 { With this capture, Black creates an IQP on d4. } 5. exd4 g6
{ This development is the best here - the fianchettoed bishop will provide good defence for the king and will exert pressure on White's isolated pawn on d4. }
6. Nc3 Bg7 7. cxd5
{ If  7.Qb3  then  7...dxc4  and ...O-O, with play against the IQP. } 7... Nxd5
8. Bc4 Nxc3
{ Black creates the pair c3-d4, and plans to play against the backward pawn on c3. }
9. bxc3 Qc7 { Immediately targeting the weaknesses on the c-file. } 10. Qb3 O-O
11. O-O Nc6 { The threat is ...Na5. } 12. Be2 Be6
{ Further increasing the control over the d5- and c4-squares. } 13. Qa3
{ Note that  13.d5?  Na5  wins the d5-pawn for Black. } 13... Rac8 14. Rb1 Rfd8
15. Be3 Na5
{ Black is already better, having placed his pieces on perfect squares. Anand's play in this game is exemplary, so check the remainder in the model game,Hebden-Anand. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 10: Various 2nd Moves"]
[Black "Colle/Zukertort Systems #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. b3
{ The Zukertort System is not an ambitious choice and Black has a free hand at choosing his preferred development. }
4... cxd4
{ By taking immediately on d4, Black fixes the structure. This is important because after White recaptures, we will have a reversed Carlsbad where the pawn on b3 is out of place. White would rather have c3 instead of it to connect his structure, and b3 also weakens the dark squares on the queenside, a3 and c3 specifically. }
5. exd4 Nc6 6. Bb2 Bg4
{ Black develops naturally and will continue with ...e6 and ...Bd6. } 7. Bd3
{ Though desirable, White runs into problems after this. } 7... Qa5+
{ This disruptive check shows that White's pieces are somewhat entangled. } 8.
Nbd2
{ The move  8.c3  loses a pawn to  8...Bxf3  9.Qxf3  Nxd4  thanks to the pin along the e1-a5 diagonal.   The other defense  8.Bc3  is just awkward as after  8...Qc7  9.O-O  e6  Black continues with normal development with ...Bd6, ...O-O while White needs to remove the bishop from c3 so that he can develop the knight from b1, thus wasting more time. }
8... Nb4
{ Hitting the bishop on d3. Now White's best is to leave it to be exchanged, because moving it to e2 is even worse. }
9. Qe2
{ White would like to keep the bishop, but after  9.Be2  Bxf3  10.Bxf3  Qc7  he cannot conveniently defend the c2-pawn. }
9... Nxd3+ 10. Qxd3 e6
{ With a better position for Black. White has absolutely no compensation for Black's pair of bishops, his own weakened queenside and passive bishop on b2. Black will continue with ...Bd6 and ...O-O, will put a rook on c8 and will continue with queenside play that can also be aided by putting the light-squared bishop on the b1-h7 diagonal. }
