1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. e3
{ This is the starting move for the Colle and Zukertort systems. Note that the move  3.g3  e6  would transpose to the chapter on theReti Opening   and the move  3.Bf4  would lead us to theLondon System. }
3... c5 4. dxc5
{ The move   4.c3  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@)  is analyzed after the   3.c3  c5  4.e3  move-order. }
4... e6 { Black simply wants to recapture on c5. } 5. c4
{ Note that  5.b4  a5  6.c3  b6  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/5n2/3p4/3P4/5N2/PPP1PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@)  transposes to the line analysed after   3.c3  c5  4.dxc5  a5  5.e3  e6  6.b4  b6 }
5... Bxc5 6. Nc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5
{ Black now has an IQP on d5, but he has quick development and manages to push ...d4 to get rid of it. }
8. Be2 Nc6 9. O-O a6
{ A necessary preparation for the ...d4 push. In case of   9...d4?  10.Na4  White wins the d4-pawn as the bishop cannot remain on the g1-a7 diagonal to defend it. With ...a6, Black opens the a7-square for the bishop, and ...d4 comes next as White cannot prevent it. }
10. a3 { Intending b4 and Bb2, but Black is faster with } 10... d4 11. exd4
Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxd4
{ With comfortable equality. The bishop from c8 will come to e6, and all of Black's pieces will be in the game. }
