[White "Chapter 11: Nimzowitsch-Larsen Opening"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Larsen Opening #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 { This has become quite a popular choice lately. } 1... d5 2. Bb2
{ After  2.Nf3  Nf6  White will play Bb2 sooner or later. For example, after  3.e3  e6  so we will have a transposition.   The same applies to  2.e3  Nf6 }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White has transpositional options, for example,   The capture on  f6  is harmless, after  3.Bxf6  exf6  Black has the plan of ...c6, ...Bd6, ...f5, ...Nd7-f6-e4 with excellent play.   3.g3  e6  will transpose to theReti after White plays c4 as will   3.Nf3  e6  4.g3 }
3... e6 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.f4  would transpose to the Bird's Opening,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  the line  1.f4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.b3 }
4... Be7 5. c4 { This is White's only way to create central play. } 5... O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and now he waits to see how White will develop. }
6. d4 c5 7. dxc5
{ This is an attempt to play a Queen's Gambit Accepted with colors reversed.  The capture on d5 is met by   7.cxd5  Nxd5  with ...b6 and ...Bb7 to follow next,  while the move   7.Nbd2  is met by the typical  7...b6  followed by ...Bb7 and ...Nbd7. The thing to remember is that whenever White takes on d5, Black should recapture with a piece.  In case of   7.Nc3  cxd4  we have a transposition to the chapter  The Main Line Various  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  The line   1.d4  d5  2.c4  e6  3.Nc3  Be7  4.Nf3  Nf6  5.e3  O-O  6.b3  c5  7.Bb2  cxd4 }
7... Bxc5 8. Nbd2
{ After  8.a3  threatening b4  8...dxc4  9.Qxd8  Rxd8  10.Bxc4  b6  followed by ...Bb7. The endgame is perfectly fine for Black.  The move   8.Nc3  @@StartBracket@@threatening to take on d5 and create an IQP@@EndBracket@@ can also be met by  8...dxc4  9.Bxc4  b6  with ...Bb7 to follow. }
8... b6
{ Black plays in the usual QGD manner, solving the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop. }
9. a3
{ Is a preparation for a queenside expansion, but it can be used by Black after }
9... Bb7 10. b4 Be7 11. Be2 a5
{ Forcing White to advance and liberate the c5-square for the knight after }
12. b5 Nbd7
{ With excellent play for Black as all his pieces are developed harmoniously. }
