1. b3 { This has become quite a popular choice lately. } 1... d5 2. Bb2
{ After  2.Nf3  Nf6  White will play Bb2 sooner or later. For example, after  3.e3  e6  so we will have a transposition.   The same applies to  2.e3  Nf6 }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White has transpositional options, for example,   The capture on  f6  is harmless, after  3.Bxf6  exf6  Black has the plan of ...c6, ...Bd6, ...f5, ...Nd7-f6-e4 with excellent play.   3.g3  e6  will transpose to theReti after White plays c4 as will   3.Nf3  e6  4.g3 }
3... e6 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.f4  would transpose to the Bird's Opening,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  the line  1.f4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.b3 }
4... Be7 5. c4 { This is White's only way to create central play. } 5... O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and now he waits to see how White will develop. }
6. Be2 b6 { Black prepares to fianchetto the light-squared bishop. } 7. O-O Bb7
8. d3
{ With this move, White wants to develop in hedgehog style. In case of   8.cxd5  Nxd5  9.d4  Nd7  with ...c5 to follow, Black has no problems.  The same applies to   8.d4  Nbd7  9.Nc3  c5  when taking on d5 will always be met by a piece recapture to keep the long diagonal open for the light-squared bishop. }
8... c5 9. Nbd2 Nbd7
{ Black develops and has the same idea as in the Reti Opening. After } 10. a3
Qc7
{ He wants to play ...Rac8 and ...Qb8, an idea we saw in the main line of the Reti. The other rook will come to d8, and the queen can also further go to a8 to increase the control over the long diagonal. Black will be perfectly placed for the ensuing middlegame. }
