[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 11: Nimzowitsch-Larsen Opening"]
[Black "Nimzowitsch-Larsen Opening #7"]
[Result "*"]

1. b3 { This has become quite a popular choice lately. } 1... d5 2. Bb2
{ After  2.Nf3  Nf6  White will play Bb2 sooner or later. For example, after  3.e3  e6  so we will have a transposition.   The same applies to  2.e3  Nf6 }
2... Nf6 3. e3
{ White has transpositional options, for example,   The capture on  f6  is harmless, after  3.Bxf6  exf6  Black has the plan of ...c6, ...Bd6, ...f5, ...Nd7-f6-e4 with excellent play.   3.g3  e6  will transpose to theReti after White plays c4 as will   3.Nf3  e6  4.g3 }
3... e6 4. Nf3
{ The move  4.f4  would transpose to the Bird's Opening,  (@@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@)  the line  1.f4  d5  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.e3  e6  4.b3 }
4... Be7 5. c4 { This is White's only way to create central play. } 5... O-O
{ Black finished the development of the kingside and now he waits to see how White will develop. }
6. Nc3
{ Taking on d5 is premature as after  6.cxd5  exd5  Black will develop comfortably with ...c6, ...Bf5/Bg4, ...Nbd7 in a natural Carlsbad-structure style. White's bishop on b2 makes it awkward for White to play the d4-move as it will close the long diagonal and leave it passive. However, now with a knight on c3, White wants to take on d5, so Black pre-empts that capture by opening the long diagonal for his light-squared bishop. }
6... dxc4 { Opening the long diagonal before White can take on d5. } 7. bxc4 c5
{ Now in case, White wants to push d4 after ...cxd4, exd4, there will be hanging pawns in the center. Black develops quickly, so he will be well-placed to deal with these pawns. }
8. Be2 b6 9. Qc2 { This move is connected to the aggressive idea to push g4. }
9... Bb7 10. Rg1
{ Moving away from the long diagonal and clearly showing what the intention is. }
10... Nc6
{ Threatening ...Nb4 at a convenient moment, so White must take time to prevent it. }
11. a3 Na5
{ This is a good move. It prevents g4 so White must spend a tempo to defend the c4-pawn by d3, thus closing the b1-h7 diagonal and decreasing White's attacking potential by shutting the queen on c2. }
12. d3
{ Note that  12.g4  is met by  12...Nxc4  the bishop on e2 is overloaded defending both the pawn on c4 and the knight on f3. This was the idea behind Black's 11th move. }
12... Ne8
{ Removing the knight in due time @@StartBracket@@to avoid g4-g5 attacks@@EndBracket@@ and placing it on d6, from where it still controls the e4-square and can also jump to f5. }
13. g4
{ The move  13.Ne4  is met by  13...f5  and the knight must retreat when Black will follow up with ...Bf6. }
13... Nd6 14. g5
{ It is important to understand what White wants here. The immediate threat is Ne4 and Qc3, while long-term he will castle long and push the h-pawn to create more kingside play. }
14... f5 { An important move that prevents White's idea of Ne4 and Qc3. } 15.
gxf6
{ Opening of the g-file doesn't bring anything to White as it only helped activate the dark-squared bishop. }
15... Bxf6 16. Rg3
{ Preparing to castle long and double on the g-file, but Black has a very strong response to White's long castle. }
16... Rf7 { Defending g7 in advance. } 17. O-O-O Bxf3
{ This is the surprising reaction. Black wins a tempo to start his own attack after }
18. Bxf3 Rb8
{ And with ...b5 to come, he will have excellent counterplay on the queenside. }
