{ It is important to understand what White wants here. The immediate threat is Ne4 and Qc3, while long-term he will castle long and push the h-pawn to create more kingside play. }
14... f5 { An important move that prevents White's idea of Ne4 and Qc3. } 15.
Nb1
{ Since Ne4 is not possible, White reroutes the knight to d2 via b1 and at the same time liberates the c3-square for the queen. }
15... f4
{ A multi-purpose move. First, Black wants to take on e3 and attack the knight on f3 twice. Second, he liberates the f5-square for the knight on d6 in order to defend against Qc3. }
16. e4 Nc6 { Controlling the dark squares in the center. } 17. Nbd2
{ If  17.Qc3  then calmly  17...Ne8  with the idea of ...Bd6 and ...e5, shutting the long diagonal. }
17... Qc7
{ The middlegame is very unusual and complex. Black's play concentrates on the dark squares in the center, his idea is to either play ...Rad8 and jump ...Nd4 @@StartBracket@@sometimes even with a pawn sacrifice in order to open up the game@@EndBracket@@ or to play ...Ne8 and push ...e5, fixing the hole on d4 and planting a knight there. }
