{ Immediately challenging the centralized knight on e5. } 15. Bd3 g6
{ Blunting the b1-h7 diagonal. Black doesn't worry about the long diagonal as he wants to close it by taking on e5. Besides, he still has the dark-squared bishop to control the dark-squares. }
16. Rfe1 Nxe5
{ Eliminating the centralized knight and weakening the defense of the c4-pawn. }
17. dxe5 Qe8
{ Moving away from the d-file and renewing the attack on the c4-pawn. Black has good counterchances in this middlegame. He has the better structure and his pieces are well-placed. Black also has pressure on the c4-pawn and White's pieces are far from the kingside to create any sensible threats. }
