[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 12: Bird's Opening"]
[Black "Reversed Leningrad #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. f4
{ After Black's next move, Bird's Opening is practically a reversed Dutch. Since White has 4 set-ups in the Dutch, we will take a look at all of them. These are:    1. The Classical Dutch with e3, d3 and Be2    2. The Nimzo/Dutch mixture of e3, Be2, b3 and Bb2    3. The Stonewall with e3 and d4    4. The Leningrad Dutch with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop after g3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ This move is played in all the versions so the fork is on the next move. }
2... Nf6 3. g3
{ This is the Leningrad Dutch @@StartBracket@@obviously reversed@@EndBracket@@. }
3... e6 { Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6.
d3 b5
{ Black prepares the fianchetto of the bishop and at the same time, gains space on the queenside. Now White can try several set-ups. }
7. c3
{ This move liberates the c2-square for the knight. This maneuver Na3-c2 is typical for the Leningrad Dutch @@StartBracket@@there it is ...Na6-c7@@EndBracket@@ }
7... Bb7 8. Na3 a6
{ Defending the pawn on b5 before advancing further with ...c5. } 9. Qe1 c5 10.
Nc2 Nbd7
{ Black is very comfortable behind his pawns, and now will proceed with his queenside play with ...a5 and ...b4. }
11. b4 { Trying to stop Black's queenside expansion. } 11... Rc8
{ White's last move weakened the c-file, the c3-pawn in particular, so Black immediately activates the rook there. }
12. Bd2
{ This isn't very good, but I give it to show a curious version of a piece trap. After   12.bxc5  Nxc5  the knight can continue to a4 to put even more pressure on the c3-pawn. }
12... cxb4 13. Nxb4 Qb6+ 14. Kh1 d4
{ With the amusing trapping of the knight after } 15. cxd4 a5 *

