1. f4
{ After Black's next move, Bird's Opening is practically a reversed Dutch. Since White has 4 set-ups in the Dutch, we will take a look at all of them. These are:    1. The Classical Dutch with e3, d3 and Be2    2. The Nimzo/Dutch mixture of e3, Be2, b3 and Bb2    3. The Stonewall with e3 and d4    4. The Leningrad Dutch with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop after g3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ This move is played in all the versions so the fork is on the next move. }
2... Nf6 3. g3
{ This is the Leningrad Dutch @@StartBracket@@obviously reversed@@EndBracket@@. }
3... e6 { Black develops in the usual QGD fashion. } 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6.
d3 b5
{ Black prepares the fianchetto of the bishop and at the same time, gains space on the queenside. Now White can try several set-ups. }
7. Qe1
{ This is a typical move in the Leningrad Dutch. The queen supports the e4-push and she can also move to the kingside to g3 after h3 and g4. }
7... Bb7 { Black develops and prevents e4. } 8. Nbd2
{ Is an attempt to push e4 at all costs, but doesn't bring much to White. }
8... c5 9. e4 dxe4 10. Nxe4
{ In case of   10.dxe4  c4  Black liberates the c5-square and develops freely with ideas like ...Qb6, ...Nbd7-c5, etc. }
10... Nbd7 11. Qe2 Qc7
{ This is very comfortable for Black. He will put the rooks on d8 and c8 and will seek play on the queenside via ... c4 at an appropriate moment. }
