1. f4
{ After Black's next move, Bird's Opening is practically a reversed Dutch. Since White has 4 set-ups in the Dutch, we will take a look at all of them. These are:    1. The Classical Dutch with e3, d3 and Be2    2. The Nimzo/Dutch mixture of e3, Be2, b3 and Bb2    3. The Stonewall with e3 and d4    4. The Leningrad Dutch with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop after g3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ This move is played in all the versions so the fork is on the next move. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 { Now White has a choice between the 3 versions. } 4. d4
{ This is the Stonewall. The idea is to play c3, Bd3, plant a knight on e5, and then organize an attack on the kingside with the help of these two pieces, with other ideas being Qe1-g3, Bd2-e1-h4, Nd2-f3, etc. }
4... Be7
{ Black develops normally for now, but the thing he should remember is that he must try to exchange White's light-squared bishop as soon as possible. }
5. Bd3 b6
{ This is the key move. In the Stonewall structure, White's bishop on d3 is the best piece, so better to exchange it as soon as possible. }
6. O-O
{ White cannot prevent the exchange as after   6.Qe2  a5  Black will still play ...Ba6 next. In fact, the move ...a5 is in his favor because his general plan in this structure is to advance with his pawns on the queenside with ...c5, ...b5-b4, and the ...a5 move is part of that plan.  A small trick to be aware of is that in case of   6.c3  @@StartBracket@@opening the d1-a4 diagonal for the queen@@EndBracket@@ Black should first castle with  6...O-O  @@StartBracket@@in order to prevent the embarrassing check on a4 losing a piece in case he plays ...Ba6 immediately@@EndBracket@@ and then play ...Ba6, exchanging the bishops. }
6... Ba6 7. Bxa6 Nxa6 8. Ne5
{ After   8.Qe2  Qc8  is a good move to play. Black will continue with ...c5, and then the knight from a6 can go to c7, e8, and d6, reaching the ideal square for this structure. From d6, the knight controls the weak light squares e4 and c4 and also supports the queenside advance with ...b5-b4. Black's advantage in this structure is that his knight on e4 is an eternal one, it cannot be chased away with a pawn, while White's knight on e5 can be chased away by ...f6. Coupled with the better bishop @@StartBracket@@not limited by its own pawns@@EndBracket@@ and the long-term plan to push ...e5 @@StartBracket@@helped by ... f6@@EndBracket@@ all these factors determine Black's advantage in this Stonewall structure after the exchange of the light-squared bishops. }
8... c5
{ Liberating the c7-square for the knight for the already-mentioned maneuver ...Nc7-e8-d6. }
9. Qe2 Nc7
{ Black will castle next and will play ... Ne8-d6 with a very comfortable position. He doesn't mind the knight exchange on e5 for the bishop on e7. Nc6xe7 is nothing to worry about because he will play with the knights, and this exchange would mean exchanging White's centralized knight, which Black can only welcome. }
