{ After Black's next move, Bird's Opening is practically a reversed Dutch. Since White has 4 set-ups in the Dutch, we will take a look at all of them. These are:    1. The Classical Dutch with e3, d3 and Be2    2. The Nimzo/Dutch mixture of e3, Be2, b3 and Bb2    3. The Stonewall with e3 and d4    4. The Leningrad Dutch with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop after g3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ This move is played in all the versions so the fork is on the next move. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 { Now White has a choice between the 3 versions. } 4. Be2 Be7
5. O-O O-O 6. d3
{ With this move, White shows his intention to play the Classical Dutch, whose idea is to play Qe1-g3 and aim for the e4-push with the help of Nc3. Note that in case of   6.b3  we have a transposition to the Nimzo/ Dutch version analysed after 4.b3. }
6... b5
{ A move that aims to prevent the development of the knight to c3. It also liberates the b7-square for the light-squared bishop, from where it will control the e4-square and make the central push impossible. }
