Qg3
{ Since e4 is not possible, @@StartBracket@@because the pawn on f4 is hanging@@EndBracket@@ White changes his plan and now wants to play Ne5 and Ndf3. }
10... Nbd7
{ Black also fights for the e5-square, but is not blocking the light-squared bishop by putting a knight on c6. }
11. Ne5 c4
{ Black continues with his queenside advance. He keeps control over the e5-square even though White cannot make anything with a sole knight there and the other pieces heavily underdeveloped. }
12. Ndf3 { In case of   12.d4  c3  Black crashes through on the queenside. }
12... b4
{ It is apparent that Black's queenside play is well-advanced while White hasn't managed to achieve anything with his pretty knight on e5. Black will continue to put pressure on the queenside with ...a5, ...Ba6, ...Nc5, and will seek a way how to open the position there. }
