1. f4
{ After Black's next move, Bird's Opening is practically a reversed Dutch. Since White has 4 set-ups in the Dutch, we will take a look at all of them. These are:    1. The Classical Dutch with e3, d3 and Be2    2. The Nimzo/Dutch mixture of e3, Be2, b3 and Bb2    3. The Stonewall with e3 and d4    4. The Leningrad Dutch with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop after g3. }
1... d5 2. Nf3
{ This move is played in all the versions so the fork is on the next move. }
2... Nf6 3. e3 e6 { Now White has a choice between the 3 versions. } 4. b3 Be7
5. Bb2 O-O 6. Bd3
{ This development of the bishops was became famous after the classical game, Lasker-Bauer 1889. However, there are several problems with this placement of the bishop. First, it is exposed to a knight attack from c5 or b4. Second, it blocks the d2-pawn so White cannot control the e4-square. Third, the bishop can easily be exchanged after ...Ba6 @@StartBracket@@again because there is no possibility to close the f1-a6 diagonal with d3@@EndBracket@@. }
6... c5
{ Black expands in the center. Having a pawn on c5 is useful in case he manages to shut the long diagonal with ...d4. }
7. O-O b6
{ Preparing the development of the bishop on b7 or a6 and also keeping it flexible with the development of the knight on b8. For example, from its starting position it helps the exchange of the bishops on a6. }
8. Ne5
{ White must be precise. In case of   8.Qe1  Nc6  all of a sudden there is the double threat of ...d4, shutting the long diagonal, and ...Nb4. The latter will force the bishop exchange on d3 since the queen is no longer defending the c2-pawn, so the bishop cannot leave the d3-square. }
8... Ba6
{ This is the simplest, exchanging the active bishop. With the light-squared bishops gone, White can never create an attack and Black has smooth middlegame play. }
9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nc6
{ Exchanging the bishop on e7 is fine for Black. In case of   10.Qe2  Qc8  he will reroute the knight from a6 to c6 @@StartBracket@@via b4 or b8@@EndBracket@@ to challenge and exchange the knight on e5. Long term his plan will be to push ...e5 @@StartBracket@@by playing ...f6 first@@EndBracket@@ or to expand on the queenside with ...b5, ...a5 and then ...c4 or ...a4, depending on circumstances. }
10... Qd7 11. Nxe7+ Qxe7 12. d3 Rac8
{ Black centralizes his rooks and then brings the knight from a6 back into the game. }
13. Nd2 Rfd8 14. Nf3 Nb4
{ The knight will come to c6, and then Black will expand on the queenside with ...b5, ...a5-a4, or ... c4. Black may also concentrate on the e5-square and play ...Ne8/d7 and ...f6. }
