1. d3
{ This is a rare guest, but it may be an introduction to a reversed Philidor or Leningrad Dutch. }
1... d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. f4
{ In case of  4.Nf3  Be7  we have a transposition to either theReti or theKing's Indian Attack, depending on whether White plays for c4 or e4 respectively. }
4... Be7 5. e4
{ This isn't very good. In case of  5.Nf3  O-O  we have a transposition to theBird's Opening where White's plan of the reversed Leningrad Dutch is analyzed. }
5... dxe4 6. dxe4 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Nc6
{ Black develops and the threat is to push ...e5 and to play ...Bd7 and ...O-O-O. White is lagging back in development and his king is stuck in the center, while Black is almost developed so it is clear that he is the one who is attacking. A sample line is }
8. e5 { Preventing ...e5. } 8... Ng4
{ The threat is ... Nf2 so White must move the king again. } 9. Ke1 Bd7
{ Black wants to castle, which will connect his rooks, and then he will open the position in the center with ...f6. }
10. h3 Nh6 11. g4 { Preventing ...Nf5, but White plays too many pawn moves. }
11... O-O-O
{ And with ...f6 next, White's center will collapse and Black will obtain more space for his pieces. }
