[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13: Various 1st Moves"]
[Black "Reversed Philidor via 1.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. d3
{ This is a rare guest, but it may be an introduction to a reversed Philidor or Leningrad Dutch. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nbd2
{ White is flexible, he can either go for the reversed Philidor with e4 and Be2, or for the King's Indian Attack with g3, Bg2, and e4. }
3... Bg4
{ This is the simplest solution. Black develops the bishop outside the pawn chain and will then develop comfortably. }
4. e4
{ White plays the reversed Philidor. In case of   4.h3  Bxf3  5.Nxf3  c5  Black will develop with ... Nc6, ...e6, ...Be7, and ...O-O. Black will have smooth development with good central control.  The move   4.Ne5  can be met by  4...Bh5  followed by ...Nbd7. }
4... e6 5. Be2 Be7 6. O-O O-O
{ Black develops in QGD fashion, the only difference being the bishop is on g4 rather than on c8. }
7. c3 c5 8. h3 Bxf3
{ Black doesn't spend time on retreating the bishop, which would give White an opportunity to expand with g4, Nh4, and f4. }
9. Bxf3
{ This is necessary as taking with the knight leaves the e4-pawn undefended. }
9... Nc6
{ Black has very smooth development and White's bishop pair doesn't account for much. Black's plan now is to play ...Qc7 to defend the rooks, put the f8-rook on d8 @@StartBracket@@since the d-file can be opened in case White takes on d5 or Black takes on e4@@EndBracket@@ and then expand on the queenside with ... b5-b4. The rook from a8 will go to b8 or c8, depending on where it is needed more. }
*

