[White "Chapter 13: Various 1st Moves"]
[Black "KIA via 1.c3"]
[Result "*"]

1. c3
{ Is another rare move with options to transpose elsewhere after 2.d4 or to play a reversed Philidor. }
1... d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. d3 { White tries to play a reversed Philidor. } 3... Nbd7
{ Aiming for ...e5, but also keeping the option to play ...c6 to bolster the center. Note that the move  3...Bg4  which we play in the reversed Philidor after 1.d3 can be met by  4.Ne5  Bh5  5.Qa4  @@StartBracket@@this is the difference, the move 1.c3 opened the d1-a4 diagonal for the queen@@EndBracket@@ when Black's bishop on h5 is in some trouble after h4 and g4. }
4. Nbd2 { If  4.Bf4  then  4...Nh5  and ...e5 next. } 4... e5
{ Taking the center. } 5. e4 c6 6. g3
{ This is an alternative, but Black's development is the same. } 6... Bd6 7.
Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Re8
{ Black is very compact in the center. His plan of development is to move the knight from d7 to g6 @@StartBracket@@via f8@@EndBracket@@ from where it continues to bolster the e5-pawn, but it doesn't block the diagonal for the bishop on c8. Then, he can decide where to develop the bishop, to e6 @@StartBracket@@he will need to play ...h6 for this, to make sure Ng5 doesn't happen@@EndBracket@@ or to b7 after ...b6. The queen will go to c7 and the rook from a8 will likely come to d8. }
