[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13: Various 1st Moves"]
[Black "1.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. Nc3
{ This is sometimes played as White still keeps some options to transpose. If White insists on giving the game an independent character, he risks ending up in a worse position. }
1... d5 { Black plays the usual first move. } 2. e4
{ The only independent try, as  2.d4  Nf6  transposes to the chapterVarious 2nd Moves   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ the line  1.d4  d5  2.Nc3  Nf6  Objectively speaking, White should take this opportunity to transpose as 2.e4 lands him in an inferior position. }
2... d4 { Grabbing central space. } 3. Nce2 e5
{ Black's play is simple, expanding in the center. } 4. Ng3
{ Opening the diagonal for the light-squared bishop. Ideally, White would like to develop it to c4 and then play Nf3,  O-O  , d3, move the knight from f3 and push f4. In case of  4.Nf3  Bd6  5.d3  Ne7  6.Ng3  c5  Black is simply better as he can play on both wings while White is stuck with a bad bishop on f1. }
4... Be6 { An important move, preventing Bc4. } 5. Nf3 f6
{ Black solidifies the center. He wants to expand with ...c5, and then develop with ...Nc6, ...Bd6, and ...Nge7 when he would be able to play on both wings. }
6. Bb5+
{ Trying to disrupt Black's intended set-up. White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops since he must play d3 in order to finish development. }
6... c6
{ Winning a tempo. Now the queen's knight will go on a different route. } 7.
Ba4 Na6
{ This is the idea. The exchange of the bishops cannot be prevented, but Black can use the time White spends on Bb5-a4-b3 to reroute his knight to e6. Black now threatens ...Nc5, so White's next move is forced. }
8. Bb3 Nc5 9. Bxe6 Nxe6
{ The knight arrived at its destination. From e6, it controls the important f4-square. }
10. d3 Qd7
{ Black is better here. He wants to castle long and start attacking on the kingside by ...g6 @@StartBracket@@g5-g4@@EndBracket@@, ...h5-h4 and perhaps ...f5. A positional idea for Black is to exchange the dark-squared bishops by ...Bh6. }
