[White "Chapter 13: Various 1st Moves"]
[Black "Grob's Attack"]
[Result "*"]

1. g4
{ This is Grob's Attack, though I am somewhat bemused what attack they had in mind when they gave it that name. }
1... d5 { Black plays the usual first move and takes the center next. } 2. Bg2
{ In case of   2.h3  e5  3.Bg2  Nc6  @@StartBracket@@preventing d4@@EndBracket@@ Black develops with ...Be6, ...Qd7, and will undermine White's exposed kingside by ...h5 or ...f5. }
2... e5
{ Already Black has the visually more pleasing position. White's idea was to invite   2...Bxg4  3.c4  but even there he is much worse. Still, no need to go for those complications when Black can simply take over the center. }
3. d4
{ After   3.c4  dxc4  4.Qa4  c6  5.Qxc4  Be6  6.Qc3  Nd7  Black is developing fast with ...Bd6, ...Ngf6 or ...Ne7 and ...O-O and is ready to take over the initiative. After all, White played too many moves with the queen and weakened his kingside in the first 6 moves. }
3... exd4 { Again playing for quick development. } 4. Qxd4 Be6
{ Defending the pawn on d5 and threatening ...Nc6. } 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. Qa4 Bd6
{ Black develops in a very compact way. He will play ...Nge7 next @@StartBracket@@in order not to be attacked by g5 in case of ...Nf6@@EndBracket@@. }
7. Nc3 Ne7
{ Black finished development and will have to decide whether to castle short or long @@StartBracket@@after ...Qd7@@EndBracket@@. Both options are good and give him excellent play. }
