[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 13: Various 1st Moves"]
[Black "Sokolsky Opening"]
[Result "*"]

1. b4
{ The Sokolsky Opening may look like an advanced Nimzo-Larsen, but the fact that the pawn is not defended on b4 will force White to lose a tempo on either pushing it further or defending it. Note that  1.e3  will transpose elsewhere after  1...d5  whether that be theNimzo-Larsen after  2.b3   or theBird's Opening with  2.f4   or after  2.Nf3  Nf6  3.d4  c5  to the Colle/Zukertort.   Similarly  1.g3  d5  2.Bg2  Nf6  transposes to various openings: theReti if White chooses to play Nf3 and c4, or theKIA if he plays for the e4-push with Nf3 and Nbd2, or the Bird's Opening in case of  3.f4   or theCatalan in case of  3.d4  e6  4.c4 }
1... d5 2. Bb2 Nf6 3. e3 Bf5
{ Since White is not threatening anything on the queenside or in the center, Black can calmly get the bishop outside the pawn chain. }
4. Nf3 e6
{ Now the pawn on b4 hangs, so White can either push it or defend it with a3. }
5. a3
{ In case of  5.b5  Black continues with development with  5...Be7  6.Be2  h6  @@StartBracket@@avoiding Nh4 ideas@@EndBracket@@ followed by ...O-O and then he will undermine the exposed b5-pawn by ...a6. }
5... Be7 6. Be2 h6 { Securing the bishop and avoiding Nh4 ideas. } 7. O-O O-O
8. c4 c6
{ Black doesn't have any problems. He will finish development with ...Nbd7 and then have two ideas at his disposal: either to play for the ...e5-push with ...Bd6, ...Qe7/...Re8,  and eventually ...e5, or to undermine White's advanced queenside by ...a5 or ...c5. }
