{ @@StartBracket@@Candidates final 2007@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3.
Bf4 { Gata Kamsky is one of the world's best players of the London System. }
3... c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Bb5 { A rare move that Gelfand convincingly refutes. }
5... cxd4 6. exd4 Qa5+
{ Forcing the knight to c3, thus making White's pieces somewhat awkward. } 7.
Nc3 Bg4 8. O-O e6
{ Black developed the bishop outside the pawn chain and has easy development now.  This cannot be said for White, who would rather have a pawn on c3 for a regular Carlsbad structure.  The theory stopshere. }
9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Rc8
{ Black makes sure he will recapture with a rook on c6 in case White takes. In case White doesn't take, Black will have the rook on the semi-open c-file. }
11. Rfd1 Be7 12. Bf1 O-O 13. Ne2 b5
{ Black starts the typical minority attack. } 14. c3 b4
{ Black already established contact with White's structure on the queenside while White's counterplay on the other side of the board hasn't even started. It is clear that Black's opening strategy has triumphed. }
15. Qd3 Qb6 16. cxb4 Nxb4 17. Qb3 Ne4
{ Black plays actively, he intends either ...Nd6 or ...Bd6. } 18. a3 Nc6 19.
Qxb6 axb6
{ After the exchange of queens, the idea is to play ...Na5, targeting the weak light squares. }
20. b4 { White grabs space on the queenside, but weakens his pawn structure. }
20... g5
{ Black grabs space on the kingside, forcing White to determine the position of the bishop. }
21. Be3 Nd6 22. Nc1 f5 { Black is advancing on the whole board. } 23. Nb3 Nc4
24. b5 Nd8
{ Black doesn't play  24...N6a5  because he doesn't want to exchange the knight on b3, which is very short of squares. }
25. a4 Nb7 { This also stops the a5 advance. } 26. Bc1 f4 27. Be2 Bb4 28. Ra2
Nbd6 { Black is systematically going forward. } 29. Bd3 Ra8 30. Kf1
{ A blunder, losing the pawn on  b5  in view of the pin on the a-file. It was better to play  30.Bd2  though after the exchanges on d2, Black can play ...Rfc8, controlling the c-file and still keeping the pressure. }
30... Nxb5 31. Rc2 Nbd6
{ Black won a pawn for nothing and the rest is a matter of technique. } 32. Bd2
{ White gives away a second pawn, but this doesn't help much. } 32... Rxa4 33.
Bxb4 Rxb4 34. Nc1 Nf5 35. Bxf5 Rxf5 36. Nd3 Rb3 37. Ra2 Rf7 38. Ke2 Nd6 39.
Rda1 Nb5 40. Kd2 Nxd4
{ Winning a third pawn. The remaining moves are a straight-forward conversion. }
41. Rc1 Rb5 42. Rc8+ Rf8 43. Rc7 Ra5 44. Rb2 Rf7 45. Rc8+ Kg7 46. Ne5 Rb7 47.
h4 gxh4 48. Rb4 Ra2+ 49. Kd3 Nf5 50. Rxf4 Rba7 51. Rc3 R7a3 52. Rxa3 Rxa3+ 53.
Ke2 b5 54. Rg4+ Kf6 55. Nd3 Ra8 56. Kd2 e5 57. Rb4 e4 58. Nc5 Rg8 *

