Nf3 Nf6 3. e3 c5 4. c4 cxd4 5. exd4 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bc4 Nxc3 9.
bxc3 Qc7 10. Qb3 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 12. Be2 Be6 13. Qa3 Rac8 14. Rb1 Rfd8 15. Be3
Na5
{ In the theoretical section, we concluded that Black is better here. Now we can observe Anand's conversion.  Please check out the theoryhere. }
16. Rfc1 Nc4
{ Black's advantage consists of the absolute control over the light-squares in front of the White pawns on c3 and d4. With this move, Black sacrifices a pawn to exchange White's most valuable piece, the light-squared bishop, and to obtain the pair of bishops. }
17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxa7 Bd5 { The bishop is a monster on d5. } 19. Qb6 Bxa2
{ Black regains the pawn and keeps all the advantages of his position. } 20.
Qxc7 Rxc7 21. Rb6 Rdc8
{ It is always the backward pawn that is attacked. White is forced to defend passively. }
22. Bd2 Bd5 23. Ne5 e6 { Cementing the light-square domination. } 24. f3 Ra8
{ Black activates all his pieces. } 25. Nd3 Ra2 26. Rb2 Ra3
{ Black's rooks are the more active ones, so Black avoids the exchange. } 27.
Nc5 e5 { Undermining White's central structure. } 28. Rb4
{ After this, everything falls apart. It was better to play  28.Be3  but White's task is far from enviable. }
28... exd4 29. cxd4 b6 30. Re1
{ After  30.Nd3  Rxc1  31.Nxc1  b5  Black's passed pawn supported by the bishops will decide the game. }
30... f5 { Taking away the e4-square from the knight. } 31. Bf4 Rca7 32. Bd6
{ After  32.Ne6  Ra1  Black wins the hapless knight. } 32... bxc5 33. Bxc5 Ra1
