1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Qc2 c6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. h3 O-O 8. Bf4
g6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Nd2 Nbd7 12. g4 Be6 13. Bd3 Qxb3 14. Nxb3 a5
{ Black wants to advance on the queenside, where he has the pawn majority. In a way, we have reversed plans in this Carlsbad structure - instead of the minority attack, White took some space on the kingside, so Black advances on the queenside. The theory concludedhere but Kramnik-Giri continued... }
15. Nd2 a4 16. a3 b5
{ Black fixed the light squares on the queenside and now plans ...Nb6-c4. He also keeps the option to open the game on the queenside by ...b4. }
17. f3 Nb6 18. Ke2 Ra7
{ Black plans to open the game with ...b4 and prepares with the doubling on the a-file, so he can then push ...a3 and penetrate White's position via the open a-file. }
19. Bc2 Rfa8 20. Rhc1
{ It's clear that White has been driven on the defensive. } 20... b4 21. axb4
Bxb4 22. Bd3 Nc4 23. Bxc4 dxc4
{ Black obtained the pair of bishops but worsened his pawn structure, making the position double-edged. }
24. e4 a3 25. bxa3 Rxa3 26. Rxa3 Rxa3 27. Ndb1
{ Thanks to the strong blockade on c3, White doesn't run any risks here, but neither does Black. }
27... Rb3 28. Bh6 Ne8
{ Black prepares the ...f5 break, to attack White's central pawn mass. } 29.
Rc2 f5 30. Bd2 fxe4 31. fxe4 h5
{ After a series of pawn breaks, @@StartBracket@@20...b4, 24...a3, 29...f5, 31...h5@@EndBracket@@ White's structure finally collapses and Black wins a pawn. Still, White's concentration of forces in the center should give him good compensation. }
32. Ra2 { A natural way to activate the rook but it doesn't suffice. } 32...
hxg4 33. hxg4 Bxg4+ 34. Ke3 Bf8
{ The move  34...g5  would have stopped the king march, but Black should still be winning even after it. }
35. Kf4 { A brave attempt to attack with the king ahead! } 35... Be6 36. Kg5
Kf7 37. Kh4 Nd6 38. Ra7+ Rb7 39. Ra6 Nb5 40. d5 cxd5 41. exd5 Bf5 42. Nxb5 Be7+
{ The simple  42...Rxb5  would have been winning for Black. } 43. Bg5 Bxg5+ 44.
Kxg5 Rxb5 45. Ra7+ Ke8 46. Nc3
{ With the cut-off king and White's active pieces, Black cannot win anymore. }
46... Rb3 47. Ne2 Rb2 48. Nf4 c3 49. Rc7
{ This being a rapid game, it is very likely that the players were playing on their last seconds by here, so the mistakes are understandable. The natural  49.Ne6  would have drawn. }
49... c2 { Now Black is winning again. } 50. Nxg6 Kd8
{ Moving the bishop with  50...Be4  followed by ...Rb1, would have won a full rook for Black. }
51. d6 { Now it's a draw again. } 51... Bxg6 52. Kxg6 Rb6 53. Rxc2 Rxd6+ 54.
Kf5 *

