{ @@StartBracket@@Olympiad 1968@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4.
cxd5
{ In this version, with a knight already on f3, the Exchange Variation is harmless for Black as he can easily develop his bishop on f5. }
4... exd5 5. Nc3 c6 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Qc2 g6
{ This is the point, White has no time for e3 and Bd3 to stop the development of the bishop to f5. }
8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7
{ With the light-squared bishops exchanged, Black is easily equal. This game is a classical example on how to play for a win in the Carlsbad structure. }
11. Bh6 Ng4 { Chasing away the bishop and allowing Black to castle. } 12. Bf4
O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. h3 Ngf6 15. Ne5
{ White seeks exchanges and obviously plays for a draw. This is exactly what Black needs! The exchanges do not bring White closer to a draw, quite the contrary. With fewer pieces, it will be easier for Black to control White's queenside minority attack and start his own on the kingside. }
15... Nb6
{ The b6-square is a good square for the knight in the Carlsbad structure. The knight keeps an eye on the c4-square and is quick to be redeployed to the perfect square on d6. The theoretical section concludedhere. }
16. Bg5 Ne4
{ Forcing further exchanges and bringing the knight to the ideal d6-square. }
17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qc2
{ White cannot take twice on e4 because after ...f6, he will lose the knight on e5. }
18... Nd6
{ This is the ideal square for the knight. First, it controls the b5-square, making the minority attack more difficult to achieve. Second, the c4-square by making the b4-push undesirable, as it will forever weaken the c4-square. Third, the e4-square, from where it can be included in the attack on the kingside. Finally, the f5-square, where the Black knight is annoying to White because of various sacrifices on e3. It also defends the pawn on b7 in case a White knight appears on c5. }
19. Na4
{ More exchanges. But Black does it in the way he prefers it - he exchanges the knight on e5, not the one on a4! }
19... Nbc4 20. Nxc4 Nxc4 21. Nc5 Nd6
{ The position stabilized and both players have their knights where they want them. But looking at them, it's clear that the Black knight is the one controlling the situation as the knight on c5 is rather useless. There is no attack on b7 @@StartBracket@@safely defended by the knight on d6@@EndBracket@@ and no minority attack to support @@StartBracket@@this would weaken the c4-square@@EndBracket@@. On the other hand, the semi-open e-file gives Black more space and allows him to start a kingside attack by advancing his pawns there. This position and Black's subsequent play show why a simplified position in the Carlsbad structure is in Black's favor and how it should be played. }
22. Rac1
{ White remains passive until the end, so it's worth concentrating on Black's slow build-up of the attack. }
22... Qg5
{ Getting the queen more active. It was possible to start with a pawn storm immediately as well, but Petrosian is in no rush. }
23. Qd1 h5 { Preventing Qg4. } 24. Kh1 Re7
{ Allowing for a doubling on the e-file, but the rook can be effective on the 7th rank as well. The rook not only covers the b7-pawn, but can also use the g7- and h7- squares for a kingside attack. }
25. Nd3 Ne4
{ Black repeats the moves first, and then continues with his plan. } 26. Nc5
Nd6 27. Nd3 Qf5
{ A typical Petrosian move - he foresees Ne5-f3, attacking the queen on g5, so he moves her in due time. }
28. Ne5 f6 29. Nf3
{ The knight only gets in the way of the g-pawn here. White's plan is to put it on h2 to stop that advance, but as we will see, Black's attack cannot be stopped. The reason is that because of the pawn structure, White doesn't have good communication between the kingside/queenside and cannot bring the rook or the queen to the defense. }
29... Rg7 { Preparing ...g5-g4. } 30. Nh2 Re8 { Bringing in the last reserve. }
31. Kg1 Ne4
{ The knight no longer needs to guard b7 or c4 and is now actively deployed. }
32. Qf3
{ Of course, Black won't exchange queens, when the White queen will be subject to the attack of the g-pawn. }
32... Qe6 33. Rfd1 g5
{ The threat is ...g4, and with a bit of precise calculation, Petrosian controls the situation. He sees that the pawn on h5 is poisoned as taking it speeds up Black's attack by opening the h-file. }
34. Qxh5 { Taking the pawn, but White was lost anyway. } 34... f5
{ Again threatening ...g4 and cutting off the White queen. } 35. Re1
{ In case of  35.Qf3  Black would anyway have continued with  35...g4 } 35...
g4 36. hxg4 fxg4
{ Black's attack is overwhelming. The threats are numerous, ...Rg5 and ...Qg6, ...g3, ...Nxf2, and so on. }
37. f3
{ Opening more files against his own king, but the game is lost in all lines. }
37... gxf3 38. Nxf3 Rh7 { The queen is trapped. } 39. Qe5 Qc8 40. Qf4 Rf8 41.
Qe5 Rf5
{ A cute trap for the queen in the center of the board. An excellent demonstration of Black's potential in the simplified positions arising from the Carlsbad structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nikolic, Predrag vs. Kramnik, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@Amber blindfold rapid 1998@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6
3. Nf3 d5 4. Nc3 c6
{ The game starts as the Semi-Slav, but after White's next move, it transposes to the QGD Exchange Variation. }
5. cxd5
{ Transposing to the Exchange Variation with a knight on f3 is harmless. } 5...
exd5 6. Bg5 Be7 7. e3 Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rab1
{ White immediately starts the minority attack. } 11... a5
{ It is useful for Black to open the a-file after White manages to push b4, as that will activate the rook on a8. }
12. a3 Ne4
{ The typical simplifying maneuver is made possible because of the queen on d3. The capture   13.Nxe4  is bad because after  13...dxe4  The queen is attacked and White loses the bishop on g5. }
13. Bxe7 Qxe7
{ White still cannot take the knight on e4 and this allows Black to drop it back to the ideal square on d6. }
14. b4 b5
{ Since the knight will come to d6 and then one of the knights @@StartBracket@@the other one via b6@@EndBracket@@ will occupy the weakened c4-square, this is a good defense against the minority attack. With a knight on c4 and the c-file plugged, it will be impossible to take advantage of the backward pawn on c6. }
15. Qc2
{ Finally threatening to take on e4, but Black of course avoids this exchange. }
15... axb4 { Opening the a-file first. } 16. axb4 Nd6
{ The ideal square. The knight from here is spoilt for choice - c4, e4, and f5 are all tempting options! }
17. Rb3 Nb6
{ Black decides to send the d7-knight to c4, since the one on d6 can be used more effectively elsewhere. }
18. Ne5
{ This looks active, but this is only temporary as the knight can always be chased away by ...f6 if necessary. }
18... Rfc8 19. Nd3
{ White understands that the knight cannot stay on e5 for too long, so he moves it to c5. But as we saw in the model game, Bobotsov-Petrosian, the knight on c5 is rather useless. While it does control the e4-square, there is little else it does. In the meantime, Black slowly starts to build up the attack on the kingside. }
19... Nbc4 { The theory endedhere. } 20. Nc5 Re8
{ The rook returns to the semi-open e-file where it's most active. Unlike the game, Bobotsov-Petrosian, here we will witness an attack on White's kingside executed with pieces rather than a pawn storm. }
21. h3 g6 { Both sides create luft for their king. } 22. Rc1 Ra7
{ This doesn't necessesarily mean that Black wants to double on the a-file - it may also mean that he wants to double on the e-file by playing ...Rae7! }
23. Qd1 h5
{ Preventing Qg4 @@StartBracket@@exactly the same as in the game, Bobotsov-Petrosian!@@EndBracket@@ and grabbing more space on the kingside. If necessary, Black can fix the dark squares there by means of ...h4. }
24. Kh1 Qg5
{ The most active square for the queen. Slowly, we see that Black is piling up on the kingside and especially concentrating his forces on the e3-pawn! }
25. Rbb1 Rae7 26. Ra1 Nf5
{ Everything is ready. All of Black's pieces attack e3 and the pressure is unbearable. }
27. Ra2 Ncxe3
{ Of course. White's kingside is abandoned, @@StartBracket@@again, the reason being the character of the Carlsbad structure that makes it difficult for White to bring his forces to the kingside@@EndBracket@@ while all Black's pieces are ready to pounce. }
28. fxe3 Rxe3 29. Rf2 Qh4
{ An uncharacteristic lapse by Kramnik, but then again this was a blindfold game! After  29...Qg3  followed by ...Nh4, the game would have been over soon. }
30. Qd2 Nxd4 31. Rcf1
{ Nikolic returns the favor.  31.Kg1  was the only move when the position is rather unclear. }
31... Nf5
{ The knight threatens the deadly ...Ng3, and taking it doesn't help as then Black takes advantage of White's back rank. }
32. Rxf5 gxf5 33. Nd1 Re1 34. Kg1 R8e2 35. Qc3 Rxd1
{ In spite of the inaccuracy on move 29, this is a great example of how a piece attack against White's kingside should be executed in the Carlsbad structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grischuk, Alexander. vs. Aronian, Levon"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@WCh Candidates 2011@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Be7 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. Qc2 Nf6 7. e3 Nh5
{ This was the first high-level game where this ambitious treatment was introduced. Aronian's preparation uncovered the great dynamic potential in Black's position. }
8. Be5 Nd7 9. Be2 Nxe5
{ This is the point. Previously, Black played the tame  9...Nhf6 } 10. dxe5 g6
11. Bxh5 gxh5
{ Black obtained the pair of bishops, but doubled his h-pawns in return. Nevertheless, the dynamic potential of the bishops coupled with the mobile central majority gives Black excellent chances. }
12. O-O-O f6 13. Nf3 fxe5 14. Nxe5 O-O 15. f4 Bd6 16. Nf3 Bf5
{ In the theoretical section, we introduced the improvement  16...b5  but Aronian's move is also quite good.  The theory is presentedhere. }
17. Qd2 Qf6
{ It is even visually apparent that Black controls the position, as White doesn't have good squares for his knights. }
18. e4
{ Grischuk tries to change the character of the game, but the endgame is better for Black. Otherwise, Black would have simply started attack on the queenside by ...b5-b4, etc. }
18... dxe4 19. Qxd6 exf3 20. Qxf6 Rxf6 21. gxf3 Bg6
{ The bishop is stronger than the knight in this open position, White's f-pawns are hopelessly weak and Black has a clear pawn majority on the queenside. These factors make the position, if not technically winning, then at least much better for Black. }
22. Ne2 { This is too passive, it was better to play  22.Rd4 } 22... Re8 23.
Rd2 Re3
{ Black didn't waste time to penetrate White's position and pin White down to the defense of the weak f-pawns. }
24. Rf1 Bd3 25. Rf2 Kf7
{ White is completely paralyzed and Black is indeed winning here. } 26. b3 h4
27. Kb2 Bxe2 { Winning a pawn. } 28. Rdxe2 Rxe2+ 29. Rxe2 Rxf4 30. Rf2 Rd4
{ It was also possible first to improve with ...a5, ...Ke6, etc. } 31. Kc3 Rd1
32. f4 Kf6 33. Rg2 h5 { The move  33...Rh1  was very strong. } 34. a4 Rf1 35.
Rg5 Rf3+ 36. Kc2 Rxf4 37. Rxh5 Rf2+ 38. Kc3 Rxh2
{ Black is two pawns up and is clearly winning. } 39. Rh7 Kg6 40. Rxb7
{ Getting one pawn back, but now the h-pawn gets to h2 without the rook being trapped on h1. }
40... h3 41. Rb8 Rf2 42. Rh8 h2 43. Kd3 Kg5
{ Black's plan is simple - get the king to g2 and promote. } 44. Ke3 Rb2
{ White managed to prevent the Black king from coming to g2, but he had to abandon his queenside for that. }
45. Kf3 Rxb3+ 46. Kg2 Rb2+ 47. Kh1 Kf5 { Now the c-pawn runs. } 48. Rc8 Rc2 49.
Ra8 Ke4 50. Rxa7 Ra2 51. a5 Kd4 52. a6 Kc5
{ The immediate  52...c5  was also possible. } 53. Ra8 Kc4 54. Ra7 c5 55. Ra8
Kb5 56. Rb8+ Kc6 57. Rc8+ Kb6 58. Rb8+ Kc7 59. Rb7+ Kc6 60. Ra7 c4 61. Ra8 Kc7
62. a7 c3 { The c-pawn will cost White a full rook. } 63. Re8 Rxa7 64. Kxh2 Kb6
65. Kg3 Kc5 66. Kf2 Kc4 67. Ke2 Kb3 68. Rc8 Kb2 69. Rb8+ Kc1 70. Kd3 c2 71. Rh8
Ra3+ 72. Kc4 Kb1 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Salem, AR Saleh vs. Kramnik, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@Qatar Masters 2014@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
d5 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 c5 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7
Nxe7 11. Be2 b6 12. O-O Bb7 { The theoretical section endedhere. } 13. dxc5
Nxc5
{ Black achieved complete equality from the opening. It is instructive to follow how Kramnik manages to keep the position unbalanced enough so that the game continues. }
14. Nd4 Nf5
{ The first moment. After the exchange on f5, the pawn structure isn't completely symmetrical. The pawn on f5 gives Black extra control over the e4-square. }
15. Nxf5 exf5 16. Bf3
{ White is playing for a draw by trying to exchange as many pieces as possible. This doesn't spoil anything and it's a valid strategy, as long as White is careful and doesn't get carried away with the exchanges. }
16... Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rfd8 { Fighting for the open file. } 19. Kf1
g6
{ Defending the f5-pawn and planning ...Kg7-f6. The pawn on f5 gives Black some space advantage on the kingside. While this doesn't account for much, it is still something little to play with. }
20. Ke2 Kg7 21. Nb5
{ White centralized the king and now seeks further exchanges. } 21... Kf6 22.
Rxd8
{ The move  22.a3  would have created the threat to take on d8 and then on a7, as the a2-pawn wouldn't hang after ...Ra8, but White goes for more direct exchanges. }
22... Rxd8 23. b4 Ne6 24. Rc6
{ White is active and he's doing quite alright. The game still goes on though. }
24... Ke7 25. a3 Rd7
{ White threatened to take on a7 and then return to b5, defending the a3-pawn, so Black defends a7. }
26. Rc8 a6 { Black pushes back the active knight on b5. } 27. Nc3 b5 28. Ra8
Rd6
{ The rook defends the only weakness, the pawn on a6, and at the same time, doesn't allow the White knight to come to d5. }
29. Rh8
{ A move that shows that White has run out of ideas.  29.a4  had more sense, to reduce the material on the queenside. }
29... g5
{ The pawn on  h6  is now indirectly defended, but it was also possible to start with  29...Rc6 }
30. Ra8 Kf6 31. Ra7
{ White continues to senselessly move around with the rook. This is the turning phase of the game. Instead of continuing in the same manner and purposefully play for a draw, like for example with 30.a4, White suddenly stopped and started doing nothing. This allows Kramnik to start to play for more. As Carlsen once said, paraphrasing, if my opponent doesn't play for a win, there must be a way that I can start to play for a win. }
31... Kg6 32. Na2
{ After losing time with the rook, White comes up with a constructive idea again - to bring the knight to b3. But then again, inexplicably, he breaks his rhythm with his next move. }
32... Nd8 { Preparing the next move by defending the pawn on f7. } 33. Ke1
{ A move difficult to explain, again reverting to the 'do nothing' like the senseless rook maneuvers. There was nothing wrong with  33.Nc1 }
33... Kh5
{ Kramnik must have remembered the classical game, Cohn-Rubinstein, from St. Petersburg 1909 where the great Akiba won the pawn endgame by getting his king to h3 against exactly the same white pawn structure on the kingside. }
34. Nc1 Kh4 35. Nb3
{ The final mistake. The knight had to change the direction and go to  e2  , though still after  35.Ne2  Kh3  36.f4  Kxh2  37.Ng3  gxf4  38.exf4  h5  Black still has good winning chances. }
35... Kh3 { Now White has nothing to show for the loss of the h-pawn. } 36. Nd4
f4
{ Of course, not only saving the pawn, but also undermining the knight on d4. }
37. Ra8 Kxh2 { First  37...h5  was more precise, but this is good enough. } 38.
Nf5 Rf6 39. e4
{ Leaving Black with a passed h-pawn is hopeless. It was better to take it,  39.Nxh6  Rxh6  40.Rxd8  though after  40...Kg2  Black continues to have excellent winning chances. }
39... Nc6 40. Rxa6 Rg6
{ Unpinning the knight by putting the rook on a defended square. } 41. Kf1 Ne5
{ The pawn on f3 is also weak. } 42. Ra5 Nxf3 43. Rxb5 g4
{ Black's pawn mass on the kingside is quick and decides the game. } 44. Rd5 h5
45. Ng3 h4
{ It would have been too much to expect for Kramnik to blunder mate after  45...fxg3  46.Rxh5  The rest is easy. }
46. Ne2 g3 47. fxg3 fxg3 48. b5 Rf6 49. Rf5 Rxf5 50. exf5 g2+ 51. Kf2 Nd4 52.
Ng1 Nxb5 53. a4 Nc3 54. Nf3+ Kh1 55. a5 h3
{ A game that shows how playing on in an equal position for a long time can suddenly bring unexpected winning opportunities. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Korchnoi, Viktor Lvovich vs. Karpov, Anatoly"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@1981 World Championship Game 9@@EndBracket@@ } 1. c4 e6 2.
Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. Rc1 dxc4 8. e3 c5 9. Bxc4
cxd4 10. exd4
{ The more ambitious move, playing with an IQP and banking on activity. The capture with a knight would have been safer, as discussed in the theoretical chapterhere. }
10... Nc6 11. O-O Nh5
{ An important idea! This forces the exchange of bishops while at the same time preventing Bg3, as then after ...Nxg3, Black would obtain the pair of bishops. }
12. Bxe7 Nxe7 { Another important move - control over d5 is vital. } 13. Bb3
{ White could have played  13.d5  and exchanged the IQP with an equal position, but if he wanted an equal position, he wouldn't have taken with a pawn on move 10! }
13... Nf6
{ The knight returns and Black establishes firm control over d5. White should still have enough activity for equality, but this puts more pressure on him because if he fails to achieve it, Black would be in a strategically dominant position with a safe blockade of the IQP. }
14. Ne5 Bd7 { The bishop goes to c6. } 15. Qe2
{ White could still play  15.d5  and liquidate to a draw, but he persists. }
15... Rc8 { Black finishes development. } 16. Ne4
{ White must have miscalculated something as this simply leads to a worse position for him. It was still ok for White after something like   16.Rcd1  and Rfe1. }
16... Nxe4 17. Qxe4 Bc6 18. Nxc6 Rxc6
{ The simplifications have favored Black as he got rid of his passive bishop and White's active knight. White does have a good bishop on b3, but lack of active ideas make his position the more difficult one to play. Black, on the other hand, has the simple plan to start attacking the pawn on d4. }
19. Rc3 Qd6 20. g3 Rd8 21. Rd1 Rb6
{ Moving the rook so as to allow for ...Qd7 @@StartBracket@@this was now impossible in view of the pin Ba4@@EndBracket@@ and ...Rd6. }
22. Qe1 Qd7 { Black is using all his pieces to attack the pawn on d4. } 23.
Rcd3 Rd6
{ White is completely passive, but it's not so easy to further improve Black's position. }
24. Qe4
{ The move  24.d5  would have been an interesting practical choice. Sacrificing the pawn immediately would have allowed for an easy blockade of the d5-pawn and more freedom of movement. }
24... Qc6 25. Qf4 Nd5 26. Qd2 Qb6 27. Bxd5
{ The transition to a purely heavy-piece position is unfavorable for White as the light-squared bishop was controlling the d5-square, while now that square belongs entirely to Black. With a triple attack on d4, he will now try to push ...e5 and win the IQP. It was much more resilient for White to mark time with  27.Qe2  for example, and see what Black will do. }
27... Rxd5 28. Rb3 Qc6 29. Qc3 Qd7
{ The threat is to push ...e5, but White's next move is bad as it fatally weakens White's king. }
30. f4
{ It was better to just abandon the d4-pawn and play a pawn down, but with a safe king. Now, sooner or later, the weakness of the White king will tell. }
30... b6 { The pawn is defended here so Black threatens to take on d4. } 31.
Rb4 b5 { Limiting the movement of the White rook. } 32. a4
{ White tries to get more squares for the rook on the 4th rank. } 32... bxa4
33. Qa3 a5 34. Rxa4 Qb5
{ The first problems with the king start to appear. The threat is ...Qe2. } 35.
Rd2 e5
{ In spite of White's efforts to prevent it, this move finally opens the position and the ultimate victim is the weakened White king. }
36. fxe5 Rxe5 37. Qa1
{ This speeds up the end in view of Black's next move, but White's lost anyway. In positions with queens and rooks, king safety is by far the most important factor, and here White's king cannot be defended. }
37... Qe8 38. dxe5 Rxd2 { Threatening ...Qc6 or ...Qxe5. } 39. Rxa5 Qc6 40.
Ra8+ Kh7 41. Qb1+ g6 42. Qf1 Qc5+ 43. Kh1 Qd5+
{ And with ...Rd1 next to come, Black wins the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Grischuk, Alexander vs. Caruana, Fabiano"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@Khanty-Mansiysk FIDE GP 2015@@EndBracket@@ } 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4
d5 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bf4 O-O 7. e3 Nbd7 8. g4 dxc4 9. Bxc4 Nb6
10. Bb3 Nfd5 11. Bg3 c5 12. Ne5
{ In the theoretical chapter we take a look at the more dangerous  12.h4  Grischuk's move allows Black to create a weak pawn on c3. For the theoretical section, please clickhere. }
12... cxd4 13. Qxd4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5
{ Here the move  14...Bd7  with the idea of ...Rc8 was more precise. } 15. O-O
Qa5 { Black has a clear plan of play against the pawn on c3. } 16. Rac1 Rd8 17.
Rfd1
{ White had to start his kingside play with  17.h4  because otherwise he doesn't have compensation for his queenside weaknesses. }
17... Bd7
{ A very good pawn sacrifice. In the endgame, Black will obtain the pair of bishops and free play against White's queenside. }
18. Bxd5 exd5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Rxd5 Be6
{ Black's compensation is excellent, the bishops are pointed towards White's weak queenside. }
21. Rb5 Ba3 22. Ra1 b6 23. c4
{ This pawn is soon lost. It was better to defend the one on  g4  first by  23.h3  but it's clear that Black is the one with the big advantage here. }
23... f6 24. Rb3 Bf8 25. Nc6 Rdc8 26. Nd4 Bxc4
{ It was better to take on g4 as that would leave the weak pawn on c4 alive, forcing White to defend it. }
27. Rbb1 Bd5 28. a4
{ White defends well, he exchanges the lone a-pawn and attempts to establish a blockade on b5. }
28... Rc4 29. a5 Bc5 30. axb6 axb6 31. Rxa8+ Bxa8 32. h3 Be4 33. Rd1 Bxd4
{ Eliminating the centralized knight. White has great drawing chances now thanks to the opposite-colored bishops, but Black is still pressing since his b-pawn is more dangerous than White's d-pawn. }
34. exd4 b5 35. Kh2 b4 36. d5 Bc2 37. Ra1 b3 38. Ra8+ Kh7 39. Rb8 Rd4 40. d6
Rd1 41. Kg2 Rd3 42. Rb6 Bd1 43. f4
{ This exposes White's pawns. There was nothing wrong with the neutral  43.Bf4 }
43... h5 44. g5 Kg6 45. Bh4 Kf5 46. gxf6 gxf6 47. Rb5+ Ke4 48. Bxf6 Rxd6 49.
Be5 Rd3 { Black still keeps pushing, though the position is a draw. } 50. Rb4+
Kf5 51. Rb5 h4 52. Bh8+ Ke4 53. f5
{ White ignores the threats against his own king. After  53.Bf6  attacking the pawn on h4, he would have been safe. }
53... Ke3
{ Threatening a mate after ...Bf3 and ...Rd1-h1. Black is winning now. } 54.
Re5+ Kf4 55. Rb5 Rd2+ 56. Kg1 Kg3 57. Rb4 Bc2 58. Be5+ Kxh3 59. f6 Rg2+ 60. Kf1
Rg5
{ Probably with little time left, Caruana misses  60....Bd3  followed by ...Re2-e5, winning the bishop. }
61. Bd4 { Now it's a draw again. } 61... Kh2 62. Bb6 h3 63. Bc7+ Kh1 64. Rh4
Bd3+ 65. Kf2 Rg2+ 66. Ke3 b2 67. Rb4 Bg6 68. Be5 h2 69. f7 Bxf7 70. Bxb2 Rg5
71. Kf2 Bd5 72. Bd4 Rg2+ 73. Kf1 Rc2
{ Black threatens ...Bc4, but White needed to know that the position after the exchange sacrifice is a draw. }
74. Rb6
{ This loses on the spot.  74.Ba7  Bc4+  75.Rxc4  Rxc4  76.Kf2  is a draw as the Black king cannot escape the corner, for example...  76...Rf4+  77.Kg3  77...Rb4  78.Bc5 }
74... Bc4+ 75. Ke1 Kg2 *

