[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Matlakov, Maxim vs. Kramnik, Vladimir"]
[Result "*"]

{ @@StartBracket@@Qatar Masters 2015@@EndBracket@@ } 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3
d5 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 O-O 7. e3 Nbd7 8. Rc1 c5 9. dxc5 dxc4 10. Bxc4
Nxc5 11. O-O a6 12. Nd4 Nfe4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Qc2 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Na4 16. Qc2
Bd7
{ The theoretical section endedhere. The position is undoubtedly equal, but that doesn't mean that a draw is a foregone conclusion. In fact, Kramnik goes on to outplay a very strong grandmaster at a classical time-control game, showing that these symmetrical positions can be played out and mistakes will inevitably happen. }
17. b3 Nb6 18. Be2
{ Of course, Black would have taken on c4 as the bishop would have more prospects than the knight. }
18... Rac8 19. Qe4 Nd5 20. Bd3 f5
{ Black defends against mate and takes space. His pawns on light squares limit the opponent's bishop. }
21. Qe5 Nc3 { Threatening ... Rc5. } 22. Nc6
{ White forces more simplifications. } 22... Rxc6 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Qxc3 Rc8
25. Qd2 Rd8
{ Black's bishop will come out to c6, and surprisingly it will be better than White's despite having almost all of his pawns on the light squares. The reason for this is that Black's bishop will be active on the long diagonal, and nothing is obstructing it there, while White's bishop cannot find a good spot. }
26. Qe2 Bc6 27. a4 Qg5 { Provoking a weakening of White's kingside. } 28. f3
Rd6 29. Rd1 { White prepares to oppose Black on the open d-file. } 29... Kf7
{ Black centralizes the king. The position is objectively equal, but the game goes on and as long as that is the case, mistakes can happen. }
30. Bc2 Rxd1+ 31. Bxd1 f4 32. exf4 Qxf4
{ Theoretically speaking, Black worsened his structure, but the isolated e-pawn is easy to defend and it provides a good protection for the king in the center. }
33. Qd3 Qe5 34. h3 Ke7 35. Bc2 Qc5+ 36. Kh1
{ Now White's king is farther away from the center. } 36... a5
{ Black fixes White's queenside pawns on light squares. It's interesting to observe how Black transformed the position. It is now White who has his pawns on the same color as his bishop. }
37. Qd2 Qe5 38. Bd3 Qa1+ 39. Kh2 Qd4 40. Qc2 Kd6
{ Black goes forward, though it's mostly a visual advance. } 41. Bc4 Be8 42.
Kh1 h5 43. Qc1 Bd7 44. Qa3+ Kc7 45. Qc1 Kd6 46. Qa3+ Kc7 47. Qc1 Kb6 48. Qc2 h4
{ Fixing the pawn on g2. Black can maneuver behind the powerful queen on d4 and now with White's pawns fixed on light squares, all bishop endgames are easily winning for Black. }
49. Bd3 Bc6 50. Be4
{ Naturally, White seeks an exchange of bishops and not of queens. } 50... Bd5
{ Black doesn't mind, as long as he obtains a passed pawn on the d-file. } 51.
Kh2 Qe3 52. Bxd5
{ Definitely a concession. It was better to play  52.Qb2  attacking the pawn on g7. }
52... Qe5+ 53. Kh1 { The king needed to rush towards the center with  53.Kg1 }
53... exd5
{ Now Black is practically a pawn up as White cannot create a passed pawn on the kingside. Black can later advance with all of his pieces. }
54. Qc8 Qe1+ 55. Kh2 Qe5+ 56. Kh1 Qd6 57. Qe8 Kc5
{ In queen endgames, a common theme is the king marching forwards under the protection of the queen. Here, Black also has a strong passed pawn. }
58. Qb5+
{ This lets the Black king go forward. It was necessary to play  58.Qe1  so that White can give checks from the front. }
58... Kd4 { Now Black is winning. } 59. Qxa5 Kd3
{ The pawn deficit is irrelevant, as the passed pawn aided by the king secures the win. }
60. Qb5+ Kc3 61. Qa5+ Kc2 62. Qe1 d4 63. Qe2+ Kxb3 64. Qd1+ Kb4 65. Qb1+ Kxa4
{ The king even managed to eliminate all of White's queenside pawns. } 66. Qxb7
d3 { The pawn is unstoppable. } 67. Qb2 d2 68. Qa2+ Kb5 69. Qb2+ Qb4 70. Qc2
Qd4 71. Qb3+ Kc5 72. Qc2+ Kb4 73. Qd1 Qb2
{ Great example by Kramnik on how to outplay strong opponents from an equal position. }
